text:
For the high cost of a nice environment, here you get cramped tables, uncomfortable stool chairs, and the usual River Valley crowds.  It's yet another place for coffee snobs than for a nice casual and affordable breakfast or brunch.

I'll take simple and affordable any day over high-end looks and coffee. Like Italian food, breakfast does not need to be expensive. Any diner in the US does it better, cheaper, friendlier, faster, and with more options, than anywhere I've seen in Singapore. 

They do have good service and good quality eggs.  The saltiness and olive oil on the eggs killed the taste for me, to where I struggled to eat them; our waitress dismissed my dissatisfaction as they being "healthy" that way. A Big No for future patronage.

French toast was a bit small for $18.

Warning: For those who don't like added oil on your eggs, be sure to specify without; 

I see it like pepper - don't put it on people's food unless you ask them first, mention it on the menu, and better yet, rather than serve it with, have it on the table for the customer to do for themselves. 

I originally gave it a high three stars for the overall quality of ingredients and atmosphere, but revised it to two (because there is no 2.5 option) as in reality, we have not been back since this visit months ago in favour of other places, and are not likely to return except out of boredom of our regular brunch places.

Lovely hole-in-the-wall coffee place which has a nice ambience and indie feel to it. Yes, the seats are limited inside but who's stopping you from buying a cuppa coffee and sitting on some of the benches outside. Grab pastries from the nearby bakery whilst you're at it.

Coffee is good. Especially when paired with their pastries and other goodies.

I found my sweet tooth here. Do not go pass the Kouign Amann or the Almond croissant. Sandwiches are good but its their Danish that gets me coming back.

Best fruit tarts in town, hands down. Pastry chef Alfred Chan once baked in the kitchens of Shangri-La, but prefers baking in the heartlands where he has the opportunity to interact with his customers. His years of expertise has made him a master in desserts, which led to the opening of Drips, a quaint cafe in the charming Tiong Bahru neighbourhood, to the benefit of us mortals who can't afford to dine at Shangri-La. 

I am a big desserts fans (a girl always has stomach for sweets!), and fruit tarts are easily one of my most favourite form of after meal delights. I've always been a ice cream or cake kind of girl, until I discovered the fruit tarts at Drips. Sweet pastry shells are filled with delicious custard, then generously stacked with fresh fruits (the strawberries on their tarts are the biggest I've seen in Singapore). I don't think my words will do the tastiness of these tarts justice. All I can say is, you don't know fruit tarts until you've tried the ones at Drips. These precious tarts tend to run out quickly so I wish you all the best in coming at the right time. 

The reason why I gave Drips four stars is because their mains are rather mediocre. I would suggest that you enjoy a cheap and hearty meal at Tiong Bahru market a few minutes' walk away before coming here for dessert.

We all have a favorite beach, but what about a favorite beachside cafe? Coastes is a great one in Singapore. 

You're paying quite a bit for a nice view/location, but the food is standard, the service is great and, again, you're on the beach. 

In the end, I would say that Coastes is a perfect spot for enjoying a cold and refreshing drink overlooking the water but I would avoid their brunch and please, don't look forward to a really good meal if you're a foodie (are you?).

text:
I know you must be thinking, who doesn't know about Starbucks. But what's special about this Starbucks is its location. Most branches are situated in crowded or popular areas like shopping malls or famed shopping streets like Orchard Road or Bugis Street. Not this one. The outlet is hidden in an office building at Buona Vista, which means that its usually quite empty on a weekday morning or afternoon. 

It is extremely accessible, just a short walk away from a few bus stops and the soon-to-come One North MRT station on the circle line. Do take note that it is also near to several schools like ACJC and Fairfield Secondary School, and may oget a little packed after school hours or during examination periods. If you plan to visit on a weekend, come early to secure a good seat, especially if you need a powerpoint. 

It is one of the perfect spots to spend a quiet day alone regardless if it is to read a book, write, study or just watch the world go by. The staff is also extremely friendly and willing to go the extra mile to make your day. I've seen on various accounts whereby staff members ask around for those willing to share a seat to help other customers that are looking for a seat to enjoy their beverage or food. Customer requests are also taken seriously, like heating up a muffin for only 5 seconds. These little acts are an excellent show of professional service levels, another reason why I keep coming back.

text:
This review is long overdue. Wanted to rave about one of my favourite places in Orchard Road, but just didn't get to do it till now (excuses I know hahahahah). 

So, here's the story. Celebrated my birthday at this cafe in May this year with my gal friends. 4 of us ordered a few mains and a dessert to share. I gotta say we were all very happy with the food. I especially love the 2 main dishes: Fuwa Fuwa Hoshino Soufflé with Porcini Rissoto Tomato Cream and Omu Rice with Shrimp & Mozarella. Just writing about them and looking at their yelp pictures are making me hungry now. 

Their dessert item, Double Pancake Soufflé Style is also recommended. It is so big I am sure it can feed 8 instead of the 4 of us. Love the service here! Definitely one of the few places in SG where you can enjoy good and cheery service at a mid-priced eatery. Good service is just super hard to find in SG #sadfactoflife.

I have been coming to this cafe chain over the years. My favourite outlet is still this Plaza Singapura one. After writing this review, I have the urge to visit it soon. Think I gotta make it real soon. #whydoeswritingreviewsmakeonehungry?

text:
I ventured on my own on a Sunday and got here after a brutal walk in the scorching heat and humidity. That is my only con about Singapore; the heat! I was very anxious and eager to try these macarons becaus supposedly they are the best. 

After my $60 purchase and taking all sorts of pictures of the box, bag, and the store's selections, and my purchase... I can say w/ confidence that these ARE the best I have ever had. The macarons are incredibly light, airy and the filling is smooth, rich, and decadent. I ordered 15. I finished it in 2 days. I had the chocolate, coffee, and salted caramel. 

The girl behind the counter was very patient w/ me, super soft-spoken, and welcoming. I did not intend to buy that many but how often am I going to be in Singapore?! Plus my GM said I can expense my chocolate/dessert purchases. What? I have the best job, the best manager, the best customer, and the best team. 

I did many hours of cardio for these. It was so worth it!!

text:
Came here in mid-morning for some famous rectangular dan ta, after a morning of exploring Chinatown nearby.

The cashier lady was an older obasan who was extremely patient and kind with us as we scoured the display window for a avoid-the-sun snack. We decided on dan ta's each, their powdered bread...which I totally forgot the name! The baked goods weren't spectacular, but that's because we're spoiled with delicious California baked goods and cheap/fresh Taiwanese bakery bread when we travel.

Their dan ta has a crunchier and thinner (not flaky) crust and sweeter egg in the center. It was pretty good, just made differently and just as fresh. Their powdered bread was not the business. We felt like it was just bread with powdered sugar on top...nothing special. Looking around, we saw that they also offered other baked sweets as well as more "kitchen-made" orders like soups and porridges. 

It's great to get a dan ta if you're in the Ann Siang Hill/Chinatown area, but it's not some place I would say is a "distinguishing" part of Singaporean local eats.

text:
I had a hair service at the Walking On Sunshine salon. After 3 hours later (yes!! It was that many hours. The vanity just got the best of me :( )

When I finally got out and joined my sister for lunch at the café, I sat down and flipped through the menu. Before I texted my sis before to go ahead and order first. A bespectacled server came to me, demanded rudely that if I was not planning to eat anything, I must put on a mask. Was she kidding?? Why must she be so rude?? 

I countered back "Yea!! I am eating!!" 

During Phase 2 after the "Circuit Breaker" (aka shelter in place", everyone in Singapore still needs to wear a mask when they are out and about. People can now dine in restaurants with social distancing procedures in place. 

Back to that server, why must she used that kind of tone to talk to me, a customer?? Ugh.. again I have to say this.. is it that hard to be polite to paying customers (Reminded me of that rude server at TCC restaurant @ Marina Bay Sands last year) ? Where was her service or manners?? She should simply say this:   "Hi there! Sorry, if you do not plan to be eating, would you please put on your mask? Thank you for your understanding!"

It is NOT that hard!!!!! 

My sister just asked me to eat whatever she ordered which were already served at the table. I may not kick a big fuss there, I surely not going to let this slide. I would throw hands the next time I visit there. I really wanted to try the soufflé pancake!

My mood was ruined but I had to say the seafood pancake was really good! There was also this basket of korean chickens which was not bad either. The ginseng ade was really good!

Ambience here is definitely 5 stars. Service was a 0 (the owner should thank their rude staff). I would give the food a 4.

Will come back and update after I return for their soufflé pancake.

text:
Delicious pastry..
I have tried many different bakeries and out of all the locations, this is the BEST.

I can't remember the names of the pastries I ate but I have photos..  These are the most popular and best selling items in the store.  Crispy outside and so soft inside...

Also, their coffee is so good..  This is not normal coffee..  Just to give you an idea, Starbucks coffee level 3, coffee from here is level 8.  Coffees are specially brewed by barista to perfection.  It takes time to receive the order but worth it.

I also ordered Ice Chocolate glass bottle drink because I love the bottle...  Not only the bottle looks pretty, taste is even better.  Very deep rich taste.  Employee told me these are made and prepared daily.  Very good but expensive compare to other items..  

Next time, I should try their fresh juice...

The espresso here is top notch, one of the best in town for sure. Waffle ice cream dish was good as well although I'm not a fan but it's a 10 min prep. Honestly i wish I ordered the hot cake variety as they peak my interest. It's a 40 min wait. Next time come with people with patience...
Venue typical Instagram hipster joint. Nice vibe.

text:
I love coming to this street - though it can be a little bit commercial at times - with all the tourists, etc., but the standard of the food is still pretty authentic. There are quite a few options, when you dine in the evening, it's pretty cool and airy, and you get all the staples of Singaporean food fare. The MRT station is just nearby - so it's pretty easy to get to.

What I Love: The options for food here is great - I love the Drinks & Desserts stall, the Fried Hokkien Mee, Char Kway Teow, Orh Luah and Ah Balling are yummy to the max. From the Drinks & Desserts stall, I would recommend the Coconut Juice, Water Chestnut Drink & Ice Kacang. The other Desserts are yummy too - but I always have the Ice Kacang there. There is a Seafood Stall that's really famous at the end of the street - it sells Ikan Bakar, Deep Fried Baby Squid, and quite a few other local delicacies. The City Satay stall is FAB!!! Gotta TRY!!! Hard to get yummy Satay in Singapore - so I do feel that they do pretty good ones.

What I Don't Love: Absolutely nothing!! :)

Hipster cafe w abundant seating near Bugis+ mall (about 7 min walk from MRT station). Interior is spacious with both downstairs and upstairs seating. I had the Baileys Coffee Cocktail which was a unique item to experience at this location.

text:
Atmosphere: cute, hipster-ish, bright lighting 
Service: decent but took awhile to receive my order. But they were nice and said goodbye when we left. 
Pastries: almond croissant was over-baked making it a little dry. But I appreciated that it wasn't ridiculously sweet like many cafes do now and the amount of almonds too! So that's a plus. 

Seating can be limited friends that people take a table for studying, laptops, etc. But there's an okay amount of seating. 

Selection of pastries, pretty good. Everything is supposed to be housemade which is nice as well. 

People seemed to be ordering the Swiss rolls of different flavors. Earl grey was out but matcha looked yummy. I did not order it but maybe another time if I come check it out. 

Tip: there's wifi! 
Tip2: you can order swissrolls in advance for pick up :)

Located near one of the entrance of Bugis Junction. When I was here the traffics isn't high. But I do think is very under staff for this outlet.

The whole experience is not that great, it take them about 15mins to come to us to take out order. For 2 drinks we waited for more than 20mins. 

The drinks are fine, but I will try to avoid here as possible in the future.

text:
This café is worth a visit if you're in the area. It's another one of those café-in-neighborhood, except this one has a Kodak photo printing station as well, and it has a social enterprise component to their business. So rather cool. 

Payment in cash, unless you're eating with several people and your bill is over $40, then Credit Cards are accepted. 

Come here if you want to print photos from a Kodak photo station. And if you want good American fare, decent desserts, and all the while supporting a social enterprise. The café is nicely tucked inside a neighborhood with minimal parking but that shouldn't be too much of a problem.

Flat White', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Flat White'}]
text:
Craftsmen Specialty Coffee is now open!

Yes! After a temporary closure due to staff training, Craftsmen Specialty Coffee, which specializes in coffee and cakes, had a reopening just few days ago.

Besides from the food options, they also have appliances for sale here.

Dutch Colony Coffee Co.'s blends are used here. The Flat White ($4.50) tasted strong and firm, yet has a low acidity that everyone can enjoy.

The bakes and pastries here are supplied by online bakery Fathiscakes and Bonheur Pattiserie. The Salted Caramel Popcorn ($8.90), one of the cakes baked by Fathiscakes, is firm and satisfying. The caramel taste is just right; flavourful and not too sweet. Add a pinch of salt with popcorns on every mouthful and this will became a delightful cake to have.

The location also meant that it is a quiet respite for people to relax with a cup of coffee or to study in during the day. With its reopening, the Siglap / East Coast area has now yet another cafe to be added to its list.

Heard about the crowd here on weekends so I was a little concerned about coming here on a Sunday night. 

The place wasn't too hard to find from the nearby bus stop (you might have parking problems if you're driving though!) and the ambience was decent. 

There are lots of nostalgic stuff laid all over the place which makes the overall ambience quite cosy - albeit a little forced, as another Yelper mentioned in his review. 

Having gone down mainly for dessert. A friend and I ordered a flat white, the crunchie hazelnut and a tiramisu to share among us. 

I take pride in my coffee and I can honestly say the flat white was nothing special - a little too flat (pun unintended) actually. 

The crunchie hazelnut and the tiramisu looked great and I thought it would at least make up for the disappointing coffee. 

I was wrong. 

The crunchie hazelnut had an overwhelming taste of fresh cream that made it far too sweet for both our tastes. 

The tiramisu came with a serving of espresso - which was something I had never seen before, and for good reason. Without the espresso, the tiramisu tasted entirely of marscapone. Even with the espresso poured in, it still felt pretty... off. I couldnt taste any kahlua liqour in the tiramisu with or without the espresso, which to me, sealed the deal as one of the poorest tiramisus I've had. If you want a good tiramisu, try out Kith Cafe at Park Mall - it's far better. 

The place was also quite noisy, so if you're looking for a quiet place to hang out with friends or loved ones, take note. 

I didnt try any of the food items, but the lamb ribs and wagyu burgers other people were eating looked quite appetitizing.  But then again, so were the desserts we ordered.

Not coming back to this place again. At least the service here was something worth mentioning.

Lots of hot sauces to add! I also had a noodle dish with pork belly, also yummy! Definitely a good stop for a huge variety of food choices!

The brekkie comes with an interesting "angmor Begedil" : the potato patty that Malay stalls sell? Nice coz they have onions in there to bring out the taste and when I ate it with the fried bacon which is on the salty side, they both went well:) 
Nice music played so good for chillaxin'

text: I googled for free-wifi AND power plugs and found this place. What's lovely about it is you can manage to comfortably get lounge seats on a weekend evening. And there's no queue, not much of a crowd throughout the night. Yes, it's QUIET. A rare gem I would say. I also really admire the fact I could drink coffee, look up and there you are, a TOILET BOWL complete with toilet paper right above my head. It's so randomly ridiculous yet genius that I LURVE IT. I even took a picture of it, go see. I ordered the banana bread pudding, - $14, and coffee. The presentation of the bread pudding was very cute, it came in a pot, on a wooden slab. Coffee was better than most cafes I've been to, and service was... Let's just say that they let you do your own thing, and they do theirs, and if both lines should intersect, colourful unicorns will bloom. Pricing is on the high side. One thing that made me feel like getting up to leave, was the glaring red neon lighting fixture, that engulfed me and my companion. It reminded me of an episode in Seinfeld (who else still watches this?!) where Kramer's entire room emitted a red glow because Kenny Rogers moved opposite his room and their crazy signboard faced his window. Check out eatlikeawhale.blogspot.sg for more pictures and reviews.

text:
We decided that the best way to try the Tiffin Room would be a high tea, which I must say was very well done and included a couple of things to set it apart from the crowd.

The staff were perhaps somewhat surprisingly very friendly, not stuffy, we saw them taking photos for groups and even allowing people to chose when they were served, so full marks here.

The food was enjoyable, and the inclusion of a buffet of Asian dumplings and extra sweets was nice; though I was a little disappointed that some of the sweets appeared in both the served tray and buffet... A minor issue really.

As a once off experience when visiting Singapore I would recommend this, though there was nothing that would excite me to repeat my dining experience from the high tea perspective.

Love the butter cake which was very buttery and moist.

text:
Ya Kun has dozens of outlets in Singapore but this is the original location. It was conveniently located near our hotel in Chinatown and was a great way to start the morning.

It was his first time in Singapore and we shared one order of kaya toast, eggs, and tea. It was not a bad way to spend a few dollars.

Just enjoying another wonderful time here... always so relaxing... We had a perfect coffee break (very good!) and I craved what I think it's the best dish for this hot Sunday: THAÏ BEEF SALAD!!
soooooooooooo yummy
Don and his team are so helpful and it's just always such a pleasure being around here!!
Highly recommend this place.
Best latte ever found in Singapore though a bit expensive but worth it when miss real coffee once in a while.

text:
Espresso - a small volume of potent coffee, partially covered with a medium brown crema. There were some citrus notes, but they were secondary to the intense bitterness which followed in the aftertaste, and which lingered long after the shot had been finished. The bitterness is dominant in this shot, with some harsh elements present also. This may not be an issue for pour over coffees, or americanos, where the end product is diluted with hot water, however an espresso shot is more concentrated, which can exacerbate harsh notes. There are a number of different types of coffee beans available however, and D'Good offers customers the option of choosing their own preferred type. It may be advisable to highlight this more prominently at the ordering counter though - it is certainly a selling point that not all cafe's in the area offer. 

Cappuccino - there are some large bubbles present in the foam, but not in sufficient quantities to affect the texture. The latte art is nicely executed also. The mouthfeel is dominated by the texture and taste of warm milk, rather than the hybrid of milk and microfoam that can work in conjunction to form a smooth hybrid of taste and texture. The flavour of the underlying espresso shot is somewhat diluted by the milk, but the bitter aftertaste is still discernible. This may be entirely subjective, but the intense citrusy bitterness described above may work better with pour over coffee, rather than with milk based drinks. However, as there are a number of bean varieties available, and the ability to customise drinks, this can quite easily be fixed, and may not even be an issue from week to week.

Staff are friendly and accomodating to requests, noticing when customers are looking for sugar or water, and stepping in to help. Also, thought and effort has clearly gone into the decor and layout, with an intelligent use of space allowing for lots of seating space, as well as a very pleasant al fresco area on the upper level. Busy periods can cause delays however (just as they would in any cafe), with a delay in used cups and plates being cleared, and tables being cleaned. Staff seem clustered in the kitchen and ordering counter area instead, but it should be noted that they did collect plates from the upper level before the end of my visit. Increasing the frequency of staff checks on the upper level may help.

The ordering counter can become crowded, and as a result customers collect drinks after they have been prepared. This may be to keep the ordering counter clear, but one minor issue is that drinks can be slightly less warm when the are collected. This is a minor issue though, keeping the ordering counter and roasting space clear is a good reason for doing so. 

At $14.50 for a single espresso and 2 cappuccinos, the prices are about right. There is also a selection of cakes and baked items available, as well as syphon and pour over coffee.

Overall, this is not a bad cafe by any means, with some admirable traits - a good selection of beans and brewing methods, and a micro roastery - everything I look for in a quality cafe, and I genuinely want D'Good to succeed. With some minor changes to the beans used for different drinks, and to the frequency of checks on the upper levels, this could be a very good cafe in a great location.

text: TBB hasn't really gotten very much love since it opened to much fanfare a few years back, and I'd just like to drop it, and this branch in the Holland Village area, some love.  I appreciate consistency because it keeps my borderline OCD from a border-crossing.  Consistency means that all I need to account for are trading hours and I know when I walk into a TBB and order a croissant, I can expect on-the-money flakiness, a bready almost dough-moist corpus, and an enveloping buttery nose.  I want and need that kind of reassurance in a world where things can turn on a tweet, and TBB has always been dependable in delivering on that promise of consistency and consistent goodness.  The Holland Village TBB at Chip Bee is no exception.   Nice that it's also located near plenty of parking at the Raffles Clinic building right behind it and within neighborly proximity to the Daily Scoop!  Hang in there Holland V TBB, it shouldn't only be banks that are dependable in an increasingly undependable world.

text:
well steeped and hence rather steep?

as you all know by now, my go to caffeine has to be a cuppa coffee but this bespoke tea bar, like others rising, has definitely gotten my attention.
but don't worry, you flat whites, magics, cortados and blacks won't be so easily replaced:)

but the folks here are giving you a really tough fight!
professional tea brewing machines that looks good and delivers a punch!
definitely very well steeped and hence might be a little steep for most.

also available are refreshing tea cocktails, like what bartenders will concoct, sans alcohol for days where you would like to give your liver a break.
well crafted and steeped but obviously less steep!

i do like their location.
easy access from bugis mrt station, to pogo ex raid gym and convenient, plentiful shopfront parking is also available.
i do like their chillax interior décor, bright and airy, filled with friendly and knowledgeable staff.
of course all these are irrelevant in times of takeout covid19:(
but yes, they do island wide delivery so you can still have some well steeped at slightly more steep.

I feel this cafe has good food potential and was certainly recommend. Coffee is quite strong which I do enjoy. My chocolate crossaint was great and partners mango smoothly delicious. However the bacon, egg, tomato toastie I felt was a little lack luster. 
What really let this place down was the speed of service. It took us 30mins to get the toastie and crossaint, which we needed to ask for as a reminder. 
Also be prepared to sit outdoor or take away. As there is no indoor seating.

This may be the first time I'm doing a review without having even gone to the shop in question, Two Man Bagels. Let me explain. 

I organized a potluck brunch on Sunday and my American friend brought a giant brown bag to lunch. I was all "hrmph who brings store bought food to a potluck?" as I cooked my organic sausages from Ryan's when he said, "I brought bagels". That made me almost drop my sausages right there.

Bagels?!! In Singapore? "

"Please tell me it's not those expensive things masquerading as bagels from 'New York' that are sold in Cold Storage?"

"Nope it's from Two Man. It's right by my house, I chat with them all the time and they make awesome, as-good-as-it-gets-in-Singapore bagels...oh and try the walnut cinnamon raisin something magic spread in that tub and thank me later."

At that point I was pretty stoked to find the bag contained TWENTY bagels in a gazillion flavors. I couldn't find a sesame bagel (cos I'm boring like that) but I found a brown raisin one, popped it in the toaster and generously spread the magic stuff on. 

Oh. Ma. Gawsh. 

Oh. My.

I ate that bagel in about a minute. And then I ate a half more.

It was crisp on the outside and had a good chew. Granted it isn't New York or Bodo's great, but hey we're in Singapore. Plus I'm told the prices are faaaairly reasonable, unlike the child I traded in at Sacha & Sons for a lox bagel. So yes, the next time I intend to blow my carb budget, I'm taking this bum down to icon village. Wherever that is.

When two champions from the Singapore National Barista Championships come together to helm the Oriole Cafe and Bar, you can be assured of the quality of this food and beverage outlet. Owner Keith Loh recruited John Ting and they have created an institution for coffee lovers to indulge in great coffee previously found only in the cafes of Europe or Australia.

It also doesn't hurt that the menu includes kick-ass mains such as the oriole burger and grilled NZ lamb rack, as well as flavourful pastas. I would end the meal with a light dessert, either the eton mess or the apple strudel, along with a flat white or the americano.

A meal at Oriole is money well-spent on great food and drinks, whether for lunch, brunch or dinner. Or even just a cuppa as you rest your tired legs from shopping.

I had a salad and truffle fries here, and I must say their truffle fries are one of the best I've had in Singapore for the price and portion. I'm a huge fan of truffle fries and I order it almost every single time I end up in a restaurant with truffle fries on the menu. Seriously give the truffle fries here a try. 

I had the P.S. House salad, and added the rosemary-honey dijon chicken. I think this was one of maybe like 3 times in my life I've ever felt satisfied after eating a salad without craving a burger or something. The salad was well balanced and I love the dressing. The chicken was very well seasoned and surprisingly tender.

The food was excellent, but I must mention that the service was not fantastic. We put our names down on their iPad checkin system, but we waited for half an hour without being seated even though the place had a couple of empty tables. We went up there and asked a server how long more we would have to wait (we were the only customers waiting), and she said another half an hour in a pretty flippant manner and walked away. We got pretty confused then, since we were told that the wait was half an hour pretty much half an hour earlier, and now we're supposed to wait another half an hour? When she came back we told her our name was in the system, and only then she led us to a free table.

My friend ordered the same salad as I did, and told them to leave out the rocket. The waiter noted that down and said it was no problem. When the salad came surprise surprise it came chock full of rocket leaves. We called the waiter back and he said the kitchen premixes the salad, so they couldn't take it out. Well before I get started on a kitchen that premixes a $25 salad, if you can't take out the rocket at least let us know before you serve it and ask if we're still ok with having it.

I only took away 1 star because the food is good although it is pricey, but I really hope the service improves.

text:
I have to say, some times fusion food can go quite wrong.  But in the case of Collective Brewers, IMHO, they've got it just right.

I went with a bunch of colleagues, and so we tried every 'rojak' dish we could find on the menu.  Off the top of my head, lap cheong aglia olio, tonkatsu burger, beef rendang sandwich and they have an appetiser which is like siew yoke sliced like char siew.  I could described them one by one, but instead I'll just Collectively say, all good!!!  And they come with ngoh hiang (5 spice) fries.

And the best part for me.  The coffee after.  They are very attentive how they make it, brewed to perfection. Will probably be a regular.

text:
The place I had been to on a previous visit has since gone out of business so I searched yelp for a place that could do nail art. I also creeped the instagram page and saw some pretty awesome designs. Be sure to check out manicurioussg IG page. This location was under construction so I didn't get the coffee pie and all that. I was offered a beverage but had brought my own ice water. Be sure to call ahead and make a appointment. I had to wait an hour for a mani/pedi. 
Though I had requested nail art when making my appointment- they said they didn't have time to do it when I came back. I ended up having a wee Baymax painted on my ring finger, but I would have really liked something more dramatic. My manicure has lasted a week with just regular OPI nail polish- that's unheard of. I have a few very small chips but it's not noticeable unless you really examine my fingers. I did pick a neutral color. 
My pedicure was amazing. I left with my feet feeling brand new. Every inch of my feet were buffed and puffed then slathered with lotion. It was easily the best pedicure I have ever had. I wish this salon was in Dallas and not halfway across the world from me! 
I would come back but be sure to specify exactly what you want when making your appointment and be sure to call ahead! Since everything is under construction inside it's not the best place to wait - head to the Starbucks across the street.

text:
Cute as a button! Don't be put off by the roadworks outside, because behind the front door Flee Away is an escape from the noise and heat outside. It's a cafe, but with a twist. Yes you can eat and drink, but look closer at the menu for a few surprises. And while you're flexing those eyeballs, look up at the walls and ceilings for old antique trinkets that make you feel like you're in a child's bedroom. There are perspex boxes by the front door and inside you will find locally made nick-nacks that you can buy and take home. A great spot for unique gifts with a Singapore flavour.

The menu is intriguing. There's familiar flavours like Chicken Curry and Laksa, but they're served up in entirely inventive ways. The Chicken Curry "sandwich" was incredibly tasty, though I'm glad to have shared one as it was incredibly rich. I don't even know what the "bread" was but apparently it's a well known Chinese food item that is never used in sandwich format. 

The same innovation extends to the drinks menu, especially the milkshakes.  At Flee Away you can order fun milkshakes like "Happy Birthday" flavour that features cake mix inside. Why eat Red Velvet Cake when you can drink a milkshake that tastes like it? 

The coffee isn't going to win any awards for third wave artistry, but it's passable and comes served in a cute teacup loaded with little lion biscuits in the side. 

The ambience here is nice, with great music and staff who really want you to have fun and enjoy yourself. You won't feel bad spending some hours here working or reading, so feel free to bring a book and settle in with some food and drinks.

text: This is a review of a dinner with a friend on a Friday evening at Privé Grill. First, as it is on Keppel Island, it is a little off the beaten path. The room is modern yet classic. This is the type of room that defines what I expect from a fine dining experience. My only issue with the ambiance is that, even on a Friday evening, the restaurant was almost completely empty. This means the evening was missing the energy brought by other diners enjoying their meals. The staff is excellent. They are friendly and professional. But, more than that, they demonstrated an eye for detail and took extra steps along the way to insure we enjoyed our meal. The food ranged from below average to excellent. It is this level of inconsistency that left this just short of a five star dining experience. The meal was extremely well paced. The staff had a knack of being there when needed. The server was very helpful with our questions concerning the menu. The food came in a perfect and never rushed order. After we had selected the bottle of wine, they brought an amuse bouche of sashimi. When I communicated to the server that my dining companion can not eat raw seafood, the server quickly whisked hers away. Soon after, a replacement of grilled watermelon was brought out. tinyurl.com/dxc3e5u tinyurl.com/cvexxd7 A nice basket of breads was provided next. tinyurl.com/c2yyzbw We usually order starters to share. However, on this evening, we went our own ways. We shared small bites but, for the most part, we stuck to our own appetizers. I chose: JAMÓN IBÉRICO BELLOTA (Saffron Pear Chutney, Tomato Bruschetta) This was very good. The Iberian ham itself was excellent. The sweet tomatoes provided a nice contrast to the ham's saltiness. The bread was simply there as an organic spoon. tinyurl.com/bn8b3c9 She chose: PRIVÉ GRILL'S CAESAR SALAD (Poached Egg, Bacon, Shaved Aged Parmesan, Garlic Croutons, Anchovies) First, my friend ordered this without the sliced anchovies. From my taste and watching my dining companion easily complete it, this seemed like a very successful rendition of a classic. The only negative was the large shavings of Parmesan were a little difficult to navigate. They may have been a little form over function. The salad would have been easier to eat with an even distribution of smaller shavings . tinyurl.com/cju9qol My Main: NEW ZEALAND "HARMONY" ORGANIC (Sourced only from free-range farms, Harmony's cattle are all 100%grass-fed in open pastures. - RIB-EYE 340g) - Hmmm, with all of that fancy talk, I expected a melt in my mouth spectacular steak. It simply was not to be. It was cooked to a perfect medium rare. However, through lack of seasoning or some other misstep, it was rather bland. While not tough, it was also not as tender as I expect from a high quality rib-eye. tinyurl.com/c4bfl95 TWICE BAKED POTATOES (Bacon, Sour Cream, Chives) This was barely edible. It was more akin to overcooked baked potato than twice baked potato. I love potatoes. I really do. For me to walk away from a potato, there has to be something seriously wrong with it. Her Main: JOSPER-ROASTED WHOLE SEA BASS (Confit of Garlic Bulbs, Lemon Caper Sauce) Every show has a star, and for this meal, the sea bass was certainly the diva. It was tender. It was buttery. The garlic and the lemon were provided in a way that they were complimentary without dominating the flavor of the delicate fish. This is how a fish should be served. Unfortunately, it was hers and I only was given remnant bites here and there. One last little touch, when asked about dessert, we looked at the menu. We both decided we simply could not eat anything else. After we told our server, she soon returned with a small bag containing a slice of carrot cake for us to share later. The receipt: tinyurl.com/d2tvq9v Overall, this was a very good dining experience. The service was excellent. All the ambiance required was the buzz brought by additional diners. The food certainly had some very high points but there were also some low ones. In the end, we both enjoyed our time at Privé Grill. (Special note: We topped it off with a lovely and very peaceful walk along the water. This is definitely a secondary perk from dining here.)

text:
While the seating isn't the greatest, the coffee is outstanding and the food is delicious. 

Grab a table and place your order at the counter when you're ready. Eggs & toast was SG$10 which seemed reasonable (for the area). The avocado toast was an absolute mountain of avocado!

I really loved my latte (for the first time in Singapore) - finally one that wasn't overly bitter. Melbourne folks continue to meet the stereotype of being coffee experts. 

We also had a vanilla-Nutella milkshake. I was a little surprised that it was watery like milk (instead of thick like american shakes) but it was still super tasty!

Free wifi - just ask for the code.

Terrible customer service. Came in thinking we wanted to try the food, took 10 minutes before anyone greeted us or said anything to us AFTER we got their attention ourselves. We were put on a waiting list and waited in the restaurants for 30min before we finally gave up. The staff are rude and unattentive. There were empty tables in the back, and staff would leave them empty for 15min before they sat anyone down. Skip the wait and the disappointment.

What's with the attitude here, ladies? Grain Traders must have the shittest service in Singapore, hands down. Not a single smile and really curt replies when we ask questions. It wasn't even at peak lunch hour. And I thought it was just me, maybe I had too many questions since it was my first time, but my two other girlfriends had the same treatment. There wasn't anyone in line after me at 2pm. Ok, maybe they were tired from lunch service.
The quinoa was yummy. The beef ok... For the same price I could get just as yummy a salad without the bitchiest attitude from the whole bunch of staff. Not cool, Grain Traders!

text:
Favorite place for yogis! I heard that they use to give discounts to students studying for their yoga teaching certificate at Tirisula, but sadly that's no longer the case.

Best coffee in Arab Street! My favorite order is the Mexican salad with organic chicken and fresh guacamole. Fresh greens, shredded chicken, and zesty guac--me encanta! Other yogis have ordered the Mongolian beef salad and salmon salad. Also quite good! I've also tried their toast, and loved the honey they have! 

Would def. come back for some food if I'm in the area!

Oh Symmetry. Why have you fallen so far so fast? I remember when you first opened. I bounced in all wide-eyed and innocent, was seated promptly and fed delicious coffee and scrumptious food in a timely manner. I felt like this was a standout for Singapore's crowded brunch/cafe scene. I felt like I'd discovered a new world full of wonder, magic and beauty.

Fast forward 6-12 months and cynical business management and poor execution have sunk an otherwise promising business. It was Chinese New Year and Symmetry was one of the few places open. I'm not complaining, I still need places to go on public holidays. But when a restaurant remains open it's a warning sign. It's more difficult to get produce, there are less places open so crowding is a danger. But none of those things should be an excuse to provide a sub-standard service or product. Which on this occasion Symmetry most definitely did.

Let's see. Configuration of the tables had changed to cram in more diners so we were cheek-by-jowl. I felt like I needed to execute a triple somersault to get from my table to the door and back. Not comfortable.

Then it took 45 minutes to get two plates of moderately fancy eggs. We're not talking about slow-roasted ox-cheek and duck confit here. Just some slightly fancy modifications on poached eggs, that's all. 

Hey your kitchen can't handle a full restaurant at lunchtime? That's a problem for you. If you have 30 covers and you can't feed 30 covers on a limited lunch menu with simple dishes then you shouldn't have 30 covers. Maybe you shouldn't be in business. Just sayin.

So how's about those poached eggs? They were frankly pretty terrible. I ordered the "sur le plat". Hey everyone - don't give your dish a fancy French name, it raises expectations. The sur le plat was like virgin sex: quick, uneventful and unsatisfying. It was subtle like beating someone over the head with a fire extinguisher. Maybe it gets the job done but it isn't worth the effort.

I was promised "artisanal bread" and good quality sausages. I got a crusty piece of butter-slathered cardboard and what tasted like supermarket-quality frankfurters chopped up and served lukewarm in a saucepan. And the eggs. Oh the eggs. How do you undercook poached eggs? You know those half-boiled eggs you eat with kaya toast? They have a very unique consistency somewhat reminiscent of what one might use for inseminating the *other* kind of egg. Y'all know what I'm talking about. 

And that's fine. I love half-boiled eggs. But I ordered poached eggs. And these eggs were definitely not poached.

I'm sorry Symmetry but even a halfway passable coffee and service with a smile did not save my abominable experience. Never coming back.

text: I'm updating my review and deducting 2 stars in the process as I feel that standards have dropped quite a bit. Quality control and consistency is lacking - different amounts of milk used for the same drink ordered, depending on the day and the barista making the coffee. The milk is sometimes merely lukewarm and gets cold very quickly. But the nail in the coffin was when the lid of the coffee cup was not closed properly by the barista and my colleague had coffee on his white shirt, pants and shoes when he drank from the cup. No apologies from the barista who swiftly proceeded to take the order from the next customer instead. And this was in the morning before work. Needless to say, that was an awful start to work. For all these reasons, regrettably, I will not be making this place my regular joint anymore but will probably still drop by from time to time to see if standards have improved.

Symmetry eggs sur le plat', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Symmetry eggs sur le plat'}]
text: I love brunch but hate boring brunch places.  Ultimately it comes down to the food but its a bonus when its a fun atmosphere.  I really enjoyed symmetry.  The food was great.  I found the menu to be interesting and well put together.  Its not standard and they seem to be trying to make interesting dishes.  I liked everyone's plate except my own.  It wasn't that it was bad. I had the symmetry eggs sur le plat.  It just had a little too much sausage and not enough flavor.  But the eggs ben was awesome as was the pork collar croissant.  They have a nice selection of beer and the prawn popcorn and bacon cheese balls were super tasty.  The staff were very nice and attentive.  They could give nice suggestions aside from the usual blank stare when you ask whats good.  The food came quick.  Everyone at brunch enjoyed it and I would recommend it easily.  I didnt feel the price was that bad. Its a little more than average but not any more than a place like PS Cafe and I find the food to be more interesting. I'll be going back to check out dinner.

One of my favorite go-tos for consistently good char kway teow! This stall has been around for ages, run by an old auntie and uncle. When they aren't hard at work with the wok, you'll catch them preparing their ingredients throughout the day. 

Situated in a fairly non-descript coffee shop, Sheng Chen char kway teow is located in a small hole-in-the-wall units beneath a HDB block. Nonetheless, they've managed to garner quite a loyal fanbase, as evidenced by the trickle of maids streaming in for takeaway orders, and the fair number of newspaper cuttings displayed. I really enjoyed the cripsy pork lard, as well as the fresh cockles, freshly shucked every morning by the auntie. It had just the right about of chilli, and the firmness of the noodles was just right (though some might prefer it a little softer). 

At $2.50 a plate, it's a sinful treat on the cheap. While paling in comparison to the epoch of char kway teow that is Hill Street in Bedok, this is definitely one of the best traditional wok-fried versions you'll find in the south of Singapore.

Robertson Quay is undergoing some serious revival with new hotels and changes in the food scene along the river. A homegrown favorite SPRMRKT has expanded and set up shop at the Singapore Tyler Print Institute (STPI) Creative Workshop & Gallery. I've walked past several times but only noticed their bistro concept SPRMRKT Daily. Little did i know that their Kitchen & Bar, which serves refined European food, is tucked away upstairs through a side stairway.

The spot is absolutely gorgeous in the day with expansive views of the idyllic riverside. Lunch sets are offered, starting from $30, served with coffee or tea. They have also started their weekend brunches and we say grab a table now!

For lunch, start with a simple but wholesome Brussels & Roots with a honey clove dressing. The vegetables are simply steamed- golden baby beetroots and baby turnips along with the Australian Brussels sprouts. The garden of greens is flavored with pops of umami from the slow-baked tomatoes seasoned with thyme, garlic, sea salt and olive oil.

For lunch, go for a lighter Pan-Roasted Chilean Sea Bass. The fish is seared and basted with butter, then finished in the oven with a simple touch of salt, pepper, and lemon juice. A refreshing ratatouille adds a juicy crunch to the mix. We agreed with the chicken stock flavored polenta which was rich and velvety with some Parmesan sharpness.

For dinner, the Firefly Squid ($24) surprised us with a bacon-like smokiness in the meatless cauliflower puree. I have no idea how but i'd take all the cauliflower puree as a guiltless replacement. The special firefly squid from Japan is intensely flavored, having been marinated overnight in soya sauce, sake, mirin and brown sugar. 

Definitely order the Octopus & Prawn ($24). This has to be one of the best (if not the best) Spanish octopus i've eaten this year. The octopus is simmered whole with mirepoix and other spices and white wine for 2 - 3 hours before grilling on a plancha. The crispy skin and that tender flesh were unforgettable.

I didn't like the Fjord Trout ($19). I'm not sure if it's due to the way it's cooked- mi cuit style, sous vide with salt, but the flesh was mushy and powdery. The flavor was great, just not the texture. 

Fresh pasta are a must these days. If you like something really meaty, the Malbec Oxtail Pasta ($32) with a smoky Scamorza will satisfy. The oxtail is braised with Malbec (my favorite wine) to impart that berries, plum, and chocolate flavor. Perfect comfort food. Can i have another glass of Malbec to go with this please?

A favorite at SPRMKT is the Smoked Lobster Tail ($42) which features a cold smoked and then seared Maine lobster with toasted garlic panko bread crumbs and a Mac n Cheese. The cheese sauce is a lot lighter than usual as they have added pumpkin puree to the Emmental, aged Parmesan, and Mozzarella mix. 

I absolutely love the Twice Cooked Chicken Roulade ($28). I've not had a chicken so good in a while. The juicy chicken thigh is brined overnight and then rolled with a creamy spinach and mushroom duxelle, before being cooked sous vide and then shallow fried for that amazing Peking-duck-like crispy skin. It's great on its own, with its own jus, or with the amazing curry cauliflower puree (seriously they are so good with their cauliflowers). 

I can go on forever about the other tender juicy red that is the Stockyard Côte de Boeuf ($94). This 200 days grain-fed 600g Australian bone-in beef ribs is good for 2. The ribs are first coated with a house made Creole spice rub before being seared and roasted. Drizzle a little of that beef jus made with roasted bones, red wine, tomatoes, and veal jus for some tart umami. The meat is served with mixed mushrooms, roasted rosemary tomatoes and vine-ripened tomatoes. Perfect date meal!

End your meal with a fragrant and light Earl Grey Creme Brûlée ($16) scented with a lemon lavender streusel base and fresh seasonal fruits.

For something rich and earthy, the Three Beet Chocolate Lava Cake ($18) delighted us with the medley of textures created with the versatile root. Of course, we cannot resist a 70% Valrhona dark chocolate lava cake. I wouldn't be surprised to see more of this beetroot and raspberry sorbet on the market. I'm already seeing a lot of beetroot on the menu of many noteworthy restaurants.

text:
Arrived just after 11am. Easily visible from main road though snugged in between the row of shop-houses with its black front door with glass. Heavy on the modern industrial look - black, dark wood and metal furnishings; but not uncomfortable. Goes very well with the coffee machines that sit along the counter. Perhaps that is what attracts the good mix of patrons. Spacious with three seating areas. We took the front porch section.  
Service was prompt and unpretentious. 
Menu is not extensive. But they have a small selection of all-day sandwiches. Ordered one from the breakfast section and one from the sandwiches section. The steak sarnie was tasty enough. I wish I could enjoy it better if the bread was a little less toasted. Enjoyed the french toast with turkey bacon and caramelised banana. Well, if you are one of those who likes savoury and sweet in one bite. The coffee was good, and the tea was served in a small teapot with double wall glass tea cup. That won us over. 
Finding parking space can be a bit difficult if you are driving.

Banana bread', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Banana bread'}]
text:
I love this place, mainly because I work nearby and it's amazingly convenient to get good quality organic produce without having to go out of my way.

Prices are not cheap (as with most organic produce in Singapore). While they have their own organic farm in Shanghai (why China I wonder...), the fresh produce looks to be mainly from Australia. 

The dried grocery are all healthy and wholesome. Case in point: you can't even find white rice here, only brown rice, quinoa, etc. 

There's also a restaurant and cafe that serves up food that's sold in their supermarket. You get the pasta, pizza, sandwiches and even hotpot. 

Join as member and you get some loyalty perks.

text:
after a long walk at Fort Canning, I was desperately searching for something ice cold and refreshing. knowing nothing about this area I was ready to walk into the first place I would come across to find a place to sit and drink..but everything I saw were massage and beauty spas...but as I walked up a little bit more, I saw a chalkboard sign that said GELATO INSIDE!  Bingo!!! in i went....

first thing I noticed...air conditioning :) then a lovely display of cakes..then..8 different flavours of gelato...i wasn't sure if this would quench my thirst..but as I was debating an attendant asked if I would like anything..so I asked for a taste of the strawberry basil. it was perfect. tart and sweet and most importantly refreshing. so I went for a single scoop in a cone. 5 bucks, and it was a good serving. as I paid she informed me there were seats in the back and water. so I found my way to a stool...plopped on the chair and enjoyed my ice cream. 

they seemed to be setting up new furniture and putting the last minute touches on things.  decor was fun and clean. and as I mentioned the desserts looked amazing. will be stopping by again to taste them. a great new random find!

Nylon Coffee Roasters is situated in Everton Park which is a mere 10 minute walk from Outram MRT, and is hidden by a row of retro and old, slighly rundown HDB shophouses. The coffee shop is partitioned into two - with one end occupied by a professional looking coffee maker, and the other end, with only four seats. 

The coffee (flat white - 7oz for $4) tastes extremely unique and different from the usual coffee joints perhaps because their unique blend is hand roasted indoors. You can also buy the beans they have handroasted for your own personal consumption. It is definitely worth travelling to this slightly out of the way place to try their unique roast.

Whatever you do, do not confuse The Coffee Bean and Tea Leaf in Singapore with the coffee shops of the same franchise you may have grown to love in California. The only similarity is the logo. All coffee I've had from both this location as many others around the city and in airports I've been trapped in has been so awful I've usually just dumped it out.

I arrived at assembly ground on a weekday evening and it was relatively empty with a few groups of people enjoying cups of coffee. While I know their coffee is recommended, I've never been a huge fan of coffee. So, I hesitated ordering a cup expecting my coffee addict of a boyfriend to order one that I can try a tiny bit of. However, he surprised me by ordering a pint...a latte it was for me, and a good thing I did too. The coffee was a good blend in my opinion, less acidic and with a great robust flavour. The milk tasted somewhat creamy which made me slightly suspicious but all in all, it was a good drink. My friend also seemed to thoroughly enjoy her ice chocolate, for those who don't particularly like coffee. I had the coney dog, while my boyfriend had the blackened tuna burger and my friend ordered the beef ragout with rosti. I wouldn't say it was spectacular, just a regular frankfurter it seems with a slightly sweeter than expected beef chilli but it fulfilled my chilli dog craving and as such, I'd give it 3 stars. The remaining star comes from the fact that my companions seemed to quite enjoy their food and the decent portions, and we were served by an exceptionally friendly waiter, who was key to our whole experience being delightful overall. To that waiter, you might think you're just doing your job but thank you for doing it so well!

Very Slow Service!!!

Because I can go to many other places to find food similar to what I get here, I'm rating this fully on service.
One thing I can't stand is my glass being empty. I had to ask while flagging a waitress down to get another drink after my glass had been empty for quite some time. To make it worse, I had to remind her much later that I hadn't gotten my drink yet.

If you have nothing else on your agenda for the day, then I would say go here. The menu is great.  However, the service is slow and spotty.

The thrill of dining here really comes from being next to a marina with yachts on a lazy morning than from the food. It paints an idyllic picture for brunch, complete with the famous eggs benedict. 

Also, the fact that Prive serves all-day breakfast doesn't hurt, especially for those recovering from a hangover or who just cannot bring themselves to wake before noon on week.

The service staff is a little forgetful. But you'd probably do well to forgive and forget too, looking out over these calm waters.

My work colleague always orders from Kitchen by Food Rebel and I've been coveting her zoodle with meat sauce for weeks.  It's not far from our office, so we treked over there Friday for lunch.  First off, it's expensive, even for Singapore, and their margins are pretty insane.  I mean I had a zoodle (zucchini spiralized with meat sauce) and it was $18.   I'm pretty sure a zucchini cost about $1.  The budda bowls looked pretty tasty, they also had some really good looking vegan desserts like carrot cake, an avocado mousse and brownie, but again all pretty steep on the price.  They serve breakfast and wine (not at the same time) and are a cute little place to go grab dinner with a friend or coworker, and the zoodle was good.  They do use quality ingredients, but for me it's still a bit steep.

text: The service was great and the atmosphere was too. I ordered the blueberry pancakes and the veggie sandwich, the veggie sandwich was good, it was packed with avocados which is a plus but it's a little bit pricy, the pancakes's however, tasted incredible along with the warm maple butter and the blueberries on top of it. 10/10 would recommend y'all to come here just to get a taste of the pancakes!!

text:
The food was absolutely delicious - quite damn pricey though - but I was very happy with my keto salad! 
However,,, the waitress got my order wrong at first and brought me a quinoa salad, and when I told another staff that it was the wrong order, she HAD to come over and tell me that she did repeat "quinoa" when I was just like, well I'm not sure what you heard but I ordered keto salad. 
So staffs were not quite friendly.... that was the disappointing part of this cafe, since the food and coffee are great

text: This market is great for lunchtime eats, as it has all different fares from Thai to Turkish to Costa Rican, but what it is really famous for is the satay vendors that set up after work hours. All different flavors and varieties of meats and seafood. Only downside is that the vendors have runners that can be a bit pushy to get you to order from their stall, so be prepared to ignore them or just settle and let them find you a seat and take your order for a few extra dollars.

text:
A rather pleasant and quiet shop. The soup broth is utterly tasty. Recommending the miso and soya broth. Some say the soya broth is a little blander than the rest. To add Matcha ice cream ($3.90) is a worthy choice. Huge cone and very good matcha flavours. 

You can have a choice of udon or Japanese rice inside the broth. We chose the rice and it may make it look like porridge. But very delicious and comforting. Matcha tea also helped us end the meal well. 

Ala carte prices are around $12-13 (excluding GST and svc charge). Sets are around $16. A great place if you'd like a Japanese-esque light and comforting meal for lunch without the crowds

Fantastic Salted Egg Croissant. The one and only for sparking the nationwide slates everything craze. Now hey are starting the chessy everything phenomenon. The beef steak with the melting cheese right in front is simply magical.

text:
We alighted at a bus stop at Dunearn Road and then walked in from Eng Neo Avenue. 
Poor people like need to 
take public transport. :( As we don't drive, we had to walk in and it is a LONG journey. 
The road aren't exactly people friendly. 
I suggest people who are going there to drive in.

The place is located beside ranches and you can probably see some horses outside the window.

The decor is nicely decorated and place looks cozy for a lovely afternoon brunch. 

I suggest you can try this. PACIFIC BENEDICT WITH SWIMMER CRAB, POACHED EGGS,SPINACH AND SHRIMP HOLLANDAISE.

Theres a pleasant surprise underneath the eggs. You can see huge chunks of crab meat. yum yum.

text: Had the breakfast platter and everything was pretty good. Nothing too special but a solid dish nonetheless. Eggs were too well done but they weren't bad. The iced Swedish berry tea was also refreshing.

This is the all day dining at King's Hotel. It's main claim to fame is its Penang buffet, which seems to be available year round.
I was satisfied with the quality of the Penang food. Authentic, delicious, and premium priced. Expect all the usual Penang favourites buffet style without making a trip to Penang.

Reasonable value if you have a M&C a-la carte card discount.

text: Brunch should be about two things.. Good food and good times and that's exactly what we got today at Strangers Reunion. Service was super quick, the Eggs On Toast were light and fluffy, and the waffles were sensational. Perfectly sweetened, and not too thick - can't wait to come back for more!

text: Cute little cafe in the back of one of ION's retail stores called 'In Good Company'. Their array of sweets on display is tantalising, and from the expressions of other customers around, the pasta's pretty good too! I only got a coffee, which was a little cool for my liking (I never enjoy a lukewarm latte) so that brought them down a notch in my eyes, but the staff were friendly and the latte art was cute :)

text:
One of the oldest .. like all eateries in SG it gets real busy during peak times. Especially now that one of the stalls that's been there donkeys years won a michelin star.. being non singas I just love hawker centre food.. to all non locals... follow the pack. If u see a line it generally is pretty darn good!! tonight I ventured here in search of the Michelin star Soya Chicken rice... But was too late.. all finito before 5pm already! was on my own and scouted slot of things I wanted to try due to noticeable local popularity.... I ate ... 

FUKIEN MEIN ... heard some loud crazy wok action and smelt the "鑊氣" ! Turned the corner and noticed a line forming decided to get into the action.. had this already at Lau pasat but this one was better. The noodles and gravy had that extra flavour due to more of the 鑊氣. 

I was actually content BUT saw another line so I mosied up behind an uncle ... and raised my victory fingers when asked how many cus my mouth was drawing a long sip if the sour sop!! 

2 X POPIAH... I would have to say one of the best so far... in SG if u want to ward off vampires eat their popiahs.. man they use a lot of garlic. But at this stall it was the right amount of everything. sauce garlic and the crunchy thingy bob

Soursop.. um watered down but still decent for $2

Chicken rice.. the line was getting crazy luckily I joined 5 min early otherwise would be waiting around corner. Again hmmmm chicken was good but rice was a let down.. 

had to waddle out..

text:
Honest, healthy, scrumptious good food! I love the DIY factor. If you like Grain Traders, you'll LOVEEE this, the food is freshly cooked and not left outside after being cooked like at GT. 

I was not a fan of the pork sausage (too sweet and tasted weird to me albeit the nice fragrance in the air), but I'm a HUGE fan of the grilled halloumi cheese. It was perfection and I dream about returning for that amazing slab of tofu-like cheese.

text:
Ticking off the rooftop bars, we headed here largely because they have their own on-premise brewery. 

We managed to get a table (but no seats) at the balcony, ordered some snacks, and sampled their wares. Their own brew beers are good, on a par with some of the better craft beers I've tried, and whilst a little pricey due to the location it wasn't extortionate.

Our food was good, a mix of sausage, hummus, and bread, and the service was top notch, very attentive and friendly.

Obviously the view is the main attraction, it's one of the better views available, but I'd definitely go back to try the full menu.

text:
Nassim Hill Bakery Bistro Bar has one of the most interesting concepts - bakery with brunch items in the dawn, bistro in the noon, and transformed to a charming bar by dusk with DJs spinning at the side. 

If this bar within a post office concept seems familiar to you, it is also done up by Imaginings who is also behind KPO, WALA WALA, Balaclava and 1128. Beer drinkers can rejoice because you can tap your own draught beers at the end of the counter. (I unfortunately, don't drink beer.) 

Considering I am not quite a carb-person, I fell in love with the Grimbergen Ambree bread ($8), a Grimbergen (Belgian abbey beers) infused bread created by Head Baker Audrey from Freshly Baked at Killiney Road. (No wonder the bread and cakes taste so familiar. The KPO probably approached her since they are 'neighbours'.) The bread is very wholesome, full-bodied and hearty, with a slightly rustic feel to it. Extremely satisfying with the marmalade jam.

We ordered delivery for Mother's Day. Definitely some of the best brunch dishes I've had!

Seafood linguine ($21) - 5 stars
Stellar! They braise the linguine in lobster bisque and the result is a rich and flavourful pasta unlike any I've had! The scallops and crabmeat were cooked perfectly. Hands-down the favourite dish at our table.

Buckwheat pancakes ($20) - 3.5 stars
Too dry this time - definitely better when we had this at the cafe itself - but still had good flavour. The passionfruit curd and berry compote that came with it had just the right touch of sweetness.

Populus scramble with lobster bisque and crab meat ($22) - 4 stars
My sister wished the croissant could have been packed separately. Decadent scrambled eggs with the lobster bisque and crab meat but eggs only do so much for me. I personally prefer the seafood linguine.

Butter rum banana French toast ($19) - 4 stars
Solid but I'm a dessert alcoholic and thought it could use more rum. Topped with Greek yoghurt.

Tuscan lamb harissa baked eggs ($19) - 4 stars
Had a tiny bit of this. Pretty sweet from the tomatoes. Flavoured well. The ciabatta was a little hard.

Wagyu beef donburi ($18) - 4 stars
A touch too sweet. The toppings (purple cabbage and ginger I believe) were well done as was the Japanese rice. Strong truffle taste. I didn't try the beef though.

text:
Went for late lunch but nowhere on the website did it say that kitchen closed at 2:30 pm as we just missed it.

We were seated for cold cuts though. Ordered a cheese and bread platter and burrata and ham and was able to get the spaghetti and meatballs.

Meatballs were nice.

They do make their own pasta and you can have a taste of their cheese.

Nice wine selection. Great ambiance.

Pistachio Tiramisu did not look too presentable as it was liquidy but taste was good.

Service could be better as there were a lot of servers just walking around and talking to eachother but lacking in filling our water glasses and clearing plates.

This place is not bad but not necessarily anything special.

Fried Oyster Omelette', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Fried Oyster Omelette'}]
text:
I had both the Oyster Omelette and the Oyster Egg. I prefer the Oyster Omelette. The sticky dough portion of the dish is crispy (which can be a rare occurrence) and a delight for folks like me who do not like gooey-tasting dough. The proportion of oysters to egg to dough is also perfect.

The chili sauce is normal, just how it should taste like.

I have had fresher tasting oysters in a oyster omelette but overall this is a good dish and I will come back for more.

text:
Coincidentally passed after morning walk. 

Outdoor is the first option for me as I'm craving fresh air.

Preferred scrambled eggs and salmon croissant vs Avocado Toast. Coffee is alright. Not strong enough for me. It taste Robusta. 

Overall, price is quite high with the portion and taste wise. 
Plus serving is so-so.

Delicious! Violet Oon don't play play with her Peranakan food. It is authentic to the source, leaves you wanting more. This is my second time to Violet Oon and the quality of her food is only improving. I highly recommend the dry laksa. The noodles is still al dante and full of flavors. The shrimp that comes with it is cooked to hold the laksa flavor until you bite into it. 

For dessert, their sugee cake is served warm. The flavor is classic and texture meant to melt in your mouth. If you have a special occasion to celebrate, Violet Oon is a great option for a sweet and fancy night. Was there to celebrate hubby's birthday and they took a picture for us with a frame! Very classy! 

The service was impeccable. The staffs were always alert and knows their menu very well. We had leftovers of our beef rendang, which was the best meal of the night. Thought that they would throw it out but no, they called us to tell us we left it! So we went back to collect it. 

Oh, I almost forgot. For gula melaka lovers, you have to try their banana smoothie! Definitely a place I would like to visit again.

text:
You can probably get the best egg tarts in Singapore here. 

The go-to place for egg tarts and 'Lou Por Bang' aka Wife Biscuits, Tong Heng has been churning out these delactable treats for more than 80 years, and judging by the queues you see everyday, you know you wont be let down. 

The egg custard they produce is soft and amazingly smooth. Especially when it's served warm and made even more delicious when coupled with an equally well-executed, flaky pastry base.

The shockingly amazing coffee art.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'The shockingly amazing coffee art.'}]
text: The location is superb, and you can actually get something 3D printed or get your phone or phone engraved with a laser cutter, for a reasonable price. The service is quick, and the coffee art is FLIPPING PICASSO WORTHY STUFF!! The flat white could be creamier, and less froth and more coffee, but apart from that, it was superb. There is also a gift shop. The atmosphere was quiet and cool, and the tall 3D Printer looks perfect on the stand. The café is connected to the Art & Science Museum ad well, which is awesome. I would definitely come here again, totally recommend it!!!

We're having an old friends get together at this restaurant. The food to say the least is "unusual" in that it's a fusion of Chinese and western. Whatever! But the bottom line is that it's interesting and the food is very flavorful. Definitely worth a visit especially if you've become jaded on the regular stuff. Arguably it is a little unhealthy in that we tried most of the fried stuff. But what can you say. Anything fried always tastes better. Sigh! Looks like a diet over the weekend. Anyhow I enjoyed the meal and company and will probably come again, this time with the family. Parking though is challenging so take a cab or plan well.
One of my favorite hawker centers in Singapore, especially for breakfast.  Nice and open, airy atmosphere, and the peanut pancake lady has been open every time I have been there.
Came all the way for the chicken rice and mutton soup but the mutton soup was already sold out. First time here and it was really one of the best chicken rice I've had. Would definitely come back!!

text:
Introduced by my lunchmate to a new tea experience at Old Tea Hut. I was not impressed from the first time I had the drink and was not a fan who buys everyday but once in a while whenever I passby the place, I will take sometime to get a cup of tea. The first reason being its huge cup size (bigger than bubble tea cup size) accompanied by the low cost.

Once, when the next time I pass by the place, I was shocked to find queues as long as 4-5meters. I hardly see queue that long and just for a cup of tea and mind you, it is not bubble tea. So why? Later I found out the more popular drinks are the  Gula Melaka Tea and Iced Honey Lime Tea

Ice Cream that tastes and feels great! Freshly made with little or no preservatives. Creamier is tucked in adorable Gilliam Barracks. After enjoying art, I walked to Creamier.

The smell of waffles is magical!

A couple of flavors with alcohol: Black Forest: chocolatey, boozy and mmmm cherries. The Rum and Raisin was heavenly and ended up being my scoop of choice.
l
For a non-alcoholic choice, I would've chosen the Root Beer Float.

I could've eaten a whole gallon for dinner!

Diamond shaped egg tart, delicious!!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Diamond shaped egg tart, delicious!!'}]
text:
DOUBLE THUMBS UP for their egg tarts!! 

Tong Heng is a real timeless institution that has been around for at least 80 years. They are well-known among the locals for having the best egg tart in Singapore. And when they are that famous, I just had to check it out for myself! 

The store lies at the heart of Chinatown, just along South Beach Road.  The shop itself is petite in space, but interior is very bright and proper. They also have quite an arrays of delicacies that are displayed inside the glass cabinet and of course, coffee/drink to go along with the sweets. 

The diamond shaped egg tart is truly unique, the shells have thick layers of crisp pastry almost like it was deep fried. And the custard filling is so smooth, wobbly and a bliss in each bite. Each tart cost around $1.90. Small price to pay for one-of-a-kind sweet indulgence.

text:
Stumbled across this place by accident while roaming through Chinatown looking for breakfast.  We chose this place because my bf needed an emergency pit stop to the bathroom.  I can't comment on the bathroom facilities because I was a bit afraid to go in there after he was done.  :/

The menu listed a Kopitiam set for only $3.50, yay!  I also saw a beautiful photo of Bah Kuh Teh that we unfortunately didn't get a chance to come back and try for lunch.

Standard Kopitiam breakfast with runny eggs, Singaporian coffee, and kaya butter toast.  Simple decor with a cute old-fashioned look with a mini Singapore coffee museum which was literally just a few ancient artifacts displayed in the back room.

I was excited to let my bf try a wife cake (one of my all-time favs from Taiwan), but I was a bit disappointed at the greasy pastry that ended up before us.  Not sure if this was typical Singaporean style or a rancid leftover, but it was nothing like the light, flaky ones I've had from Taiwan.

We also grabbed some bottles of grass jelly to quench our thirst, and I didn't realize they were mint-flavored.  So that was a bit weird, but still interesting to try something new.

Ambiance 100%

This is the immediate impression when we stepped in to this charming cafe right in the middle of no where one rainy afternoon after lunch. It is so idyllic and very quiet when we were there. We absolutely adored the decor! It felt like someone's open kitchen, filled with delicious things on the shelves.

We only tried their coffees since we already had lunch, but seems like I need to go back again to try the food. I'm already sold on the ambiance, so the food won't be a big problem. Now, how to get there without driving is the challenge...

text: Few good stalls at reasonable price. Famous wah kee prawn noodles started here. My fav chicken rice also nobody covers but at $3, duck at $3.50, no where to find tasty yet so affordable chicken duck rice stall. Except the queue is always at least 45 mins.

Sorry but I don't get it. I really don't.  I agree with a previous reviewer: Why is every single place in Singapore which serves good tasting, real food combined with good service expensive? Seriously, Singapore: you are raising your children to believe that healthy, locally sourced food is only for the elite? That giving good service and being polite comes at a price?

That being said, I am happy that places as Open Farm Community exist and that I can afford going there now and then. The food is delicious and the service is how it should be. The watercress-kale soup is really good, but for 19$ I expect no less. I do wonder though: the other dish we had was beef rib eye: where do they source cows in Singapore?

To me, Open Farm Community needs to seriously walk the talk. Their website reads that they want to connect the community to nature and  celebrate local spirit. In addition to being on the costly side, their location is not reachable without a car.  In a country where a lot of people do not own a car, this is not really helping to reach the local community.

5 stars for the food & service but 3 stars for a concept mismatch so 4 stars overall.

I had heard a bit about FIne Palate but had never had a chance to stop by until a few weeks ago when I came with a friend for a work photo shoot. 

I came in on a Saturday at around 2 and made it just in time for their brunch menu. I ordered the Breakfast Cook Up ($20) which served two eggs any style served on fresh homemade bread, bacon, apple and sage sausage, and potatoes. The apple and sage sausage was my personal favorite and extremely flavorful. I also ordered a cappuccino which was also delicious surprisingly enough

The atmosphere was perfect as they share a wall with a Church next door so you often hear singing. 

The staff were lovely! Attentive and so polite. Great great place for brunch on a lazy saturday afternoon!

text: had the primal and lamb bagel. for someone that isn't hugely into bagels my verdict is....well I loved it. They were huge and cut in half so my wife and i were able to try both.  Coffee was good. Had a long black. They have cold pressed juice and everything was ready in a little over 5 minutes. People working there were nice and friendly.

Toast Box is a nice stop for a break during the workday as they offer all sorts of little snacks and drinks.  The seating here is shared with other restaurants in the this "food court" area.

I had the plum soda which was refreshing, but very much too sweet.  All the sweet "plum" stuff is at the bottom, so make sure you stir it up really well.  They also have kopi/coffe, Milo, barley tea, and various other hot and cold drinks.

Not much else to be said about Toast Box - extremely affordable, air-conditioned, food court-type pick-me-up during the work day type of place.

A nice piece of food heritage! I've always being a fan of the "Chinese" tutu kueh but this brings me even greater satisfaction. The fluffy rice flour cake with a delicious gula melaka filing and sprinkled generously with fresh shredded coconut  and pandan leaves - a taste of heaven and still very reasonably price!
