text:
This place just opened in UE Square, replacing an Italian restaurant. Epicurious is friendly and nice, fairly welcoming. We were there during a soft-opening weekend, which meant they were still waiting for some electrical work to be finished and, thus, some items on the menu couldn't be made. Still, breakfasts looked quite attractive.

I had the eggs benedict while my wife had scrambled eggs on green pesto. Both were good and did the job, but were a bit lackluster. We ended up with an uneasy feeling, that there was something missing. I mean, food tastes good, but is far away from spectacular, and that's when Epicurious starts losing points. There's no "wow! factor", nothing that would make us be anxious to go back. The bill just confirmed this uneasy feeling. We realised that for the same amount we could walk a few blocks and have a dazzling breakfast, or a much more memorable breakfast in Tiong Bahru. Even on UE Square itself, we can get a much more thrilling breakfast for less.

Our friends at Epicurious do a good job and are clearly making an effort. Unfortunately, the food ends up being average while prices are not. I wish they can overcome this gap, they surely deserve better.

text:
I haven't really explored many brunch spots in Singapore. But from those that I have visited so far, Riders Cafe is my favorite. We tried to get a reservation the day before and was told that they were fully booked. They would still accept walk-ins though, and that's what we did. We had to wait for about 30 minutes for our table. Not too bad, considering you can wait in the car until they call you.

I had the poached egg, portobello, sweet corn polenta and it was cooked very nicely. It's a very simple dish but the execution was very good. Another dish that we had was the almond-granola crusted fried chicken. I think the crispness of the almond & granola matches very well as a batter for the fried chicken. I must note that they also served the corn polenta in this dish, too repetitive IMO.

We also ordered the roasted pork belly and it was the letdown of the meal. It was such a sin to cook a pork that way. The skin was hard and not crispy and the meat was just dried out.

I'll definitely go to Riders Cafe to try the other items in their menu again though. I heard that their dinner menu is also good and that's another reason to come back.

Nice and quiet coffee bar that serves good wraps, croissants and some cakes. Relaxed atmosphere with an interesting DIY feeling interior. Young audience. The name comes - I suppose - from the bags and backpacks they sell.

One of those with good roast duck! I have been here a few time becos we love the duck. 

The sauce is pretty sweet and it's easy for lot of people to like it. When the duck slices are dipped in that chilli, it is very appetizing, and goes very well with rice.

They have soups too. Some of the soups sell out fast, and those remaining is usually slightly plain. 

The char siew is lean and nice, lots of people likes it too. If they are slightly fattier, it would be heavenly.

text:
Most of my dreams revolve around the following things:

-PIE
-Pedicures with endless polish color options
-Cute and colorful bags, stationary and jewelry
-MORE PIE
-People serving me free coffee, tea and hot chocolate
-Flying

Not sure if I was dreaming or awake in Manicurious, but I can confirm that I was sitting down, getting a pedicure, sorting through endless polish colour options, and being served pie and (free) coffee. And this was all after perusing a beautifully curated selection of bags, jewelry, and notebooks. Welcome to my dream come true.

text: This may be the best spot for people watching on all of Orchard, outside on the wide sidewalk but tucked behind planters and situated at the corner of Scotts and Orchard.  The dinner buffet is spendy but comprehensive, fun, includes lots of Asian fusion options and delicious.  Not a place to go if you're watching your pennies or your figure.

This place does magical things with vegetables.

I like salads but I'm not really a *salad person* but everything I had was just really freaking good.

Like with one bite you suddenly realize how a pasta salad should be prepared and everyone else has just got it wrong, or you eat a avocado cucumber slaw that's so light and refreshing that you seriously wonder how this isn't a staple for all humankind.

I like this place a lot. 

Playlist and garden feels also A+.

Slight minus for the small space.

This food centre seems a bit out of the way which is good because it wasn't too crowded on a Friday afternoon but bad because I need that crowd to know where to go. I feel so helpless if there are no lines of any sort to help me make the very important decision about what to eat. 

I settled on some curry chicken and bread which was good.  Plenty of seating both inside and out.

Had a craving for bingsu and was always curious to try this place. The little cafe uses the corner shop house well, and is a nice spot to have a chat or date. 

There is a little room on level 2 where kids can play with shaved ice falling from the ceiling, although honestly I think it's a safety hazard. Haha, but that's just me. 

Bingsu wise, the ice is nice and "dry". Its mind-boggling how ice can be so dry. But, I still prefer the bingsu from nunsaram. 

Despite this, it still deserves 5 stars

text:
I love the boba milk tea at Koi Cafe! Chewy pearls and refreshing drinks are perfect for the Singapore heat and humidity! 

This is just one of many outlets throughout Singapore! You'll find one at almost every mall or corner! They have many tea flavors and you can choose the level of sweetness you want! This was my first boba shop stops in Singapore. I really enjoyed my Honey Green Tea with pearls!

Service is quick and they have an automated system that calls out your number when your drink is ready for pick up!

Cash only.

Nearest MRT station: Orchard

text:
Singapore has recently jumped onto the cupcake bandwagon which has been popular in other countries for years. I was excited to try Swirls. But unfortunately, I was disappointed. 

They have many flavors here--traditional ones and also specials like key lime and carrot cake. They also have mini cupcakes if you want to try to different flavors or cant finish a big one. 

Prices here are ridiculous in my opinion. The small cupcakes which can be finished in literally one bite are $3. If I am going to pay this much for a tiny cupcake, I want it to taste amazing. It was just ok. Honestly, the three times I have tried it it was REALLY dry. Not cool for cupcakes at all. 

Also, the staff here was very unfriendly. I went in and out without them saying ONE word to me--how unprofessional.

text:
My expectations were high for what I've been told are the best egg tarts EVER. Perhaps that was the problem. 

These bad boys are diamond shaped with a light and wobbly custard. I just didn't really like the crust. It was too buttery and very crumbly which just wasn't my cup of tea. I also like my custard sweeter but again this is probably just down to personal preferences. 

I actually preferred their char siew pastry puffs which was petite but packed with flavour. 

Best ever? Hmm, debatable. Definitely worth a pick-up if I'm in the area though.

text: Best food court I've tried so far. The wanton stall had an awesome pork and shrimp dumpling soup. Also had their spicy noodle on the side which was perfect. The tried a lime juice fresh from the cold drink stall. Also amazing! Totally refreshing and not too sour/tart.  Lastly grabbed a hot red paste bun from the only place selling hot buns in there which was so fluffy and perfectly hot and topped with sesame seeds, white and black.  I will definitely be back! All for the low low price of 4.90 for all of the above :)

text: This place does the best flat white! Their granola with yogurt and fresh fruit is delicious too but they are quite pricey. Two flat whites and one granola bowl around $30

Solid coffee! I had a good flat white and Americano, but my eggs on toast was just average. The sourdough was fresh and well toasted, but the eggs were runny and bland. The extra sausage I added looked like German weisswurst, but sadly didn't have much flavor, adding to the blandness.

The prices are cheaper than more hipster options like Group Therapy, but it's still pricey for the quality and portions. SGD 15-20 for most breakfast options.

Cash only, unless you've got a NETS card.

Maxwell Food Centre is conveniently located near Chinatown and easily accessible by MRT. If you are a visitor to Singapore like me and with limited time, this maybe the only hawker centre you should visit,

So many choices here. A lot of tourists and locals all come here to enjoy some good food. It might not have as many stalls as the nearby Smith Street Chinese Complex but I love the design a lot more,.at least I don't feel too overwhelmed and lost.

So what are the not to miss food here? Just go and look for the longest lineups with all these locals queue up for their food even during off peak hours! I personally rather not to queue up.. but my sister went and waited over 30 minute for her fish soup and I thought she got lost!

And even if you don't want to queue up for that long, there are also other options... sometimes I just want something quick! 

Tip: for a hot day, I would always pick up a cold drink or ice kachang and the wait can be more tolerable!

I guess I would be back again...and again...

userinfo: {'link': '/user_details?userid=D6-pwyZgXy8wxFy-NbCWCw', 'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/assets/srv0/yelp_styleguide/514f6997a318/assets/img/default_avatars/user_60_square.png', 'srcSet': None, 'markupDisplayName': 'Etienne T.', 'displayLocation': 'Singapore, Singapore', 'altText': 'Etienne T.', 'userUrl': '/user_details?userid=D6-pwyZgXy8wxFy-NbCWCw', 'partnerAlias': None, 'friendCount': 2, 'photoCount': None, 'reviewCount': 48, 'eliteYear': None}
text:
Came here on a weekend for a temporary -- and tragically illusory -- escape from the madding crowd. Well, at least the portion of it sensible enough not to splurge on high tea, I suppose. The tea-related desserts were good! But mains and ice cream flavours were a little hit and miss.

Mains: 
We had scrambled egg with saffron, and foie gras terrine which came with fresh brioche toast. For the egg, you get to choose between three flavours: matcha, saffron, and truffle oil. Matcha+egg sounded a little Dr Seuss so we skipped over that. But I think picking saffron was a mistake, since the saffron flavour didn't come out at all. I was initially skeptical about the foie gras but it turned out to be a winner. The toast was crispy, and soft but not soggy, and the foie gras spread perfectly over it.

Tea:
The selection of tea here really is overwhelming. We zoomed in to the "exclusive blends" section of the menu and ended up with something called Snow Mountain Tea, which is white tea. It was light, clear, and refreshing, and went really well with the dessert.

Dessert:
Madeleines with clotted cream and some TWG Tea jelly, and three macarons. I adore the macarons here. Flavours are rich enough and ingredients are fairly decent quality, something I can't say for many other macarons made in SG. The madeleines were also a delight -- fluffy and warm and perfect with the cream and the jelly. I love the jelly so much I wouldn't mind eating it every day. We also had two scoops of ice cream. One was dark pink and tasted of berries, I can't remember its name but it might have been the Timeless. Not memorable, not worth getting. The other was the Napoleon which had macadamias. This was good.

text:
Back again at my fav cafe. But to be honest, calling Lokal a cafe really doesn't do the justice as its food standard is one of the highest in SG. 

Unlike the weekday mornings, the place was PACKED. They had a waiting list of people to be seated around 11:30am. But I was able to grab a seat at the chef's counter and gawk at all the delicious foods that were coming freshly out of the kitchen and enjoy my food. 

I started off with English breakfast tea-- not bad, but nothing exceptional. But I wish there was an option to have the tea set out of the pot as the tea got way too bitter towards the end of my meal. 

Then I had the roasted pumpkin salad  (5/5 )which just AMAZED me. One of the best salad I've had. It's flavorful without being drenched in dressing and just the right heartiness with well-cooked, yet still firm pupkin, healthy mix of quinoa and nuts, and fresh beans. It is definitely a must try.

Then finished the meal with the chef's first attempt at anzac cookies (4/5; Australian traditional cookies--made with coconut and oats) and my gosh. I'm generally not a huge fan of oat cookies, but this sweetness was just right. And for that I had to order a cup of long black (I've come to not call it Americano anymore while in Singapore) to go along. I was told the beans were roasted by Sarnies and the blend was created in-house, and was called fuzzy wuzzy (4.5/5). But boy did they do a good job. The aroma and the finishing note of the coffee well-complemented the cookie. 

Really aiming to come for dinner in the upcoming weeks.

text: I would say that I accidentally discovered this place, but having walked past it a few times in a number of days, I decided that it might be an idea to step in and check it out. Anyway, I hadn't had much in the way of breakfast yet and I was starting to feel hungry. Well, if you happen to be in that position, then this place is certainly a place worth checking out. The staff were excellent, and the food wasn't all that pricey either. They made a decent pot of tea, and there was a reasonable range on the menu as well, It is certainly a decent place to check out.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/c8p77YT56jEcY9qAvsQSBw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/starbucks-orchard?reviewid=UBW_KtMwktCVfSYBPjaAGw&select=c8p77YT56jEcY9qAvsQSBw', 'altText': 'Photo of Starbucks - Orchard, Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
The baristas here are always so nice. I have been by a few times during my visit to singapore and they always very politely answer all my dumb American questions like if they have pumpkin spice lattes or if my mobile app will work here. Starbucks has consistent drinks and merchandise, but the service is variable and I like that this store is consistently friendly.

I take that part about the consistent drinks back. Starbucks in Asia have some interesting drinks unavailable in the US. I've had matcha tea with red bean in Indonesia and yogurt citrus drinks in Singapore. Apparently I can't get PSLs anywhere but North America, but I can settle for caramel macchiatos, and regular lattes. I also like collecting the city Starbucks mugs and picked up some singapore espresso shot mugs here (I've never seen these little cups anywhere else). 

This store has a little seating area upstairs from the cashier. It's cute and comfortable, but can get crowded in the early afternoon. I'm also soooooo happy that they finally got free wifi. I was getting tired of walking across the street to the cuppage st. location.

Here's an alternative place to view enjoy the beautiful Singapore skyline without having to push and shove against too many people. While it's best to book for the outdoor seat, you should be able to get a standing table after 9PM. Service is usually great as well!

They have a variety of beer to choose from. If you can't decide, order the sampling set first. I haven't tried their food nor their cocktails, but they look decent.

Dirty Norwegian croissant', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Dirty Norwegian croissant'}]
text:
Flavor Flings is all kinds of unexpected. A halal cafe in the middle of a HDB estate that is known for its salted egg croissants. Make that unexpectedly good. 

The afore-mentioned salted egg yolk croissant is all kinds of decadent good. Perhaps a little pricey at $7 but worth the occasional treat. It's a light and flaky pastry with a rich, sweet, and savory salted egg filling that is so unctuous. It's yummy. Note: they do sell out of these so come early. 

I've also had the Dirty Norwegian croissant which is great for a brunch entree. It's the same flaky croissant with smoked salmon, poached eggs, with the same salted egg yolk sauce plus buttered cereal. It's everything great about the salted egg yolk croissant and then leveled up for brunch. Also served with a side salad that I appreciated and chicken sausages that I thought was extraneous and distracting. 

Great casual spot for brunch.

text:
Came here for brunch on a Sunday. My friend and I started out the day right with a beer each. I had an amber and my friend had a blonde. The beers were poured into frosted glasses, and were very refreshing. I could keep drinking and drinking my amber if not for the fact that my food came very soon after.

So I ordered a reuben sandwich. The bread was nice and soft with a slight sweetness to it. The pastrami was tender. There was nice onions in the sandwich too. But I wasn't impressed, and in fact was rather frustrated at why I was still underwhelmed. After a whole day of thinking and discussing with fellow foodies, it finally dawned on me that (and this is kinda embarrassing for me to admit this) the sandwich was just not greasy enough! Maybe I'm used to something with more spice, something with more cheese, something with more warmth. Something this healthier version didn't quite meet.

Located in Tanjong Pagar Plaza next to a bunch of local restaurants and coffee shops, Koko Rooloo serves up reasonably priced Korean food. The restaurant is nothing special, a place to get a quick fix on food and get out of there. I ordered the U-Dong noodles ($8) for takeaway and was pretty happy. These are vegetarian noodles with egg strips, seaweed and skewered tofu, although a small-small-ish portion for the $8. Check it out for something different.

text:
Another excellent eatery in the new Hillv2 mall. Lots of organic stuff and healthy drinks, although cheeseburger is also on the menu.
Very contemporary atmosphere, brand new and icy cold aircon, accompanied by (too much) thumping music. It's nice for a quick meal. Don't stick around too long.

Guess where', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Guess where'}]
text:
A place that I would hangout on weekends. It can get pretty crowded and the seats are not many. Plus, never understood the way the seating arrangements are done in all Toastbox Outlet. Kinda crampy with tables that are hard to slide both your legs underneath. Maybe it's my size, my legs hardly have space below the table and I need to seat like a crab!

But, I still like their Kopi-c. Fragrant and not too sweet, which is the opposite of Ya Kun version. And they offer many different accompaniment for that cuppa. Yam Cake, Thick Toast and Otah Toast and many more. Just next to it is their bread store with different selections and you may just buy from there and sear down to have your bread with a cuppa if the main menu doesn't please your palate.

This always will be my good cup of coffee apart from my favorite Starbucks.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/QvWMFu7oQNYGhAIrLpPQSQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/spinelli-coffee-company-singapore?reviewid=qDKFGqusU387xdIdtr52NQ&select=QvWMFu7oQNYGhAIrLpPQSQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Spinelli Coffee Company - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text:
I love Spins drinks - this place is my favourite chain coffee outlet. The only problem I have coming is choosing what to drink on the day.

I tend to avoid the regular lattes and coffees etc, because they're pretty average here. What I really like are their "spins" and "twists". 

My favourite would have to be the Strawberry T - Twist which is this icy drink mixed with strawberry bits and black tea - super refreshing! 
I also love the Cookie Spin ... it's a super sweet icy cookie mix but really addictive. For something a little less sweet, I'd suggest the Espresso Spin and Hazlenut Chocolate Spin (I love the nutty bits inside). 

Aside from that I prefer their selection of cold pastas (they can warm it up for you) and bruschettas, etc. that are available for a much for reasonable price than Starbucks .

text:
A very cool place for cat lovers!! Better book a few days in advance if you plan to go there. How it works is that, you have to pay for a cuddling fee of $12/hour/person. Then on too of that every half an hour is at a certain rate (not too sure). You will be removing ur shoes so I recommend slippers or easy to wear kind. Also will be required to wash hands with soap before going in the cats area. 

As for drinks, their recommendation is ice chocolate and various teas they have. I don't usually like chocolate but Since the waiter said it's not too sweet but slightly on the bitter side ao I gave it a shot and it's not bad!

Oh and they don't make drinks or food in that place so mostly pre-made. Didn't try their cakes cause was too full but they all look pretty appetizing! Give it a try. :)

But most of the people leave their drinks on the table and go around the place to play with cats instead. And take photos and videos, in fact loads of them haha.

This is my two hundredth review, so we're going to be all dramatic and have pretty LIBERAL USE of FULL CAPS.

A friend once commented that I use full caps in every review I write, and looking back, that's basically true.

Amidst the LUSH greenery of the Rochester area... okay before I go further I have no idea why I typed lush in full caps. It was kinda superfluous wasn't it. It's not like the greenery there is all Botanic Gardens or Bukit Timah Nature Reserve or anything. Definitely didn't need the cap lock.

So amidst the not-so-lush but definitely not sparse vegetation of the Rochester area, is THE nicest Starbucks in Singapore. I believe the one at the Delphi Orchard comes in second, though I will note that I have yet to experience the special Starbucks store near Fullerton. The one that's billed as the 100th Starbucks store in Singapore or something like that? Anyway. This Starbucks. Is. NAAAAAIIIIISEEEEEE. It's like got this colonial aura thing going on with the white wooden and black trim. Even though it's pretty near various schools it's generally not too crowded when you head over in the afternoon, and it's got everything you expect a Starbucks to have.

You have your coffee bagels Wifi overly-sweet-desserty-things students-studying couples-canoodling middle-aged expat working on a laptop... it's EVERYTHING YOU LOVE ABOUT STARBUCKS but somewhere NICE. and AIRY. AND OPEN. 

What's there not to like! 
The only thing I don't get is why they don't open 24 hours or at least till late. It's got this great location. I'd DRIVE there to chill (much like what people do for the Holland Village branch)... SO WHY THEY KEEP CHASING ME OUT SO EARLY. :(

#YUdunwanmymoney

text: I was hungry for Satay so my friends and I headed to Stall 8 at Lau Pa Sat.   Honestly, I was disappointed.  It's not as good as it used to be.   They've added prawns to the menu and frankly I could have done without them.  The beef, mutton and pork sticks were cooked well and the condiments of cucumber and onion were sparce.  Like many things in Singapore, they are cheap with the ingredients.  We also didn't get enough peanut sauce for all the satay we ordered.  And since they already had our money the stall owners didn't care.   Which means we won't go back to their stall again.   Bad service had penalties.

text:
Opened 3 weeks ago, staff is still bouncy and chirpy and the manager is marshaling everyone around, including the new dude that had been standing in front of the cold water tanks for the last 15 min.  When I asked the manager about what he is doing, apparently this is pet of the training to be social.... He is very social with the water bottles for sure! :)

The 4 shot latté is very good and had the right effect.  Croissant was warm and buttery, they get it from the Swiss something (kitchen? Cottage?...), very good.

The open face omelette is a little lethargic even though I asked for it to be made with 3 eggs, it is normally made with "about" 2 eggs... Qual eggs perhaps?...  Lots of good mushroom, cherry tomatoes, beans, a generous serving of cheese and topped with a bunch of fresh spinach leaves.

The only thing about this place is that it's a bit out of the way (but still quite accessible by MRT) and there's a bit of walking.

It looks like this place was recently renovated as the seating is pretty clean and modern looking (marble tables?) and the bathrooms rival those of malls. Not to mention there's an escalator to access the second floor rather than just stairs.

First floor is a market for flowers, goods, produce, meats and etc.

Second floor is the magical food court! On the day I visited there was also a guy singing covers of famous English and Chinese songs which just made the dining experience all that much better.

As I was still stuffed from my early lunch at Maxwell, I only got to try two things here:

Lor Mee: I got the recommended order and added on fried shark nuggets. I mean it's fried shark meat? It was kinda just like eating fish...I couldn't really tell the difference. The gravy that accompanies the noodles is pretty good though. I think you definitely need to come hungry in order to finish a whole bowl by yourself as the gravy is pretty heavy.

MJ drink: wow who knew grass jelly and soy milk went so well together?! Why was this combination not in my life till now! And it's soo cheap too! I would get this all the time if I lived near here! I'm so glad I managed to get here about half an hour before they close shop for the day.

I really really wanted to try the prawn mee by the escalators (looked like it was good as there was a line) but my stomach said there was no more space so next time for sure!

Smart Idea: There are lots of restaurants upstairs. Go there for a meal, then come down here for desert. Make sure you save enough room for desert... well, there is ALWAYS room for desert anyways, right?
That's exactly what I did. Even though my friends and I were full, we couldn't help but to come here to continue our eating adventures.
*Celeb alert: There is a waiter here who is an internet celebrity! There were girls taking "selfies" with him in the background.

We shared the green tea sampler which is a good way to try all the deserts, including the green tea tiramisu. We also had the deconstructed green tea cheesecake. 

Overall, not a bad place for desert, but its a little bit pricey!

text:
This place is quite interesting. It's an eatery under a wellness center. They provides fruit and veggie juices with ingredients that are hard to come by in many healthy restaurants I've been to. They have juices with coconut water, goji berries, cilantro, wheatgrass, etc., but they also add supplements to some of their juices like Vitamineral green, lecithin, maca powder, etc. Their smoothies and shakes are vegan, made with nut or rice milk, a refreshing change if you want to cut dairy out of your diet. 

The food menu, however, is not 100% vegetarian. They have chicken and fish on the menu from what I remember. The night I went, I had the TLC roll and the TLC Cheeseburger, both of which are vegetarian. The roll did have homemade mayo so I'm not sure if its totally vegan, but the quality of the ingredients are definitely very good. The price sort of matches that, reasonable. I paid $40 for a fruit and veggie juice, a roll, the cheeseburger and a vegan/gluten free chocolate cake.

This place also sells supplements, tools to make things at home like a nut milk bag, mason jars and the like, as well as ingredients like salt, vanilla extract, palm sugar, etc. Not gunna lie though, those items were expensive and I know that I can get these same items for cheaper back in the states or even in other shops in Singapore.

text:
I love this chain from London and was excited to hear that it was here in Singapore. Of course you get the peri peri chicken, it is just a matter of what size and heat level. For me and my sister we ordered the 1/2 order of chicken with cole slaw and chips (fries) as well as a side salad. We get mild and that is pretty tasty. They also have 8 different sauces in the front that you can choose from. 

My niece got the children's meal which was a good portion of chicken breast, rice and veggies with apple juice. The apple juice has little aloe bits which I enjoyed and the rice tasted like this Vietnamese rice (xoi). Chicken was actually very moist which is difficult for chicken breast.

text:
I love the living cafe so much, I could cry. 

Located on Bukit Timah and 5th Avenue, I'd be here day after day if it weren't so far and out of the way from where I lived. 

As I try to get away from the plethora of oil laden carb heavy hawker food and onto the raw foods wagon, I start to realise how much Singapore is lacking in it's healthy, organic, gluten/dairy/refined sugars free cafes. In fact, if I'm not wrong, The Living Cafe is the only of it's kind so far here in Singapore (if someone knows of another raw cafe, please let me know!)

The Living Cafe specializes in food that nourishes your body, from the inside out. Most of their menu is raw (meaning, they are all raw vegan foods that have not been heated above 115 degrees fahrenheit in order to preserve it's nutrients). I know, sounds like they'd only serve salads, correct? Wrong. 

My favorites on the menu include their Zucchini Pesto Pasta (note: this isn't actually pasta but zucchini shredded to look like spaghetti and pesto sauce homemade uses herbs and nuts), their Raw Lasagne, Raw Vegetable soups (cold - perfect for a hot day), their Living Rolls (rice paper rolls), Tofu Avocado Rolls, Raw Zucchini Dip (with Flaxseed crackers to dip) and not forgetting their AMAZING AMAZING raw/gluten/refined sugar free desserts. Honestly, the desserts in itself make a trip down here worth it (imagine tiramisu that actually tastes like tiramisu but made solely out of coconut, dates, nuts and other whole ingredients that give you a sugar fix WITHOUT the sugar high)

I love raw foods for it's long term benefits as well as for how good it makes me feel right away, however, making raw foods is truly an art and without the proper knowledge and creative skills, you'd end up eating salads everyday. The Living Cafe truly makes it easy to eat raw from time and time with their creativeness and amazing sauces that liven up otherwise tasteless vegetables. 

On top of that, service is very friendly and the space is nice (nice enough to sit all day with a book) with a small area for your kids to play while you enjoy lunch too. 

My advice? Go for lunch (they close for dinner), get dessert and take a look at their little store upstairs after (they sell things like the Vitamix, Raw Cacao, Chia Seeds, the Zucchini Pasta maker and much more!)

Probably my favourite TCC outlet  - staff are friendly, price is reasonable and opens til late so it is suitable for those who work late. 
I come here because it is convenient and the drinks are good.
The food quality here is reasonable and I actually prefer it to Cedele.
Their best selling iced peach tea is refreshing and delicious.... be sure to give it a try. 
The menu is updated frequently and so someone who comes here often (like me) am always greeted with different things, which is another plus.
I like all their salads - tuna, tataki and tofu are my top 3 picks. 
Their seafood alio olio pasta is another dish I would recommend.

If you're a member you get 15% discount and earn points that you can rebate, so per person it costs around $30 to dine here (food and drink).

text:
Who needs a review for Ya Kun, right? They're all around Singapore, and almost everyone knows them.

But I agree with @Mervin L. who wrote the earlier review, this Ya Kun is just different, and one of my favourite branches. So it warrants a review on its own :)

I am such a local 'Teh' kind of girl, and these are the reasons why this Ya Kun is special:

- Orchard Central, for some reason, is much less crowded than most parts of Orchard, making it a haven to chill and unwind (even work on your laptop - if you have a USB dongle), especially on a weekday/weeknight

- This Ya Kun has full-length windows, lots of natural light, beautiful whimsical drawings on the walls, and a very comfortable relaxed ambience

- In fact, it's so nicely setup that they even offer rental space for private and corporate events within their premise

- Quiet, quiet, quiet (unless there are some stage performances going on downstairs), the Ya Kun to go to for some peace and tranquility

- Choice of in-store or corridor seating (I usually take the latter, more privacy)

- One of the few select branches where Ya Kun pilots newer menu items, e.g. fried toast cubes, kaya balls, toast sticks etc.

- It's right next to NIKS Shop Salon, which happens to be where I stock up my supply of skincare products, so....

The food is delicious and uncomplicated. The staff is friendly and unpretentious. The atmosphere is relaxed and welcoming. Free wifi if you need it. Quirky & clever little bits all around to show you that the proprietor & his staff enjoy what they do.

text:

they also allow substitutions, for extra $$, depending on the coffee and/or salad you get. 

for eg: if you get their infamous cold brew instead of a flat white, you top up $2

i usually get the tomato soup (with pancetta!!), salmon soba! heard great things about the burger and the rice and pork belly usually runs out, so get their early if thats ur jam!

set lunch runs weekdays 12-230pm, excluding weekends and public holidays.

But, we stayed anyway for the satay, which wasn't even that good. It was also too sweet. I've had better satay at Satay by the Bay. The noodle dishes were also not good. The only decent food at Lau Pa Sat was the Singapore oyster omelette. But, this was not a dish that was worth coming back here just to eat. Unfortunately, we will not be returning to this hawker center.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/0sMgtSYAV-5D4pvTZGfNJw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/foong-kee-coffee-shop-singapore?reviewid=HUJOhBIrI7khPHYfu7JSlw&select=0sMgtSYAV-5D4pvTZGfNJw', 'altText': 'Photo of Foong Kee Coffee Shop - Singapore, Singapore. Char siew and roast pork belly.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Char siew and roast pork belly.'}]
text:
The Foong Kee Coffee Shop consists of just one stall that does char siew, siu yok soy, sauce chicken, roast duck, and a pretty good plate of wanton noodles. Oh, and rice too if you prefer that.

The star is undoubtedly the char siew, closely followed by the siu yok. The char siew is a delicious combination of fat, lean meat and charred exterior that really hits the spot. You will probably end up with a couple of slices of char siew that are all fat and you can ignore them because really, a little fat goes a long way. If you're really squeamish about the amount of fat on your meat, you can request for leaner portions.

Place your order at the stall with whomever's holding a notepad (usually a lady) and choose between the warm and humid coffee shop interior or the hot and warm-airy outside. Either way, you're going to have to wait if the tables are filled because the food takes a while to get to your table. Going in the evening makes for a more comfortable dining experience but don't dawdle because they close at 8pm.

Get your green chilli and chilli sauce yourself from the side of the stall. The chilli sauce is provides a nice acidic and spicy kick and goes perfect with the meats. Drinks and ice are also self-service from the fridges and are at a standard price of $1 per can.

Good brunch spot - favorites include the crab eggs benedict and symmetry big breakfast. Pleasantly surprised by the taste - very good execution - something you don't find in a lot of brunch places which tend to make me feel like "all eggs are the same." 

Nice funky ambiance - good for catching up with friends.

This Koi cafe is located at the first level of Bugis + (its new name) just next to Macdonald's, and it faces the main road so not easy to miss it. I particularly like this outlet as although sometimes the queue can be pretty long, like all other koi outlets who put service as their priority, the staff would come out of the counter to take orders. 

Even if the staff doesn't do that, the queue still manages to clear quite fast and customers just have to wait a maximum of 10minutes or less to get a thirst quenching drink. I have been to other outlets and the queue is long too but the waiting time can go up to 20-30 minutes which is madness. 

I like their variety of drinks and coffees, and particularly the bubble milk tea which is the most basic drink there. The tea just tastes so natural and once you try the tea from this stall you wouldn't want to buy any other bubble tea from other stall cause they just don't taste that good anymore. The yakult green tea and black tea macchiato are also must tries.

text:
I've been wanting to visit Whisk and Paddle ever since I saw the green trees and a river that was just within a stone's throw from the café. I almost took a taxi there but decided to use the MRT instead because it was about a 21 min drive from Lavender. So during our first day in Singapore I dragged Hubby along for a joyride to Riviera LRT. Don't worry, we had never even heard about the LRT line before today but the café was within 5 minutes walking distance from the LRT.

Whisk and Paddle was a popular choice for cyclist and families especially since it was a bit of a mini getaway place from the always busy city. I think a lot of people appreciate the change of scenery that they could find within the small area. 

Service was really good and the staff was quite attentive as every customer were given glasses of cold water right as they sat down. There was a small kids' corner where little boys and girls can enjoy some activities using toys provided by the café. If you can't bear the humidity, there is also indoor seating available for customers.

One important tip: as soon as you get off the Riviera LRT, take a lift / stair down and use your google maps to locate the Punggol Police Station. Once you've found the police station, there's a restaurant complex nearby (Popeye's Chicken, Seafood restaurant etc and you will see the Whisk and Paddle café soon enough).

FOOD
The humid weather made hubby crave cold drinks more than usual so he ordered a glass of yellow mango smoothie. I went with the black sesame latte instead, a drink that will certainly make a person conscious of having black sesame powder stuck on their teeth after a few sips. I like my black sesame latte since it wasn't too strong and it came with pretty coffee art too.

We tried the Pandan Melaka waffle that came with Movenpick Vanilla Dream ice cream, cubic butter cakes, roasted cashew, gula Melaka and bits of cornflakes. Today's waffle was crispy and it had a really good texture. The Madagascar vanilla icecream didn't disappoint too and to be honest it was probably the best vanilla ice cream that I ever tasted! Every material worked well together and also perfect to be shared between two people. Next time I will request an extra bowl of gula Melaka ;-).

text:
I had a lovely time visiting the cats at The Cat Cafe. 
Entry is $15, which includes one soft drink, I upgraded to an iced latte for an additional $3.50 and ordered a slice of red velvet cake with cream cheese frosting which tasted like red velvet cheesecake. Total with taxes was about $26, I spent about 4 hours here. Given that most cat cafes in Singapore charge about the same and have a one hour limit, this was pretty comfortable. 

There are tons of cat, and all of them for the most part are pretty well behaved. The patrons on the other hand were not.  I kid you not... there was a grown man who went around annoying all the cats and made the staff take pictures of him posing. It was pretty ridiculous.  He even changed his shirt at one point... in front of me. Annoying and inappropriate but whatever. None of the cats liked him.

Mr. Tommy was my favorite. He was such a little cutie pie.

text:
+Before we begin, It was 10.30pm when I got there. 
The first thing I asked out loud was "Where'z the coffee"

true story.

--------------

This place, when you sit down, you don't just watch people. People watch you.
So when you eat, a good tip is to eat like a lady.

-----------------

I had the chocolate Earl Grey tea. It was damn nice. I loved it. 
It smelled and tasted of chocolate and tea.
The only horrible thing was they only served 1 pot and the cups were too dainty.
Give it to me in a beer mug and a barrel of tea , i SAY!

Food..i had some foie gras salad thing and chicken.
I'm sorry if i can't give you the exact details. 10.30pm was way past my bedtime and they don't seem to serve coffee.

Chicken was meh. it was alright. tasted like chicken. I've had better chicken elsewhere.
I think i had better chicken at a hawker centre.
¯\_(ツ)_/¯

Foie Gras...meeeeh
no opinion. sorry guys

-----
Tea Fantastic
Food Meh
French Waiter Cute but my singaporean accent threw him off

As someone who moved here from New York, I was accustomed to having a nice, crisp, chewy bagel at least 3 times a week. Hence upon moving to Singapore, I scour the island every time my inevitable cravings hit. 

Two Men Bagel is an obvious choice for bagel lovers and you can see from the queue that it's made up of a lot of homesick westerners. 

The bagels are no where near as massive as in New York and it doesn't have that sheen to it, but then again, they don't have the water. The sandwiches are inventive, bordering on too ambitious. Because the bagels themselves aren't that large, the filling often falls out, leaving your hands a mess. 

Like all foreign foods swept far from their homeland, it's more expensive (especially the drinks, my God it's robbery) and not as good, but it's all we have. 

+1 star for the great 90's and 00's rap and hip hop playlist, interrupted only by great 00's emo music.

text:
This place has cool lights and figurines resembling Ultraman. 

That's about it.  Their sandwiches for lunch are bland, at 13 a pop -- stingy with meat or salmon and are dry. Drinks are overpriced. They price a $5 can of boddington ale from coldstorage at $18. They forgot orders. Same experience as prior reviewer that the proprietor does a good job but the other waiters were a disaster. 

They could do so much better if they improved the food quality, expanded the menu, added better beers and wines to their selection, and dropped their current crop of waiters. 

2 out of 5 for food, 4 out of 5 for atmosphere, 1 for service.

Opened by the BreadTalk group, Bread Society is set to be a posher version of the usual breadtalk chain store. While their offerings do look impressive, incorporating european influences with japanese flavours, getting a good bun here is sort of like a lucky draw. While they have interesting flavours, texture of their bread and buns are rather inconsistent. 

I would recommend their chocolate croissants as those are the only products from bread society that has not failed to disappoint time and time again. Their blueberry bread is not bad too but once again, I've had good and bad experiences with it. Their cakes did not impress on the 3 accounts, so if you are looking for quality cakes, go elsewhere.

text:
Seriously, this place has the most amazing ice cream. Move aside, Island creamery! I haven't raved about ice cream in a long time. They also serve ice cream with waffles. Waffles are light and fluffy and freshly made. The flavors are very intense, robust, not too sweet yet creamy. You can really taste the actual flavor in the ice cream!!! And it packs a punch! 

It was so good I had it after lunch and after dinner on the same day. Trust me, you won't be disappointed. 

Flavors I tried that was incredible : pistachio( my favorite!) Ferrero Roche, black sesame, strawberry ( they roast the strawberries before making it for the intense fresh strawberry flavor)! And oh yes, speculoos cheesecake!!! 

Coupled with the clean environment and friendly staff, this is 5 stars without a doubt.

The renovation's to this one are quite appealing, and I could easily spend an afternoon munching my way from stall to stall. I know everyone raves about the satay in this place, but my heat still rest with the little guy serving up roasted pig's feet and pig organ soup, clearly one of the best meals that I've had in Singapore.

text:
I cherry picked my pastries based on visual-appeal. I swept sweet bakes like Vanilla & Raisin Swirl $3.50 & Orange Brioche off the shelve, and the former wins slightly but with low marks. The Danish presented in burnt rims, has a notable buttery flavor but not rich enough to remember. The sweet glaze blend gently with the flaky pastry partnering some scattered candies raisins. I wasn't really impressed with the taste, just mediocre.

The Orange Brioche $5.00, was weaker in taste. It didn't sing any buttery tune like other artisanal brioche, no signs of flakiness and rather dry in its texture. There was a small helping of citrus scented custard piped in the middle of the dough, mildly sweet. The orange fruit slice hindered my chewing - simply aesthetically pleasing on the the sweet bread.

The Madeleine $2.00/pc, was a decent piece. Not exceedingly sweet with a soft interior. I'd prefer it to be served warm like db Moderne Bistro so that I could taste the rich buttery structure in its comforting warmth. This one was left in the open, atop the pastry glass cabinet, side-by-side the Financiers. Obviously, it has been overpriced.

The Kumara & Bleu Tart $6.00/pc, champ the fleet in my whole selection when its rivals failed to compete well. The soft and crumbly tart shell adapted quite well to the sweet orange-pigmented kumara cubes gelled together in a pool of coagulated cheese - buttery rich and very delightful. Noticeable flavor is seen coming from the flaky tart, less from the filling.

The battle field continues to be less interesting when the limping Roast Chicken Sandwich $11.50, hit the ground. The fillet slices were dry and fibrous, no traces of flavor until my taste buds met up with the sweet onion chutney above the fresh lettuce. The hard-like-rock baguette made things worst, it was a total shame!

When I thought nothing will be praised, I was charmed by the healthier fare, $8.50 - Quinoa & Lentil Salads. The power grains are executed in perfection along with a mixture of soft lentil which is often undercooked. Carefully seasoned with the right amount of tang lending from the balsamic reduction and some sweet hints from the fresh apple slices, the rehydrated dried cranberry fruits, the heap of rocket greens woke my taste buds with a striking saltiness from the accompanying shaven Parmesan. Just as the episode starts to climax, I felt a cold gush of water came splashing down - the 2 sesame rolls that served alongside was rockier & rubbery than the earlier baguette! What's happening to the breads here? I let out a heavy sigh!

text: Joe & Dough is a little cafe near one of the entrances to the Square 2 shopping centre. It has a small range of sandwiches rolls and cakes, and offers some hot and cold drinks (teas and coffee etc). I had lunch there recently and the staff were very warm and friendly. Overall the cafe doesn't have a great range of food and the few sandwiches on offer didn't look very appealing. Unfortuently eating my tuna on rye sandwich didn't do anything to change my opinion.

text:
We attended a Yelp Elite brunch event here (for Nik's birthday month!!!) and then life got crazy, so I'm just now writing this review. 

The company, of course, was superb. The food was really good, but the menu was really tough if you're trying to follow the Paleo lifestyle. Hubby order the roasted wagyu rump with ratte potatoes, poached eggs, red onions, chili bearnaise and brioche bun. Because of the quantity of food, he ended up eating the bread to fill up. I got the eggs benedict with poached chicken, spinach, semi-dried tomatoes, and green curry hollandaise sauce. I had them sub the sourdough for more spinach. I left hungry. Again, the food was awesome, but didn't fit Paleo and portions were on the small side, so this place gets a 3.5/5 for me. 

I really did love the setting and the style of food they prepare, and would like to try my luck with their lunch or dinner menu. It's still on my to do list and I promise to update this review once I've given those two menus a shot. 

Ultimately, go. Try. Enjoy. :)

text: This is such a cute cafe!! It was great to come in from the heat to relax with some tea, a.c, and play with rescue cats. It's limited space so get there when you don't see it busy. The food is pricy so we just had the "complimentary" beverage (I understand why the prices are a bit high, though). This was our first (and so far, only) cat cafe visit in Asia. The owners of the cafe are super nice and friendly. I love that all of the cats are rescues. Don't expect the cats to be playful, they were all sleepy (which is why I prefer dogs. But hey, no judgement here)!

text: Toast box is a subchain of the overall bakery - Bread Talk. If you walk around the mall, you will see a lot of bakeries selling various types of asian bread. Toast Box specialize in recreating the ambience of Singpaore in the 70's/80's.  Obviously I am not from the era so I cannot judge if the food is a good representation of that period but overall, I do like the food. Kaya toast is kaya spread & butter sandwiched in two thin slices of toasted white bread. Kaya is a green  or brown paste ( the color depends if yours had panada leaves in it) made out of thicken coconut milk and sugar, reduced into a paste. So yes, it is extremely bad for your health to consume this in huge quantities, especially since it goes together with thick slabs of butter. But, the warm melty goodness is worth it

Relatively new coffee place - right next to Rise & Grind. Korean style 3rd wave / specialty coffee, with the usual range of espresso and manual brewing methods. They also roast in the shop - which accounts for the burnt cookie smell that fills the place from time to time. But what drew me into the store was the huge, white EK43 lurking in the corner that signaled the potential for a good pourover. Peeking behind the counter, portafilters locked tight into the group head are always a good sign of a café that knows its shit. 

Ambience is bright and airy, despite the tight confines of the unit, and the staff are friendly and welcoming. 

So, coffee. It's certainly a step up from the other coffee outlets in the building. They do a tasty cold brew (also done in store), and espresso beverages are well-pulled. 

But of course any self respecting coffeenista will want to know what their hand brew is like. They brew with a Clever at 88 deg C, for about 3 mins. Have tried their Ethiopian and Kenyan beans, and found their hand brew to be a bit over extracted - nonetheless, still tastier than the competition. 

Still, it's early days and I reckon I'll drop by often since its in my patch. Staff were open to my feedback on the grind size, so I'm looking forward to some variety in their pourover.

text:
Breakfast is the most important meal of the day. Sadly, it's a meal most of us go without. The solution? All day breakfast! 

Their meals range from the traditional eggs and bacon to salads to steak sandwiches, and don't forget the coffees. 

The quality of food is pretty decent. All that you would expect from a cozy restaurant located in a higher-end mall.  Oh and if you prefer your toast thick, then you've come to the right place. However, if you can cook a half decent egg on toast, then you might want to give Wild Honey a miss. $20 for eggs on toast isn't my cup of tea.
 Just a heads up. 

Expect to wait at least 15 minutes for a seat if you come on weekends.

There was no way we could resist a visit to a brewery 33 stories above Singapore. The views are most definitely worth the visit. Possibly even better than at MBS, because you get to see the enormous building in all its glory, as well as its surrounds. 

As for the place itself? The beer is expensive and extremely bland. I'd take a Tiger over the offerings here for a fraction of the price. The food is just as bad, if not worse. Super expensive pub-fare, very bland. 

Honestly, all of this is to be expected. This place is all about the wow factor and they are hardly the first restaurant to capitalise on the tourist trade! We enjoyed our visit as a must-stop on our list and were happy to pay for the beer as the price of entry.

text:
Really liked the ambience of the place! Visited on a Tuesday evening & it was busy but not annoyingly loud. It doesn't hurt that the staff were very friendly too! 

Got the fresh tagliatelle & a cup of chai latte- I frankly expected more from the tagliatelle but the chai latte was very enjoyable. A wonderful blend of cream & spice. I'll definitely be back, maybe not for the food, but for that chai latte!

text: The selling point of this waffle place is very obviously the location: it's in close proximity to C.H.I.J., which I guess is where most of its business originates from. The waffles and ice cream are mediocre at best and slightly overpriced. Truth be told, I'd much rather walk down the road to Lorong 1 market where better desert stores await.

text:
This place is without a doubt one of the best brunch places in Singapore. The cafe has a really small and cozy indoor dining area which can be a little claustrophobic at their peak period. But fret not, their outdoor dining area is pretty spacious and being located along Telok Ayer Street, you get to appreciate the well-restored, heritage shop-houses that lined the street as your dining view.

When I'm there, I get my usual Bacon & Egg Sarnie with Tomato Relish with an add-on of Avocado! The combination of all that is just heavenly (I am even thinking about it right now as I'm typing this!). The serving is really generous; if you're a female, you could easily share it with another girlfriend of yours. Some of the other recommended dishes will be the Either the Homemade Granola or Pancakes with Berries, Honey and Greek Yoghurt.

And before I forget, their coffee is fantastic too so don't missed that out! I'm can't wait to go back there again for brunch already. x

text:
a quick visit to DAWN coffee at south bridge road the other day. the space is really small (can accomodate up to 10 pax most?) and they can only seat you when your party is complete. interesting concept for a cafe but totally understandable. 
.
coffee wise, DAWN uses @manhattancoffeeroasters from the netherlands. it's on a sourish spectrum and totally acidic. so you've been warned. the teacakes and cookies are very good and delicious. they're all baked in-house by Jane, who is also the owner of the cafe. Jane was previously with Ronin and then Kurasu for a short stint.  so very happy for her.

text:
I was excited to visit Old Airport Road Hawker Center specifically for "Lor Mee" from the Uber popular stall- - "Xin Mei Xiang Zheng Zong" after watching a segment on YouTube. 

I braved the long queue and waited over an hour to partake in, what I expected to be a bowl of yumminess. Unfortunately, it was a huge disappointment! 

Lor Mee- served with noodles and a generous topping of fish and other ingredients. The gravy was significantly rich and thick with a slightly gelatinous texture and predominantly tasted of fish. It's definitely an acquired taste. Not something I'd get again. 

Despite the rave reviews of Lor Mee, the unsung hero is the Minced Mixed Noodle IMO. Pork dumplings and minced pork swimming in a bowl of wide rice noodles. The broth was light and full of flavors with the fresh herbs adding brightness to this delicious dish. A must try! 

Char Kway Teow noodles and proteins were impeccably cooked with a beautifully smoky charred flavor however, it was well under seasoned and one noted. Perhaps a dash of soy sauce will help lift the flavors a bit or it was an off day for the stall. Overall it wasn't a bad dish. 

Fried prawn and pork rolls were a mixed of sweet and savory flavors. While it wasn't my favorite, it was a nice side dish. 

Curry Chicken and Black Pepper Pork Puffs had a flaky crispy crusts and loaded with herbs and spices. A great snack especially on the go. 

A great tourist destination for food, sweets and beverages on the cheap!

text:
Had a nice breakfast here this morning on the way to meet some friends at Suntec City. At just before 10 AM on a Sunday, the place was virtually empty. 
The coffee was excellent - I had a Long black and it was a tasty cup of Jamaican coffee. It was among the best cups of coffee I have had in Singapore. 
I ordered the bacon and egg sandwich while my wife had the "avocado smash", which appeared to be basically the same thing with fresh avocado. I thought the bacon was excellent and really enjoyed the breakfast sandwich. At about $13 it was pretty reasonable my Singapore standards as well. 
Since we had almost the whole place to ourselves, we got excellent service. There are only about 6 tables indoors but there lots outdoors. Was frankly surprised that no one else was there. 
My only (very minor) complaint was that the is significantly different than the one online (we had scoped it out before heading down). Or kids were really excited about the pancakes only to find out upon arrival that they aren't offered. 
Overall, a simple, quick and tasty stop in Tower Three!

text:
Artisan Boulangerie Co. is a fun cafe style restaurant that offers an interesting blend of drinks and/or quick meals. 

For those of you who know Killiney Road you know that there are a number of coffee houses and cafes in this area. Many of them are outdoor or open air cafes. That's great if you wish to embrace the elements but if you want to sit in air conditioned comfort this is the place for you. 

The food here is as you would expect. They offer numerous bakery items and quick meals like various egg-based dishes for breakfast and salads and sandwiches for later in the day. Of course, they do a great job on their lattes and various other coffee-based drinks.

The seating is nice here. The staff is friendly and helpful. Overall, it is a great place to grab a quick meal or sit back with some coffee, cruise the internet, or talk with friends.

$12 for a decent selection of 2 bottled beers... what's not to love? I had Stella Artois while my friend had Coronas. It was a pretty cool evening so we seated right outside on the pavement next to what is now a walking street, so it's pretty great for people watching.

Had the Chicken Cordon Bleu, surprisingly big portion with 2 sides (I chose mashed potato and pasta salad)  and fairly decent tasting as well. My friend adores the tictactoe fries (waffle fries really) which are pretty crispy.

Decent spot it you're looking for an affordable night out!

Ambient is good, foods not bad, was quite impressed by the 'Scallop and Parma Ham' presentation.

However, everything got turned down by the lousy service! A staff would rather clean the table instead of taking our order, we have been waiving our hands but no one could be bother to attend to us. Ice cream was served with no spoon, when we were trying to get one from the waiter who was walking pass us, he pretended did not notice and just walked away. 

I always believe good foods matter, and good service matters more. Hope they will really look into this issue.

text:
I came in yesterday to buy a cake since I heard the original owner is retiring. 

Cash Only.

You need to order this at least a week in advance, and I think they are getting more and more backlogged so now that wait is up to 10 days. 

I ended up with some remnant cake that they had - some kind of walnut, chocolate, raisin, date cake. I absolutely did not want it, but since I just walked from Farrer Park station in the sweltering heat, I was leaving Lana's with a cake either eay - I would have paid someone else walking out of the door, even.

My date cake was absolutely awesome and delicious - it was so smooth and just the right amount of everything - 5 stars all the way. 

What was not five stars was the lady's attitude who worked there. It was ATROCIOUS. So high and mighty she is, selling cakes, that she cannot even be bothered to answer questions. Let alone, listen to them. You can sell five star stuff but if you do not have a shred of decency you don't deserve five stars. 

Others who have reviewed have talked about their terrible attitude going way back a few years. I can imagine that this was not a one-off thing or the recipient of someone's bad day. It is ingrained.

Now that Tiny Roasters has moved into my neighborhood, it's so much more convenient to get a good caffeine fix! Also, gone are the worries that I'd go hungry if I don't eat before going for a coffee - they are surrounded by amazing foods! 

The space has also expanded - there's plenty of seating now, so you don't have to worry about the lack of space!

text:
"I bought some rich and good cake."

'Oh really? Where did you get them from?'

"Rich and good."

'Stop kidding me! Just where did you get them from???'

#truestory

For the unfamiliar, you would probably not know Rich & Good Cakes, which is tucked along one of the streets near Arab Street. It's a swiss-roll cake speciality shop, that sells nothing but swiss-roll cakes. As good as the signboard says! 'Rich & Good' ;)  I love both the durian and kaya ones. Best and fresh!

text: First let me say that I am not quite on board with Australian coffee culture.  I was just learning about americanos and now I have to tackle flat whites? Give me a couple months to catch up.  Aside from that little jargon on the menu this place is an acceptable chain coffee shop.  I only frequent here because of its proximity to my husbands office and I go with my standard latte.  One time I tried to order a iced chai latte and it was the worst coffee experience in Singapore.  The barista should have warned me. It tasted like drinking cold pepper and still leaves a bad taste in my mouth for Dimbulah. Stick to your usual.

text: I went here on Easter Sunday with a couple friends and enjoyed the food and atmosphere quite a bit. It's set in a park, so it was exactly the kind of place that you'd want to go for a cute brunch. We got pancakes (I got the plain and my friends got chocolate chip) and they were delicious and fluffy. I got scrambled eggs on the side and felt that they could have had a bit more flavor (nothing a little extra salt can't fix), but my friend got eggs Benedict and really liked those. I would recommend going here because it was a really cute place and wasn't too expensive, with pretty good food for both breakfast and lunch.

text: This is one of our favorite lunch places. Great atmosphere, great good. Friendly service. Always busy. We had the awesome sandwich, which is like a tasting platter af smaller sandwiches. Highly recommend. The vegeterian awesome salad was very good. We had the drinkable idea. We are not a huge fan of coconut water but you get to keep the the light bulb. Go here. You won't be disappointed.

Live band music with both English and Chinese songs.
We didn't need to make a reservation on a Friday night so kudos to that. Do check out their Fb page for opening days as certain days may be booked for events or so.

Overall the location of the place is excellent at Bugis+ and they have a smoking area outside as well.

Typically you get tapas bites and 1 for 1 offers, great for big groups and intimate gathering for beers! Had their luncheon meat fries and they were fried beautifully with a serving of nancho cheese chips.

They have dart machines in the bar as well so dart fanatics, dart your night away.

For fellow Yelpers and Yelp Elites, do write a review and get a free luncheon meat fries on ur next visit. Do check with the staff on this promotion!

Located at void deck next to b1 lift lobby. Compare to the smoky & stuffy food stalks at roof top, I prefer to have my morning coffee and toast here.

text:
For those of you living in Kovan, you got lucky! Lola's Café has only been around for about 3 months, it surely added more liveliness to the area. This vintage café is also easily accessible - it takes you less than 5 minutes to walk from Kovan MRT (the exit opposite Heartland Mall).

This café is set up by 2 young entrepreneurs, Choo Kiat and June. Besides being the boss, Choo Kiat is the chef cum barista. On the other hand, June is responsible for the pastries that you see in the café. By the way, 'Lola' is actually June's middle name.

This small and quaint café is filled with a variety of vintage furniture and mood lightings. I was particularly attracted to their tables - they are all made from our traditional sewing machines! Furthermore, most of the vintage furniture here are for sale - Do check them out if you'll like to add a bit of character to your room! 

The most unique part of the cafe is their beer menu consists of a good variety of carefully drafted beers from boutique breweries in US, UK and Belgium. 

I went for their Matcha Latte which costs $5.00. The latte was pretty smooth and had a sweet aftertaste. It's a little sweeter over here compared to other cafes, you might want to ask for less sugar. I also tried their Banana Earl Grey Tart ($4.00) which is one of their specialties. It's topped with a layer of sugar and pistachio nuts which tastes very crunchy. The Earl Grey paste was a little too moist though.

My favourite was their Wasabi White Chocolate Mousse ($7.00). Never would I have expected wasabi to go well with white chocolate! An exotic mix of ingredients, it's a surprising recipe and very delicious! Don't worry about the spiciness of the wasabi; it's very gentle and not too overwhelming. The sweetness of the white chocolate complements the overall taste and it melts in your mouth! It's so unique I can't describe it with words. You have to try it for yourself!

Lola's cafe is very conducive for reading and for studying. You could also reward yourselves with some savoury desserts while working your brain cells! It's also a good place to hang out with your friends in the late evenings over some beer and honey wings. Service was great, staff were all very friendly. I will certainly come back again to try out their brunch and beers!

P.S: This cafe is free of GST and Service Charge!

text: Chic japanese themed cafe located in Millenia Walk. Not a typical place that I would head to for a cup of cuppa. Heard and saw pictures of the 3d latte art totally made me want to check it out myself. Coffee beans are from local roastery Liberty Coffee was definitely a plus! Be sure to try out the desserts from the Cordon Bleu pastry chef Gwen Lim who has apparently worked under Pierre Herme himself! Pretty Awesome!

Warning: Don't come on weekends. Menu is limited. This not available, that not available... also weird tables. They have this bench table but the seats are too low with the table top or my body is too short. I'm 5' 8" and the table is almost at my chest level, I feel like I'm in a hospital, with the  table too near you. 

The dishes were ok, we had eggs and toast and a sausage. 

Filled my tummy and that's good, but the service and furniture needs to be improved.

Latest Update 21 Nov 16: I got a message thanking me for the feedback that I gave (above). What really surprised me was that the business owner actually took the time to update me on the changes that they have done since my review. 

This shows that they are very positive in taking negative feedback and changing it to suit their customers. 

I salute your management style. Keep up the good work!

text:
This review is long overdue, especially given my below average experience.

Let's start with the good...
1. The space is great and you can't deny the wow factor as soon as you walk in the door
2. The coffee is decent

Ok now on to my experience... firstly, this place is pricey. Think Sydney prices, which would be acceptable if we lived in Sydney (and even then I don't think the food is of the same quality). Secondly, I ordered a takeaway flat white here once before, but I may as well have sat in because no one served me until I looked for a waitress (there were people behind the counter but completely distracted) and then it took 15 minutes for a take away coffee? What the.

I could have let this all go IF I'd had a good food experience.

But I didn't.

One hungover Sunday I thought the burger would be a good idea. It was actually a very bad idea given the burger that turned up on my plate was RAW. Not rare, but raw. I sliced through the middle of my burger, super excited to have that first big messy bite but the inside was cold and, I'll say it again, raw. I had to fight a reflex retch motion... 

Slightly embarassed (as was dining with 'new friends'), I waved down a waiter who took it back to the kitchen to be re-cooked (no apology?). In the meantime, my dining companions all finished their meals, I filled up on the fries, and I then had to conspicuously eat my returned burger (where both halves of the meat patty had been recooked and reserved) in front of everyone... my appetite was well and truly over and  I wouldn't have even finished half of it - not an ideal outcome especially given the burger is a steep $28!

When paying the bill, I was asked how the meal was? Of course I gave my opinion (tactfully of course) but was told the burger is usually served medium... if that was the case, why was I not given a refund? With juice and coffee, the bill added up to $44 per person (insert "whistle noise" here). 

OK rant over, I'll just vote with my feet next time and suggest elsewhere.

text:
Ok, so most of the stalls start shutting down around 8:30, despite that yelp says it stays open until 11:00. I was so impressed with the food and disappointed that the stalls were closed, I went twice :)

Chicken rice. Steamed pork buns. Pho. Young coconut. dim sum for days. 

Would go again in a heart beat.

One of the oldest gay bars in the Gay Stretch, I've been coming here for.. a decade? It hasn't changed very much. It's still full of white boys and the azn boys who love them. But the $10 drinks really help, no matter your gender -- or orientation.

The shophouse it's in is quite homey, if you can indeed call a gay bar homey. Most nights it's the same: a place you go to repeatedly if you're a regular. On special nights like on Pink Dot nights, it's packed silly to the brim.

One of the standards. Can't recommend it excessively, can't say anything too bad about it either.

And the choice of music is superb! I could read, write or have a decent conversation without having to raise my voice. 
I'll definitely be back again!

text:
I have been to this place a couple of times and they have never disappoint me with one of the best zhi char dishes. 

Their specialty is the Mongolian pork rib which is heavenly. The ribs are not cut into small cubes and there are still huge chunks of meat stuck to it. Perhaps it's not favourable for dainty ladies that will be paiseh to hold up the bones and rip the meat off; I have no qualms for that =D  The ribs has a very unique taste; creamy, peppery and there's a hint of mint. The sauce is very appetising and I can finish my whole of rice just with the sauce alone. The rib if always cooked till tender but not too soft till it just falls off the bone. 

Another house special will be the signature tofu. If I guess it correctly, it's normal tofu smashed with other condiments like onions+ carrot + minced meat, then being re-shaped into a cube and deep fried. Sounds like a perfectly simple dish yet tastes awesome. They are served with some fresh cabbage and mayo on the side. 

The rib and tofu is my "must-order" dishes. Other common zhi char dishes are very good too; sambal kangkong, fu rong egg, pai gu wang. 

The next time you are around Bugis but looking for a non-shopping-mall-food-chain-place, you should definitely try 3838. Highly recommended!

Great ambiance and decent coffee however we were not at all impressed with the pastries / cakes we ordered. Blueberry cake was overloaded with sugar it was all you can taste. Too bad the food wasn't better because it is a nice venue to hang out for awhile

I had the best tiramisu in Rome that was perfect and home made in an old little restaurant so I was looking for singapore's own best. 

This was it. In an understated cafe in Clarke quay's The Central mall. 

A bit hard to find but I managed to do it without a sweat. 

The classic tiramisu is your best bet. Perfectly moist and not too sweet, light on the palette but just the right amount of cream.

I didn't really enjoy the matcha version as it was too bitter for me, though pure matcha lovers might enjoy it.

Honestly, I felt the price was okay and justifiable plus the size of the cake just nice to satisfy, especially since Starbucks is able to get away with selling their subpar cakes for the same price. 

Would return again!

text:
Charsiew, Roast Pork, and Soya Sauced Chicken. The holy trinity in which these aunties and uncles have perfected long before I was born. Get it with plain rice, or (wanton) noodles. 

I popped by one afternoon and ordered Char Siew rice but settled for Siu Yok Fan when the cheery uncle said Char Siew was sold out. 5 mins later this elderly man comes strutting down and orders Char Siew and he gets it. Felt like I was at the door of Le Bain in NYC all over again. 

But you know, these guys, they do what they do, and they do it well. Not a huge fan of the vinegary chilli sauce, might help to ask for some sambal instead.

Best pulled pork burger we've had, followed by The 1925 Microbrewery.  
Their brunch is based on bagels and sous vide-d eggs which comes out perfect!  

Great ambience plus most definitely nicest looking pastries and cakes.  

My new goto brunch place for a slow relaxing day on the weekends.

text:
It's a butchery and a diner to satisfy your meat craving any time in the day (not night)!

I find that it's a little low profile on the shop front, which might mislead some passerby to imagine it as just another meat store. However, they have an interesting concept here!

In the store, you can choose the type of meat you'd like to go for, and the expert will do the cut and serve it hot for dine in with a extra handling fee of $8 which comes with 2 side dishes. The people in store definitely know their stuff, so I can trust them on the food delivered. You can also purchase wine and other beverages here. For lunch, they serve gourmet sandwiches as well with coffee/tea. Desserts are also available in their fridge.

First visit and I had an Aussie 90 days grainfed ribeye stinky $4/100g!!! DAMN SHIOK AH. I returned subsequently a couple of times to bring my colleagues for meals too. Go early for lunch as there's really limited seats inside (just 1 counter top if I remember correctly).

So yes, this is a also a fresh meat supplier store. For days when we require meat for parties, I'll get the whole slab of good quality meat back home to serve. The price is reasonable and you can be guaranteed on the quality! The frozen section sells frozen USDA meat and seafood as well, which I rarely check them out.

Give me quality meat at low cost and I'm a happy customer!!

After visiting the Botanic Gardens, we were looking for a place to sit and drink / eat something small. 
This place was just across the street and had still one small table left outside. 
Their was no menu, you had to go inside to look at the big board, order and afterwards they would bring your things to your table. 
It was 6pm and there was not a lot left anymore of the sweets (like we saw on the pictures here on Yelp), but there were still many pizza slices. We went for the vegi slice (7,5S$). It was served hot, with a wide variety of vegetables, but unfortunately the pizza was somewhat dry. Therefore only 3 stars, but it could have been more.

Ambiance and staff is above average. 

Located at the strip of restaurants of Maple Tree Business City, this starbucks is also easily accessible through the connecting bridge with ARC mall / PSA building. 
Starbucks is one of the few places to open up at 7:30 AM at MBC making it the perfect place for breakfast if you have to come in early. Between 8-8:45AM and 1-2PM there is a small queue, which increases the waiting time to around 7-10 minutes. You never to have to worry about finding a seat. 

They also serve "Jo to Go", a big carton with 15 cups of coffee inside, good for department events. 

Mon - Fri : 0730 - 1900 hrs, Sat. Sun & PH : CLOSED
