text:
After visiting a few hawker centers, this one is definitely one of my favorites. Conveniently located in Chinatown, this is a great place to stop by for a bite to eat after you're done with souvenir shopping / exploration in Chinatown. For the food, simply go to the second floor, and bam! You'll be greeted with food stalls upon food stalls and the delicious smell of various food wafting around.

As a tourist, I was pretty overwhelmed at what to eat and where to start. My suggestion to anyone who hasn't been to a hawker center before is to walk around first and observe the food prior to just jumping to a stall and ordering right away. Since the place was quite big, it did take some time for my friends and me to explore the different food stalls and making mental notes at which ones we wanted to try. Best plan when traveling with a group of people is to pick a general eating spot, split up, get whatever food you desire, and regroup at the eating area. The eating area itself is scattered around with tables and chairs. 

For the food stalls, there was a huge variety that ranged from only fresh fruit smoothies / drinks to various cuisines like Chinese, Indian, Singaporean, Indonesian and etc. If you need food suggestions, simply go line up for food stalls that have huge lines. Most likely, these food stalls are either popular with locals/tourists, or the food is pretty cheap and tasty. I used this tactic and ended up with delicious food that I at first, had no idea what I was eating. 

For food here, I highly recommend lining up for the Food Street Fried Kway Teow Mee. Simply put, it's noodles mixed with a spicy like sauce, seafood like taste and such. Not sure what else goes into it, but it is one tasty dish!! To find this stall, look for a long line (or at my picture). The wait is definitely worth it and it's cool to see the chef in action on making your meal. As for drinks, pretty much most of the drinks stalls have similar prices (price average around $1-3). As for another random dish I tried, the green bean rice dumping at the Jia Ji Mei Shi food stall was amazingly good. With its sticky rice texture on the outside, and the green bean taste mixed in with the meat and rice......man, this was so yummy and at the same, mad filling on the tummy. If you do order this dish, I highly recommend getting the sweet and spicy chili sauce with it. So good. 

Overall, prices for most food stalls is pretty cheap (with a few exceptions on higher end seafood dishes) and you do get the option of picking your portion sizes that range from small to large. I spent roughly $5 that landed me 2 food items + 2 drinks and that alone made me go into a food coma. Make sure you bring cash since most places don't take credit cards.

After eating, I recommend checking out the first floor where it's like a mini clothing market that sells various clothes and small trinkets :)

text:
This is the only 24 hour Indian Muslim food stall in Balestier; the rest of the late-night food options are predominated by Bak Kut Teh and other more Chinese-styled food options. 

However, whilst I do have a hankering for prata from time to time, this really isn't the best place for it. Despite being open for 24 hours, they tend to run out of curries before the night is over. I love my fish curry, and egg prata with dhal just doesn't taste the same! 

The maggie goreng is not bad, but it can sometimes be overcooked. 

In short, not a great place for prata after-hours, but for those living in Balestier, this is your only choice.

Pancakes: $18.00 SGD', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pancakes: $18.00 SGD'}]
text:
So long as Clinton Street Baking Company continues to dish up the best pancakes I've ever had in my life be they in New York City, Tokyo, or Singapore, I'll continue to give them five stars.

Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?

This Clinton Street is a cute little one comparable to their Tokyo location, and while it lacked the natural light conducive to food photography (I know I know I'm sorry for even pointing that out), the service was fast and friendly. Star. 

Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?

$19.00 for brioche french toast was pricey, but very much on par with other spots catering to tourists and expats like Clinton Street and Common Man. Star. 

Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?

Clinton Street continues to dish up the best pancakes in the world - seriously. I don't know how they do it and especially how they maintain consistency internationally, but these fluffy cakes of goodness are so flavorful and go so well with the blueberries and maple butter syrup that it's just impossible to compete. Two Stars. 

Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?

Always. Star.

text:
We were looking for more Thai Milk Tea after our trip to Thailand and we heard about Tuk Tuk Cha. 

Their Thai Milk tea is pretty authentic! It was a little too much on the sweet side for me, but you can customize how much sweetness/ice you want when you order.

text:
Great concept and ambience, so-so value for money and limited menu. 

The idea of farm to table is what drew me to this place but I doubt if even 10% of the food served come from their farm. 

Brunch for 2 on a sunday: buttermilk pancakes, ocean trout crepe, Caesar salad (shared) and lemon tart with basil ice cream (shared). Total bill 110 sgd. Pricey, and that's without any drinks at all.

The food was ok in general. I recommend the lemon tart, with delicious basil ice cream. The ocean trout crepe was good, with quality ingredients. Pancakes were so-so. Caesar salad serving style was novel but taste was average.

text: Had the Rootbeer Float, Chocolate Waffles and a Chocolate Tart..forgive for not remembering the exact name..but the chocolate from the tart was HEAVENLY! It was just oozing out and we ended up dipping that with the waffle instead of the Earl Grey ice cream we ordered. Noms! Definitely coming back for more.
My fav is the Avo Baco bagel. It fills me up all the way til early dinner. It's a little hard to find, but once you find it, try it, you will keep coming back for more. Great bagels in cbd.

Love the yatsura - hazelnut praline cake. It's light but it hits the spot! :)
The cheesecake was good too.

text:
I was surprised at how good the cappuccino was. I did not expect that as it was fairly empty when I was there on a Saturday morning. Maybe it was the weekend. There was a promotion for a cake and coffee set. 

So I also had the ondeh gula melaka cake which was delicious. The cake was moist and soft and full of gula melaka goodness. 

The only drawback was the fact that they do not serve water at all. I mean, sometimes you do want water to wash down the cake and coffee, just like you need water after ice cream. 

I solved the problem by buying bottled water from Guardian Pharmacy which was across from it.

text:
I've been to this place a few times and what I have to say will mostly be about the beer and the views. 

First off, if you're planning a visit here for a meal, do yourselves a favor and book a reservation beforehand. If you love eating outside and beautiful views of Singapore; make sure that reservation is outside. The views at this place are spectacular! Some of the best in the city. Now, the food is in my honest opinion, nothing to write home about. I've had a few different things off the menu and nothing ever knocked me off my feet. Last night, my wife took me here for my birthday dinner, I had the truffle linguine, she had the brewery burger. For sides we shared the roasted potatoes and the mushroom dish. The potatoes were cooked well, but were mostly bland and flavorless. The mushrooms had some taste, but still quite bland for my tastebuds. The linguine was excellent, a perfect portion that paired well with my IPA. Do not forget that this place is a Brewery, so have a beer. Leave the wine for other restaurants! The IPA was so great I had 2. I'm a huge IPA fan, but you can follow my reviews on Untappd, not on Yelp. 

All in all, the restaurant gets a 3 for food and a 5 for the views and the atmosphere.

text:
Although I think you have to catch this place on the right day when the weather is not so stifling, but after living in Singapore for a year now, my husband and I think this might be our personal most favorite hawker center to have visited (and we tend to visit a lot!).  

Why does it get high marks from the Nings?  Cleanliness, community feel and flow of space.  

The place is super clean and seems cleaner than any other hawker center we have been too.  It is off the beaten path a bit from touristy spots and has that community feel to it (although easily reached via subway and then a 5-10 minute walk).  The center area of the hawker center is open and thus a bit more breezy, if you are lucky to have a day that is breezy.  

When we were here a few weeks ago, we enjoyed many dishes, but the Laksa at stall #50 was my personal favorite.  We both commented that this would be the hawker center we would bring future visitors too, for the cleanliness and flow make it a nicer experience for the uninitiated to absorb.

text:
We went for dinner after reading amazing reviews about Violet Oon. It surpassed our expectations with regard to the food, decor and service. 
The restaurant is very charming and the servers are helpful and Oh so precise when they set the table :) 
The food is delicious - we had a chicken appetizer and a prawn+turnip filled in a cup thing. Both were delicious. Followed this with chicken curry and vegetarian meatballs - both divine. The highlight of the meal were their cakes gula melaka n sugee. 
We absolutely loved everything about the restaurant and will be back to try more dishes :)

text:
On the main level of Tanglin Mall, Caffe Beviamo is always jam packed with mainly expats from morning tea onwards into late afternoon. Very simple straight forward café food here, nothing really inspiring or funky on the menu, just comforting café classics like bruschetta, sandwiches, bolognaise pasta etc. 

They also have a wide selection of cakes, cookies and other nibbley bits. Has an Australian influence throughout the menu, lamingtons, rocky road etc. This is great for someone like me that misses home from time to time, though a lamington that isn't filled with jam and cream!!! That just cannot be!, as an aussie in my book it should be a criminal offence to do a lamington which isn't wedged with both jam and cream, saying that though it is a pretty decent piece of cake. Service while not the most knowledgeable is always cheerful and helpful. Good place for a cheap comforting lunch.

text:
Nestled by the millennium pool on the roof of Marina Bay Sands is Chocolate Bar, an all-you-can-eat dessert bar. Yes, you heard me right -- all-you-can-eat.  I totally understand that I'm playing the tourist when I come here. But you know what, I do it anyway. I think it would also be a great place to bring out-of-town guests. 

They open at 8pm, making it sound like a dessert place, but don't be fooled. Here's some advice. Don't eat dinner! Come hungry so you can try all the different cakes, cookies, fondue, tarts, ice cream, hot chocolate and more that they have to offer. Trust me, if you eat anything before you come, you're just not going to make it through. 

The dessert here is very good. I'm not going to say that it's amazing or mind-blowing, because it's not. But it's very good. There is a passionfruit and chocolate cake there that I'm crazy about though. Not everything is pure chocolate. Everything does has something chocolate in it though, even if it's just garnish. So there are many fruity things, light things, and very different things. This actually makes it nice because, realistically, how much chocolate could you really eat? There are so many choices of dessert, good luck trying everything. Don't miss the fondue with the homemade marshmallows. 

Coffee and hot chocolate is included and you can pay for cocktails. 

Unfortunately, there are no tables in this place that has a view off the front of the hotel. There is outdoor seating, but it faces the back, and so not over the city, Marina Bay and the pool. But, being able to get up to the pool is pretty great. And you should definitely walk around up there before or after your sugar overdose. Don't tell the staff at the restaurant that though, because they will tell you that you have to straight back down, and that walking around is not allowed -- just do it, and no one will bother you.

text:
The first time I was here on a weekday during lunch hour, my eyes were glued on the katsu and curry don (on the lunch menu) so I decided to try it out.

The food was served within 15 minutes of waiting. The katsu was cooled down when served. Texture wise, it is as crunchy and tender as it looks but would prefer it to be served warmer. The curry had potatoes and beef in it and as I was pouring on my don (rice), it still had the steaming effect. For the lunch set, it will come with salad and a small slice of watermelon. For this dish, I would gladly give a 4 stars.

The second time visiting this place was on a Saturday during tea break (around 2pm). Decided to give the Yuzu Snow cake a try. The Yuzu was strong and the jelly square bits on the top made it more chewy. According to my friend, it was refreshing.

I also managed to take a spoonful of my friend's matcha cake. There were too much cream in the middle that the taste of matcha was rather mild. It was soft and light. But for a friend with little tolerance of sweet desserts, she claimed that it was just right for her tastebuds.

Ambience here is pretty cosy. Depending on the crowd, you can chose an indoor or outdoor (open space) seatings. I prefer the outdoor seating as you can see how they drip the coffees too and also good spot to observe people.

Price wise, I think it is on the pricier end. But I did enjoy my dish that I got on the first visit. Will drop by to fulfill my curry and katsu cravings in the near future :)

text:
back here again wanting to try e eclair but alas! I was distracted with e pastries and ordered a chocolate gnut instead.

1. Flat white - good coffee but nope I still didn't get my 3D coffee art. sigh

2. chocolate gnut - $4 - price is kinda steep for a mini bite size pastry. I have no idea what it is but it kinda tasted like a mini donut hybrid with croissant (cronut) good amount of chocolate cream with every bite but e price ... e price... e price $$$$$

3. ham + cheese croissant - $5 this was just OK, wished it came warm but it was kinda cold when i had it.

I srsly have to try that eclair next time - looks nomilicious

text:
Believe it or not, I was dragged here by my Swedish boyfriend because he saw the word "fika" along with a picture of Moose outside the cafe. Yes, as you might have guessed it, it's a "Swedish" cafe, right in the Kampong Glam area in Singapore.

How Swedish can it be? Well the decor inside is very Ikea-ish and they do have a lot of Swedish dishes like meatballs (halal, obviously), pytt i panna and many other dishes that were on the menu. Since we weren't feeling like eating Swedish dishes in Singapore (hello, laksa!), we came here just to get refreshments and shade from the harsh Singaporean sun.

Boyfriend ordered (Swedish) coffee while I got myself a lingonberry-ade that was surprisingly fresh and nice (a little bit sour). We shared an earl gray cake, although there was prinsesstårta in the cake shelf.  

Overall, it's a nice ambiance, maybe for Singaporeans who want to try out Swedish stuff, or for the Swedes who miss food from home, but as for me, it's just another concept cafe that is currently trending in Southeast Asia

text:
I actually only came here because my hostel (Royal Hostel) had a breakfast deal with them. The line at 8am was fairly long though which suggests good things - line also moved fairly fast.

I got the lo mai gai - or sticky rice chicken. Usually a dim sum item, steamed while wrapped in a lotus leaf. There was no lotus leaf here, but it was actually pretty tasty overall. It did lack the characteristic leaf flavor but the rice was cooked very well and the sauce had a terrific depth of meatiness and savoriness. I would recommend it.

text: We stopped for a quick lunch - very nice ambience next to the riverside. While the chicken Milanese wrap was good, the pan seared salmon was just average..if you want a late lunch/brunch with a good view, you may consider this..

Agree that portions are a bit small. Enough for me but I don't eat all that much (or so I think!) anyway, popped in ard 830 on a Friday night after work, it filled up pretty quickly. Thought it'd be a nice quiet cafe but boy was I wrong! Decor is nice and all, but the chatter quickly magnifies too.. I was somewhat assailed by all the noise.

My pan fried salmon took 20mins to come. And when it did, I was first wowed by the crispness of the salmon, but not so much the texture inside. It was a little overdone/dry and the sauce wasn't sufficient to save it. 

That being said, it seems that the potatoes were more the saving grace. Nicely roasted and herbed, very comforting and deliciously savoury!

Yep... Official... This place just changed my life with only one bagel!! Do yourself a favor and try something!

this place has got style, flavor fusion and makes me so happen when i get one of these.  while the calorie count is not great, it is totally worth it!

i cant wait to get back and try more of their crazy flavors!

Pretty much any food you could ever want for cheap prices. However a number of vendors were closed on a Sunday afternoon which limited choice and atmosphere. It's gritty for Singapore and it's hot... but definitely worth the trip!

There are a number of Michelin star places here for very cheap.

text:
I had this a few years ago in New York. Unfortunately it was after a visit to Katz (and if you've seen the size of their pastrami sandwiches you'd know how stuffed I was at that time) so all I had was the bacon and it didn't leave much of an impression then.

FAST FORWARD TO 5 YEARS LATER! And Clinton Street Baking Co is now in SUNNY (hazy) SINGAPORE!

They don't take reservations, and we were here on a sunday morning, and the queue was 1.5 hours. By the time it was our turn to be seated it was 2 hours. Be warned that the queue is deceptively short because everyone just gives their handphone number and goes away while waiting. There are some red benches to sit on outside the shop but it could fit a maximum of 8 people. 2 yummy mummy-types tried to cut the queue ("why don't we tell them that we have a baby?"). To which I said. "IS THE BABY GOING TO BE EATING THE FOOD HERE???")

My question was answered when I made the mistake of ordering the cheese grits. A mush in a plate, it tasted as good as it looked. Which was not at all. I'd rather some mashed potatoes. Even the powdered ones that you get from 7-11.

Other sides were good but not impressive. We had the southern chicken (skin was yums), the scrambled eggs with salmon (not baaaaad), and some farmer's platter. Like, good but I wouldn't wait more than 30 minutes for them.

BUT THE STANDOUT WERE THE PANCAKES. 3 flavors - blueberry, banana, chocolate - to choose from. You can add 1 more flavour for $2. Same pancakes, different toppings. These were nice and fluffy and thick yet light. I think the only other place in Singapore that comes close so far is Skyve. If you put the pancakes from those 2 places together and made me choose 1, I don't know which would win. But maybe Clinton Street because of that wonderful maple syrup/butter mix, which married the taste of maple syrup with the smoothness of melted butter.

Come here! Unless you're a yummy mummy with a baby trying to cut the queue -_-"

text: A small little place nestled inside a mall in Tanjong Pagar, offers a verity of bags. Usually very packed around noon - lunch time, good to go there a little earlier, excellent lox bagel and walnut cream cheese bagel as well.

Started with a couple of great Cosmopolitan's... :-)

Meatless meatballs (parmesan and walnut) appetizer was absolutely delicious... as were the Spanish mackerel and black diamond pasta (which was REALLY good) mains...

We were tempted by dessert and were not disappointed... the sticky toffee pudding was fab... the tapioca cake was pretty good too... they were heavy desserts and we probably did not need 2 ;-)

Definitely a recommend - would love to come back, but just a few days left in Singapore with so much more to do :-)

Came here for the salted egg croissant. They warm it up for you, but it doesn't ooze out like liu sha bao because it's not that type of salted egg. It reminds me strongly of the salted egg yolk that resides in traditional mooncakes, which is ok if you're a fan of that, but I happen not to like that. I have to give it credit for the texture of the croissant, which is deliciously flaky, fluffy and crunchy without being overly oily.

I love the concept at Froth, the menu items are interesting, and makes you want to try every one of them. The dishes, unfortunately, are a hit or miss. Some are really very good, like the seafood tom yum risotto, the slipper lobster sandwich and the waffles, especially with the salted caramel ice cream. The tom yum flavor blended surprisingly well with the creaminess of the risotto, and the generous portion of lobster with mentaiko was decadent and tasty. Others, just lack a little bit of flavor or oomph. The bacon chowder and seafood broth is chock full of flavor, but the consistency of the chowder is  a little chalky, and the sous vide salmon in the broth is a little too briny for my liking. The matcha rice with beef was disappointing, with meagre serving of beef which was too dry despite being one of the more expensive items on the menu ($30.90). The prawn aglio olio and carbonara lack flavor as a whole, and the sweet corn risotto was a tad too sweet, which was the same issue with the chilli crab spaghetti. 4 stars if you are wise with what you pick, 2 stars if you are not.

text:
Popped by here on a Saturday noon for brunch, and the nicer interior was all reserved so we had to sit outside (2 people), so it would be prudent to call ahead at peak times. 

I had the fish tacos and a hot chocolate with soy milk. My companion had the big breakfast and a cappuccino. My fish tacos came with salad and curly fries, which I really liked, and wiped out. The tacos themselves were okay, with fish and a mango salsa, and a very crunchy taco. I do wish they had a cream element within to balance the flavors, but all in all, I wasn't disappointed. My hot choc wasn't overly sweet, and still frothy despite the soy. Yum. 

While the prices are on the high side because of its location, it is still cheaper than it's upstairs neighbor, and offers non-brekkie options for you! 

I didn't get any coffee because I don't drink coffee - but I've heard it's good!

text: My daughter insisted I try this place. I had ricotta pancakes with caramelized bananas and espresso butter. I added the sausage. It was good. The cruffins- cross between croissants and muffin - unusual with somewhat flaky bread like texture. Quite good but personally I prefer the cronut texture.

text: Coffee here is on point! Brunch is great, my favourite on their menu is the crab cake. Smoothies are also delicious, banana chocolate is a must try. Friendly staff and lovely ambience. Outdoor seating in the garden is really refreshing.

text:
A new cafe located in Macpherson area that is welcoming with a very minimalist look to their interior design. Went on a Friday and surprisingly full in the late night. 

Many were here for the pretty rainbow cakes with assorted creams. Today is the oreo and salted caramel cream. The former is a little dry and the latter a bit too caramel sweet. But its a decent rainbow cake. not overly creamy and the colors of the layers are impressively bright. Not the best rainbow cake I ate (as of now i have tried like A LOT of them) but its up there with a couple of my faves.

Savories - sweet potato fries were well done. could have a little more powdered sugar. Truffle Parmesan Fries - alright. The half and half pizza is served in its rectangular form and the crust is thin and filled with herbs (think foccacia bread). an interesting take with the pepperoni and mushroom
with arugula. Overall not a bad pizza. The crust saved the dish.

Drinks - as a coffee and chocolate lover I went for the latte which is small and decent (my girlies beg to differ, so you guys try it and let me know). I was attracted to the chocolate drinks especially with african red hot chocolate and chilli hot chocolate in the list. so we ordered them. THEY WERE NOT HOT. Lukewarm at best. *sad face. But the chilli chocolate had that spicy punch after a sip. so that was the saving grace of that. The african red chocolate had nothing to rescue it from its sad lukewarm (and by now cold) state. *sigh

 The service staff are friendly and one was really honest to let me and my girlies know it was her first day. Not very proactive but attentive when called. So overall not bad. a very young team of girls.

For an estate like Macpherson to have such a cafe really brings a twist to the feel of the place. Will come back again to try the other things like their mains, all day breakkies (weekends only hor) and their non cake desserts. Oh they have interesting cheesecakes too. 

Overall a very good cafe with quality food and a passionate service team. Come here before it gets popular!

When you're craving for some American style Chinese comfort food and a flight to Australia for the next best thing is not in the cards, get your fix at Chop Suey, but prepare to pay up what the food you remember from back home in the US.

High end service, well executed food and prices to match.

Our favorite dish was the Crispy Orange Beef featuring tender strips of beef fried nicely and coated with orange flavored glaze.

The Wok Breath Rice Noodle was nice as well as the sticky crunchy baby squid.

Cocktails were tasty with appealing Asian accents, especially the Hot Lychee Margarita.

PARTING THOUGHT: sooner or later we'll save enough room to finally try the desserts!

You'd never expect a cafe to be located in a kitchen appliance showroom, but yes, it's here in an industrial building a short walk away from Paya Lebar MRT.

I'm here for the coffee (double shot, of course) and occasionally the lunch items. Good choices are the Yakiniku Beef Striploin Rice Bowl, Grilled Salmon or Chicken at wallet friendly prices. They offer pastry and bakery items as well.

Been a regular customer since they opened in 2018 but the crowd has since picked up and it gets a little noisy inside. It is recommended to arrive outside lunch hours.

text: I am currently in the midst of preparing to record an album at the Goodman arts centre and there aren't too many options for food in the centre. However i did manage to try a bit of food at Cafe Melba. I had what can be described as a type of pizza basket. It's clean slices of flour and dough with some meat, vegetable and cheese toppings on it. These pizzas are extremely thin and you may eat them with a choice of 3 sauces that are given to you - pesto, olive and chick peas sauce. The price range is a bit high. The quality of service is pretty good. And the ambience is the best part of the place. They have a very cool outdoor space seating area with wooden benches and tables. They also have pretty excellent coffee. It's a chillout sunday sort of a place for me.

Ordered a chai tea and banana bread toast.  Toast was good, and tea made a few cups but I went there to work and realized after I got there that WiFi is only limited to 10 customers. That ruined my whole visit. Gosh--get with the modern day ages of having free WiFi...for all customers.

text:
Decent place if you want an inexpensive cup of coffee with some quick (albeit oily) food to go. The food variety isn't that different from the myriad Yakun Kaya/ Toastbox establishments that are littered around the island so don't get your hopes up if you're really into quality food. 

Situated right at the main entrance of Bukit Panjang Plaza, so it's pretty impossible to miss.

text:
Absolutely perfect service here - so kudos to their staff!!! 

Minus one star for the bathroom, but that's just me. Kinda dark and wet and blehckkk.

The food and drinks are pretty awesome though. Nachos were well done, lots of toppings, decent serving size. Smoothies my gf and I had were really good - my favourite is the apple pie smoothie. 

Great music to suit the Mexican theme, and they have ice cream cookie sandwiches!!! 

All in all, frickin' amazeballs.

text:
This is such an awesome place! I would rate it as the best hawker center in Singapore.  Of course there are other good hawker centers and we can debate endlessly which serves the best chicken rice or prawn mee or popiah but the reason I love Amoy Street Food Centre is the diversity and sheer range of options it offers.  I feel truly blessed to be working in its 5 min radius and so spoiled too!

For S$5.50 you can get a big bowl of salad (from any of the 4 - 5 salad shops operating there) when the same bowl of greens can easily cost you 15 or more in the fancy cafes around telok ayer and raffles place.  Or if you want something different you can go for costa rican chicken rice with tacos.  It was here I tried my first "lei cha" - the Hakka "thunder tea" which is another healthy choice apart from salad.  "Noodle story" seems to be another recent favorites judging from the line.  And then of course there are the stars of the show - the famous piao ji and han kee fish soup / fish porridge. Lines are quite formidable every day from 11 am to 2 pm so pick your time wisely if you want to try.  Fancy some dessert after your meal? There is Koko Icecream - the popular coconut icecream served in a real coconut.  Or you can venture to the second floor for some baked goodies at Bake-of Muffins at very reasonable price. There are also fruit juices stalls aplenty so take your pick.  If what you crave is Japanese, Thai or Korea they have it too! It's probably the most international hawker center and the food options itself is a reflection of the changing demographics in Singapore so definitely a great place for people watching as well!
How much fun was this! It was a bit windy when we were up there but I loved taking the elevator up and then having a good IPA on the patio. We didn't eat--just sipped and enjoyed the view.
As with many Bucks in Singapore, this is a nice haven to duck in and do some work in a generally quieter environment.  Staff won't bother you and there are outlets if you need to plug in and charge.

text:
I attended the July UYE at Chop Suey Cafe today at 38 Martin Road and meet yelppers like lawrence, peter & gloria from USA as well as the local yelppers like Nik, Sonya, Ping etc

Thanks Sonya for arranging this brunch. The food is fantastic and great ambience ... oh my it's so relaxing. I had a great time today brunch-ing with all the lovely people.

This cafe serve American Chinese cuisine, i ordered a smoke duck with herb omelette and the portion serve is big and it's really tasty. I expect the smoke duck to be placed on top the omelette but it caught my surprise. The smoke duck is wrap within the omelette and it's placed above the toast with alittle veg & marmalade garnish on top of it and the sides dish is 2 roasted tomatoes and mushroom.

Oh my ..... I never regret ordering this ..... It's simply delicious and I'm really full.  BLURP! 

I envy those people who stay around here .... They have nice cafe around the vicinity and you people are so lucky.

Tumbs up ...... I will recommend my friends to visit ......

I never figured it out...was it a hardware store? or was it built up as such?  quite honestly it doesn't matter.  The coffee here (iced or hot) is some of the best I had in Singapore...but it's a bit far to get to.

text:
Oriole is owned by Keith Loh, Singapore's current champion barista. Head Barista and Assistant Manager is John Ting, who came in 2nd at the Singapore National Barista Championship. That's right, Oriole has the two best baristas in Singapore, and it shows! If I were still living in Singapore, I think it's safe to say that this would be my favourite coffee hang-out. In fact, I've been here three times in two weeks.

 Coffee prices here are just a little more expensive than the chains before factoring in service charge, but it's well worth the extra money. The staff pick their coffee with care, as Ï witnessed when I swung by yesterday, with a helpful chap talking me through the beans they used when I wandered over to the giant coffee roaster (named Ella, so I've read). He also mentioned that they were expecting some really nice coffees in a couple of days time so I should return. I will definitely do that, even though I don't own an espresso machine (yet) and only have a Bialetti.

 The best drinks to have here are the piccolo latte (comes with two shots), the chilii chocolate mocha and the citrus sin! The last two are drinks created by Keith for the World Barista Championship, and both were really nice indeed. For the chili chocolate mocha, I couldn't taste too much of the coffee, but it wasn't overwhelmingly chocolate-y either. It was a tad smokey (which I liked) and the flavour of the chili got stronger as I drank more of the beverage, but not enough to kill this chili weakling. As for the citrus sin, it was absolutely fantastic. It comes with a slice of orange so that you can squeeze the juice of it if the drink isn't citrus-y enough for you. I didn't taste very much of the citrus, but it was very smooth, and by far one of the most delicious coffees I've ever had. Two thumbs up!

 The latte art has been of a generally high standard, and I was only disappointed once, when my friend's piccolo latte came with three somewhat splotchy white patches. Possibly, they could have been three separate flowers, but, to me, they looked... messy.

 But enough about the coffee. What about the rest?

 The food was so-so, to be honest. I have had a set lunch consisting of crab and corn soup and a spaghetti bolognese, and a prawn aglio olio. All the dishes were decent, nothing much to complain about, or shout about.

 The cafe is very cosy. It's fairly dark in here, and tables are generally well-spaced so you never feel as if you're being crowded even when the place is full. I like the lighting fixtures for some reason. Very modern without being too showy. The ceiling with the exposed piping toughens the place up a little so it doesn't look pretentious.

 So, if you haven't already been able to tell, I love this place. I will do my best to return before I go back to London, even though I have several other coffee places on my list to check out. And given its late opening hours, I don't think it'll be too hard for me to do so!

text:
As I rarely come to this area, I have no idea the existence of this cafe, thanks to Natalie. From Lavender MRT station, the walk takes around 10 minutes, but do bring an umbrella if the weather forecast is rain as there is no shelter for most parts of the walk: 

When I think of 'Bao' (Chinese bread), I expect a Chinese style cafe or something like that but when I entered the cafe, it was different from what I expected. I didn't read the review or find out about more this cafe as I wanted to get an element of surprise and I did! The cafe is quite spacious as there is good amount of privacy between you and the other customers. If you are in a big group (around 6-10), you be pleased to know there is a Long table and if needed, they just add a table or two. Perfect for some catching up as its quiet and not crowded for most of the time, according to another Yelper. 

Orders are self service and free wifi is available but you have to ask the staff for the password. It would be nice if they could leave the password either on the table or on the receipt. Staff were friendly and more importantly no sign of impatience or pressure to leave the cafe even though the group had finish the food for quite some time and got lost in the wonderful conversation. 

I ordered the Namban Chicken and Classic (check my photo of the menu for more information) and I find them to be my liking for my taste bud. Not the best but decent enough for me to make another trip back to try out the other flavours. Prices is reasonable and portion is definitely value for money. 

Overall, this is a great cafe for catching up and enjoying the "bao"! Do drop by if you are nearby or have a craving for "Bao".

text:
Headed down for a quick lunch meeting so I didn't get to try much other than the tea.

I have to say the decor for the place is absolutely spiffing and probably the thing Enid Blyton novels are made up of. Love the bits and pieces on display and for sale. Pick up some tea cups if you even want an extra quality in your life. You can just start with your first special tea cup, even if you don't want to pick up the entire set. Trust me when I saw tea works better in special teacups.

I've heard amazing things about their quiche and passionfruit meringue tart. Marcus' story about the place below sounds amazing so I'm looking forward to partake in the "cook" part of this cafe.

I know of a friend holding an engagement party at this very spot!

All in all, I'll give a go for the atmosphere alone - non-pretentious and pretty private amongst your seating space. The servers are polite and helpful without being too intrusive, something which I always appreciate. Will be back to try more of the food and review this spot again!

text: This is by far the best option for 'real' bread on the East Coast + the staff are wonderful and the coffee good. Great location for a relaxed atmosphere

Valle is something of a well kept secret. Tucked away at the end of the row of shops including Haato and E-Sarn at Ridgewood Close Condominium, I would not have known about it myself if a friend hadn't brought me there. Valle is a nondescript neighbourhood bar, but don't let appearances fool you. The bar is stocked with a smorgasboard of beers, ciders and ales from all over the world. I was shocked and delighted to find Paulaner Munich on tap for $12 a pint. In fact, all the drinks are priced super reasonably. You can get Rekordlig for $12 compared to the $15 you usually see it sold for at the bars in town. You can refer to this page valle.com.sg/fullmenu.ht… for the incredibly comprehensive menu. The prices listed are delivery prices (yes, they offer delivery) but I believe the prices at the bar are $1 or $2 more. Needless to say, if you're an avid beer drinker, you will really like Valle. I also like the low key and casual vibe of the place. It really is your friendly neighbourhood bar where you can hang out and with your friends while enjoying a really good beer. Sadly, I've heard that the condo management has been forcing Valle's owner to revise the closing time earlier and earlier. While they used to close at midnight, they now have to close at 10pm, I'm guessing because of residents' complaints. This is probably why Valle's happy hour ends at 6 as the owner wants to encourage people to visit in the day. I do think Valle would be a really nice spot for a quiet afternoon drink as well.

text: One of the best pizza I have ever had in my life. Honestly, better than Mozza here in Singapore. Classy, friendly and great pizzas.  Absolutely perfect texture and chewiness in the crust, delectable and amazing creations and combinations.  Awesome wines to go with it- ensuring you to have an amazing "high class" pizza night.  Don't miss the great baked goods. This branch is the hub for all of the delectable and scrumptious pastries that are delivered throughout the island... so make sure to snatch up some amazing new and creative desserts while visiting! Bravo!

text:
Only reason why I came here is because it was the closest place for a coffee and my friend was in a pinch for time. 

I prepared myself mentally for a bad cup of coffee and pointed to the coffee that had a label that said "most aromatic". 

At $6.70, I was amazed at how horrible the latte was. Zero flavor. I should've ordered water instead. 

I'm puzzled by how this chain or ones like Starbucks are in business, knowing that they peddle sub-standard products to their customers. 

Yelp did not allow me to post without adding 1 star. But technically this place deserves zero stars.

the place is absolutely beautiful - everything from interior design and the way each dish is plated. great attention to details, and the food tasted great too!

will definitely come back to try more

text:
This place is tucked in a corner of Shaw Leisure Gallery, just before the food court. Basically, you can have 2 flavours of ice cream for all sizes; they're not cheap but really quite worth it for the taste. Beside ice cream, you can have milk shake, waffles and hot tea too.
I have the salted egg yolk ice cream, which was partly inspired by the Hong Kong yolk-filled custard buns in. It taste like the salted egg yolk found in mooncake, but surprisingly it's not salty, with a tad of sweetness, creamy, rich and filled with yolk in grainy forms. It was surprisingly good and really a refreshing take on the good old ice cream.

I also had my usual favorite, Chocolate. It was quite chocolatey and really one of the best chocolate ice creams that I've had. 

Overall, this is really one of my favorite ice cream places around.

Sea Salt Gula Melaka: 5 stars

Earl Grey Lavender: 4 stars

Love this place. Only problem is the food is inconsistent. Once my scrambled eggs looked like mash omelette and the next time it was so runny almost like half boiled eggs. Service is a tad bit slow and the chairs aren't comfortable. Affordable prices but it seems recently the portions are getting smaller.

text:
Delicious tapas amidst lush greenery.

I'm a little surprised about the low rating for this place. My friend and I went there for dinner last night and we were quite satisfied with the experience.

We didn't have a reservation but the host was kind enough to offer to wipe down the table (it was pouring earlier) and seat us outside. They had mosquito coil under the table which I thought was a nice gesture, I was still bitten once but that's not too bad..

I love the fact that the menu is not too big and the waiters seem knowledgable about the food. Quick individual reviews: Cod (extremely delicious and was our favorite, perfectly cooked; the mushroom and spinach and broth complement the fish well), cauliflower (tender inside with a slight crunch on the outside), lamb ribs (must try, very interesting spices), bone marrow (i've never had bone marrow with snails but good combination), strawberry basil sangria (a little too sweet, would have been perfect for brunch).

Minus: Slow service. Price is probably average for Dempsey Hill :)

Didn't know about this place until a friend insisted on getting some because she was in the area. out of curiosity i bought the durian roll. it was a couple hours later till i got home and that was the recommended time it should be outside the fridge once you buy it from them. the expiration on these rolls is 2-3 days. 

the roll itself was fluffy and the texture was nice. not the best durian filling but it was good enough for my first try. there were many other flavours so if i am back in that part of town i would give it another try.

text:
1 star each for the 5 things that make it for me. (Service, cleanliness, food, price and "will I come back?"). This place hits all five. FIVE STARS!

Service was good, attentive and non-intrusive. I asked about the iced-coffee and the server was able to explain everything AND accommodate my special request. No fuss!

The restaurant was clean and well-kept. The menu was small, but had pictures for most, so can't go wrong there. Gordon Ramsey will have a fit, I'm sure. "NO PHOTOS IN YOUR MENU, ARE YOU STUPID OR SOMETHING?" he'd yell. But me, I like to see a preview of what I'm ordering. By the way, since this is a Japanese coffee shop, there is a huge display of waxed facsimiles of most of the food available for you to ooh and ahh over.

Souffles! Savoury and sweet souffles! Pancakes of incredible thickness, but fluffy and light like a... souffle! Each pancake is almost 2 inches thick! The french toast was also very good. I had a savoury souffle, and even though it was topped with a huge souffle, the dish was not heavy at all.

Price was slightly high for some items, but reasonable for others. The coffee items have a refill option of $3 or so. 

Will I come back? Yes, please!

gonzo! temporarily for now, while going under renovations, as my local friend says, it's about time...yes, an average-to-good hawker centre in CBD area, but was getting old and dirty...

think the Wendy's is still open though, thankfully....

text: I attended a wedding dinner here not too long ago. The food and service were good, but nothing to scream about. Recently returned for lunch, when I had the festive menu. The main pasta dish was very good, but the Caesar salad or the dishes ordered by my lunch mates were quite meh. Prices are not exorbitant, but there are LOTS of restaurants in Singapore that serve better Italian food. Convenient for guests of the Shangri-La, but definitely not a gastronomic destination.

Let a social coffee drinker offer some tips on Highlander:

a) they're a coffee geek sort of place. Which means the coffee beans are freshly roasted, the beans and some bits of equipment are available for purchase should you feel like playing barista at home

b) they're a coffee place. DO NOT DO WHAT I DID AND ORDER A NON-COFFEE DRINK. Goodness me that smoothie was not smile-inducing, let's just say. 

Out of the various coffee joints on the street I do feel that they do java best, though I will say that if you're not looking for coffee head elsewhere!

text: Dropped by on a quiet Tuesday afternoon and they had 1-for-1 promotion for pizza going on so we took full advantage of that. We got two half&halfs - Chilli Crab and Pepperoni as well as Forest Mushroom and Parma Ham with Rocket. The pizzas are the thin crust variety which is perfect for when you're feeling peckish and not wanting to feel too full too quickly. I'd really recommend the Chilli Crab, my Favorite among the lot we chose. Truffle fries were decent, as with the flat whites. Spotted their promotion on margaritas when I was in the Ladies midway through our meal and decided to get a carafe of Strawberry Margarita to ease into the evening. Frozen margarita was a good idea; tangy refreshing and very much welcomed on the palate after too much carbs between two girls. A word of caution for the slow sipper though, frozen beverages doesn't take too kindly to our harsh humid weather so it didn't take too long till we had a quarter of our carafe left with unattractive slush floating on lukewarm pink liquid - and we were seated indoors! Service was attentive and laid back and I wouldn't mind coming around again to try other items off their extensive menu

text:
Honestly not sure what the fuss is about.

Saw decent crowds in the cafe, so I decided to try it some time. 

Their brunch menu is pretty standard for a cafe (no proper kitchen, so everything is toasted or pre-made) - waffles, toast, granola, salad, etc. I ordered a Croque Monsiere (ham and cheese on toasted bread) and a matcha milk.

The Croque Monsiere was decent, but nothing to shout about. The matcha milk was pretty good (very lightly sweetened and not bitter). 

However, the cafe itself was small and seating was not cozy, which takes away from the experience. When I'm paying cafe prices, I expect it to be nice, intimate and cosy. It wasn't. They also don't accept credit cards, which is not really acceptable for the kind of food and prices they charge.

I've heard their cold brew coffee is good - I'm not a coffee person, so I can't judge that. But based on everything else, I don't think I would go back.

The chicken and waffles was awesome. The burffle (waffle burger) was awesome. The price - is fair and not dodgy (no additional taxes, no service charge - you order and pay at the counter, but they serve food to you), you pay what you ordered.

I would definitely come again!

text: Very fresh Japanese fresh bakery. Everything looked good to eat. I would recommend if your looking to get your bakery on to come here.

Recent renovated and always popular CBD oasis. Good selection of stalls. Nice Indian and Filipino selections and one of the better Kway Teow stalls in town. Nighttime becomes a touristy, but still good, satay Mecca.

I always loved 15 Minutes and to see if close down was a sad moment as it was a great place to chill and hangout. However out with the old and in with the new. 

Overall atmosphere of this place was comfy and it has a very organic theme to the place. Plenty of seats and a stage for performances. Overall I loved the atmosphere. 

Food is not too bad as well, however I do have to point out I was here for lunch and all I had was the Dory Fish dipped with Beer Batter and the Carbonara. The Carbonara was lovely as it was not drowned in sauce like how a lot of places does it. It was however a little more to the dry side and I did wish for just a tiny bit more sauce. This fish was by far my favorite, golden crunch on the outside and moist on the inside. Definitely would recommend it.

Will definitely come back here a second time and will update this review as I get to try out more of their food.

text:
This place really doesn't need more 5-star reviews, but I *have* to rave about one of my fave desserts!! 

I was late to the whole bingsoo craze (as always) and have honestly only tried 2-3 places. I was brought here by a very reliably up to date and discerning friend, and once I tried the Green Tea bingsoo (~$13), I was sold. The huge heaping bowl of icy white flakes, dusted with matcha powder and topped with a generous scoop of green tea ice cream, with free-flow condensed milk if you so wish...It's a lot for one person to eat on your own, and it's regrettably a lot more expensive than bingsoo in Korea (~$8SGD). It tastes relatively authentic though. The toppings are generous, and can be tasted throughout the whole bowl - not the type of dessert where the ending dregs are basically tasteless ice. The ice itself isn't actually sweet, and doesn't melt fast too. I love sharing a bowl with friends! 

Another good thing is, the seating area (next to the glass walls of Evolve martial arts gym) is spacious, quieter than other parts of 313 or OC, and rarely crowded. Thus a great place for leisurely chats! 

I've also tried the injeolmi bingsoo, which comes with peanuts, almonds and soy flour. A little too nutty for my taste, but very tasty, and loved the little chewy mochi bits. 

I can say I'm confident bringing friends here to chill - can't say that about many places!

text:
*Coffee Snob Intro*
When you're let go from a company the locations you frequent many many coffee shops.

These wonderful roasteries provide the perfect balance of professional attitude, casual attire, and passionate delivery to aid you in your job search.

I'm going to rate a bunch of coffee shops based on this metric and a few others and provide an overall rating for the experience.

----------------------------------
OVERALL: 4 stars

Ambience: 4
Coffee: 4
Food: N/A (did not try)
Meeting Place: 4
Working Space: 4
----------------------------------

*Coffee Review*
Baristart is a solid 4-star coffee venue ticking all the boxes! If you can handle the heat I suggest you sit outside at the slim table and enjoy the people watching in Tras Street which is an interesting distraction from your digital device ;) 

Inside is a very slick 'n' slim modern coffee shop which buzzes with activity. You order at the counter, take a buzzer, then wait for your coffee order to be ready back at the counter. This actually helps to keep that area free of a queue clutter --- and why are we all standing around waiting anyways when we have our stupid friend Nancy's endless insta stories to catch up on? [Note to Nancy: No one cares about your ugly cat Minxy!]

If I come here to work I generally pick the spot at the high chairs, with the wall-garden, facing the front door. This maximises serenity and peripheral optics.

The coffee has some solid options (usually fruity or nutty for the single origin aficionado's) and I almost always opt for the dark nutty single origin varieties as I like a dark 'n' rich roast - always sans milk. Otherwise I'll just opt for a soy latte. It's a good coffee, and definitely one of the best in the area. Also a solid place to meet for an interview or 1-to-1, as the sharp-looking surroundings should suit the business formality.

NB: Tras Street itself has many shophouses which have a mixture of full-length French windows and half-length casement windows so you'll be taking photos.)

text:
My husband and I watched "FRIENDS" every night when we lived in Singapore so I said, why don't I check out the actual cafe right here? 

Well. It was bound to happen. I went to a tourist trap. 

It isn't the exact replica per se of the famous TV show, but they've got the weathered couch and Monica's kitchen (off to the side of the main entrance) spot on. Of course, you'll notice some familiar decor (Joey's white dog art, Ross' Unagi moment captured on photo) around too. They play FRIENDS re-runs constantly on the big screen and everytime the intro song plays, the staff will stop to clap to the beat. 

Right off the bat, you'll notice that the menu is full of catchphrases and puns from the long running TV show, like Janice's Oh My God baby ribs, Chandler's Thanksgiving Dinner, etc. It's cute and funny, but not worth the multiple dollar signs. I was really glad that I had lunch beforehand, so I only paid S$8 for a latte. I had to do it, so I could also have the opportunity to sit on the couch and take my picture. 

Because, if you didn't take a photo, were you even there?

text:
I have some mixed feelings about this place.

The cafe is in a prime spot of telok ayer, a cute little street with loads of character and just an overall pleasant part of SG.

The outdoor seating is definitely preferable, as it can get VERY cramped inside.

Food: the food is good, but I think it's definitely too pricey for what it is. I have tried both the Caesar salad (good yoghurty dressing with some herbs) and the Halloumi salad (too salty!) here, and I have heard the bread is great too.  The Caesar portion is large but I still do not think it is worth the price, unless you're itching to spend $15-$17 for a salad! 

My main concern with this place is that the last time I ate here (had the Halloumi salad), I got food poisoning!  Regardless of their fancy spins on salads, I don't think I will risk it again and definitely not for the exorbitant cost!

Nylon is a rather tiny place with essentially no tables/sitting, so don't expect to really hang out comfortably here.

I know close to zero about coffee-making, but I think that Probat machine they have in the back room looks pretty cool. Like it's the heart & core of their operations.

One of the very few coffee places that are open on Mondays, along with Stranger's Reunion and Toby's Estate.

Parking: You'll see many cars parked illegally around the back of the blocks. Not sure how "safe" it is, so I usually park at the multi-storey behind which anyway has a linkway (level 2B I think) straight to Nylon .

text:
If it's hearty grandmother food that you're hoping for, you're generally better off going to one of Singapore's many hawker centres. I'm sure the regular punters at Singpopo come to enjoy the chilled out vibe and the heart warming "blast from the past" environment, knowing full well that they could probably get the same food but better and cheaper elsewhere.

Having said that, on a scorching day in Singapore, a Gula Melaka Soft Jelly ($4.90) and a round of Sng Muay Pop ($3.90) would definitely go a long way in helping you to keep cool. Points for commitment to recreating some of Singapore's vibrant past but the "classics" on the menu in Sinpopo's case, aren't really worth returning for.

text: better than gong cha! To taste is to believe. Can't be in SG and not queue at koi. Their tea is very flavorful, the boba not hard nor half cooked.  I like the lemon black tea and the milk tea variants.

text: I have been to this bakery bistro twice now and I have to say that I have not been impressed. They always say to give the good feedback first, so here goes - the ambiance is quite nice with its Parisian feel and decor. The service is passable but lacks any warmth. Now, my biggest complaint is the poor quality of coffee and pastry. After a hectic day of shopping, I just wanted to sit down and get a nice hit of caffeine. But I really can't get pass the weak coffee that tastes so diluted. Tried the blueberry and chocolate tarts - crust is too thick and hard and the filling is nothing to write home about. All in all, I don't think I will be making a third trip back.

I have not reviewed this place yet?

Well, I am trying to hide this from all of you here.
This place is crowded in the weekend as people from all walk of life come here for a cuppa of coffee and some delicious croissants! 

In the weekday's mornings, thankfully, it is not as packed but it is still buzzing. I wonder why people do not have to work and hang out at coffeeshop all the time. 

The bakery is good, though I chance upon quite a disappointing macha croissant today. Just order the original croissant will do. The kouign amann is also good, but a lil too sweet. 

Overall, I like this joint better than the one at City Hall as it is more quaint because it is located within the hip Tiong Bahru neighbourhood.

I've had brunch there once and enjoyed the salted egg crab pasta the most. Portions are huge so I'd advise sharing so you'll have room for dessert... Like their ondeh ondeh cake! I loved it so much I ordered some for my mum's and aunt's birthday. We had some snafus with the delivery service initially but Hafiz was quick to rectify and mistakes and provide a solution. TMC can count on me as a repeat customer!

Great innovative spot with lots of press. Very creative menu options for a dessert I truly love - vanilla ice cream with a shot of espresso over it...the affogato.

This place takes that idea to the next level and starts mixing up all different types of ice cream flavors with different kinds of coffee and other toppings. Definitely worth a look for these reasons.

However, where my frustration comes is that there is no seating time limit policy and in a way it is a great problem for them to have. The place is a coffeehouse but also a dessert spot - you literally cannot eat an affogato if you have nowhere to sit. You can't have it for take out since the point of an affogato is a hot espresso over a cold ice cream.

Unfortunately, many patrons buy a shot of espresso or coffee and read a book or work on their laptop for much time as if it is a normal coffee shop, even during peak hours when there is nowhere to sit.

I hope they do figure this out as I would for sure come back much more often!

Oreo Cheesecake', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Oreo Cheesecake'}]
text:
I was at Ogopogo last night and at first I found the name a bit of a mouthful to pronounce but all these were set aside after the staff at the cafe greeted me with a big cheery "HELLO!" 

The ambiance of the place was quite 1970-80 ish. People like me who were born during that era will find it a fair bit nostalgic with their quirky chairs and toys on display.. they have those 10 cents lollipops I used to buy in Primary School sold straight from the jar. 

Their menu which arrived in the form of a jotterbook, which according to the staff, each and every book was painstakingly handwritten (so don't go spilling drinks or food on the jotterbook since it was someone's blood, sweat and tears!). They have coffee, lattes, beers, ciders, sodas and smoothies. They also have a range of cakes available and a little shisha place at the back where unlike other places, you don't have to smoking by the street side with the cars zooming by and people staring at you. It's a nice private enclosed open space at the back where other than the distant sounds from the other stores around Ogopogo, you can pretty much smoke in peace. 

If you are hungry, feel free to ask the owners for their food menu. They have an arabian food menu and an italian menu where once you order, the staff will run to the stores next door and place your order for you. 

I really like the ambiance of this place as it's very laidback, the staff are very friendly and the drinks are delicious! Will definitely come back for more here!

I'm typing this after being done with the salmon and cream cheese bun thing and the pear tart. Had a flat white as well. I must say, I had high expectations seeing as to how my friends have raved about this place. Verdict? Nahhhh

The salmon wasn't fresh, very unlike the salmon baguette I had at Broers Cafe (and their specialty isn't sandwiches!). And they could've been a bit more generous with the cream cheese. The pear tart was okay (with the so-so hand action). Could've been sweeter, given how the girl asked me "would you like any sweets to go with your meal?". Coffee was okay too.

I guess it could be because it's 6pm and the food isn't quite as fresh. I'll give it a second chance and be sure to be here much earlier in the day. So far, seems pretty overrated.

The lovely takeaway area, many tasty delights for a next day&#39;s breakfast.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "The lovely takeaway area, many tasty delights for a next day's breakfast."}]
text:
Hmm, the food is good, the atmosphere is nice, even the "outdoor" seating, but the service and policies really bring it down, I'd give this 2.5 stars if I could.

This a popular restaurant and the long queue waiting to get seated shows that, it also calls out for a better managed system, maybe a waiting list and SMS when there is an available table, something better. There is also a take away counter, like a traditional bakery with many tasty items calling out to be taken home. This take away counter presents another odd policy/system that should be better thought out. There are items at the take away counter that aren't on the menu, and you can't order them if you are dining in. This is such an odd decision, it is the same restaurant/kitchen the food is already prepared, sell the item for a dollar more and laugh all the way to the bank; yet they would not serve it. Speaking of serving items, our drinks arrived much after our food, and many follow up requests, even a freshly baked waffle came before Ice Lemon Tea. Even the second round of tea took so long to arrive, very disappointing.

text: 2 of us decided to walk there after coming back from the fantastic LeonardoDaVinci'sBlueprints exh on the final Saturday of 2014. It was pouring heavily but fortunately, the place was just 10mins' walk from apt. Was enticed by the 3for2pints of draft HoffbrauDunkel and had those with tandoori roll, sambal eggplant and lotsa complimentary groundnuts. Everything was tasty and ended up staying until they closed shop@10:30pm.

I'm surprised this place rates so low. It's a popular lunch spot among my colleagues because of the buy one get one free lunch deal, and the fact that the food is pretty good

They don't take reservations for lunch on weekdays, but it wasn't a problem for our party of 17. We made sure we arrived by 12pm to get a table. 

The menu that qualifies BOGO isn't large, but it's still decently diverse. You don't have to get the same item, just anything on the BOGO menu. A lot of people got the salmon with balsamic vinegar, and the Dory main dish was pretty popular too. I had the beef lasagna, which I thought was excellent. At half the price, it was a steal. 

The service was not outstandingly bad or good.

Definitely a good place for a fancier lunch.

The good:  Quaint space, happy customers, reasonable prices and good coffee.

The bad:  I know I'm going to get roasted for this (pun intended!), but the above is the list of all the good things about Nylon.  Nothing more, nothing less.  Feels like you're walking into someone's kitchen, so depending on whether you like that feel, it could be good or bad.  Took me awhile to locate the shop as it's buried beneath a HDB block.   By the time I got there, the LAST thing I wanted was something hot (because Singapore is hot!).  I came with a friend and we both ordered the recommended coffee, iced.  Drinks came out in a timely manner and we both intently sipped them outside (because there were already 3 people inside...i.e. packed house).  My friend thought her drink was a bit bitter, so she flagged down one of the staff for some sugar.  Their response, "Have you tasted it?".  God bless that pretentious barista I thought to myself as I nearly spat out a mouthful of my iced bean-from-somewhere-interesting coffee.  For the first time in awhile, I was transported straight to Williamsburg, Brooklyn (if you don't know, google it).

The ugly:  They deal strictly with coffee, so right there I have a cap of 4 stars.  I'm not a huge coffee fan, and by that I mean I drink 1-2 cups a day from various local spots and chains.  Is Nylon coffee good?  Yes.  Is it better than the rest?  Maybe.  Can anyone really tell?  Probably not.  Therefore, unless this place was on my way to work, I wouldn't make it a destination.  With nothing to eat and nowhere to sit I would prefer any other cafe around the way.  I'm so annoyed at Bean Snobs/Coffee Cults (I just made those up) that I'm borderline close to organizing a blind taste test just to prove that coffee is as much about climate, sensation and temper as it is about taste.  To put it another way, the best tasting meals are when you're hungry.  So, in short, people crave the experience.  Plus caffeine...can't forget about the spectacular drug caffeine.

text:
Quintessential Singaporean breakfast! Kaya toast, runny eggs, and coffee. Well I don't drink coffee, so I had tea with milk and sugar instead.

A really nice man asked me if I was eating there or for takeaway, and when I said it was for there, he told me to take a seat anywhere and then brought over a menu. I got the above mentioned breakfast set, which was set A. There was a set B, C, and D, which had different kinds of kaya toast. I remember set D was a kaya peanut butter toast which also sounded amazing. 

The kaya butter toast was pretty delicious the bread is very toasted and crispy. At one point, the nice old man sat down with me and showed me how to properly eat kaya toast. He asked to put soy sauce and some black pepper into my runny eggs. Then I mixed it and he told me to dip my toast into the runny egg/soy sauce mixture. Really tasty! Great hearty way to start the day!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Et6FuTelj48CstmQMiBuYw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/creamier-handcrafted-ice-cream-and-coffee-singapore-2?reviewid=KovRndeZBradfrbURfbTGQ&select=Et6FuTelj48CstmQMiBuYw', 'altText': 'Photo of Creamier Handcrafted Ice Cream and Coffee - Singapore, Singapore. Waffle w Premium Single Scoop ($9.30)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Waffle w Premium Single Scoop ($9.30)'}]
text:
One of my fav ice cream joints in Singapore! I enjoy visiting the Tiong Bahru and Gillman Barracks outlets more as there's usually more space for parking and dine-ins. No wifi on site, self service for water and food collection (but they charge GST & service charge?), full parking lot right behind the store. If not, this outlet is about a 10 min walk from Tiong Bahru mrt Station. 

Waffles are great, you get 2 pieces of made-to-order Belgian waffles -- crispy on the outside, soft and fluffy on the inside. $6 per 2 pieces can be pretty pricey, but it is a popular item. 

Roasted pistachio is my favourite flavour on their menu. Nutty, full-bodied flavour and nothing of that fake extract taste that you'll get from cheaper options. It's a premium flavour at $3.30 a scoop, but the ingredients are not skimped on. 

Other yums flavours:
Earl grey lavender -- one of their classics. Not too sweet and aromatic. 
Plain ole chocolate -- May be boring but done right. Rich and bittersweet. 
Mango passionfruit sorbet -- tastes like (sweet) frozen mango in a pint. 
Matcha -- quite an elusive flavour but was surprisingly good, bittersweet and creamy. 
Banana chocolate chip crumble -- simple and good. Tastes like real banana!

There are many many other flavours. Don't feel shy to sample at the store! They have a 1 for 1 deal on Burpple Beyond for their ice cream and waffles. 

If you're too lazy to head down to an outlet, they also deliver on GrabFood at $12 a pint for regular flavours, and $16 for premiums (+$3 delivery fee). Alternatively, order directly from Creamier and get free delivery over $60!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/JeX04Yxxce1zExtm_GDFjA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/haritts-donuts-and-coffee-singapore?reviewid=NdpMm4GtDSspdGaiRnyVaw&select=JeX04Yxxce1zExtm_GDFjA', 'altText': 'Photo of Haritts Donuts & Coffee - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
They do only a few things but do them well. The few things being good coffee by local roaster homeground. And donuts in a multitude of flavours.

The donuts are just like the Haritts when I had the in Tokyo. It has this unique soft chew a bit like tender bread but is not like local airbread. The dough has a nice delicate flavour and the chew is somehow springy and not flatlines.

Their most popular flavour is the cream cheese and it costs more accordingly. It takes more effort and time to prepare. $3.20. This is my clear favourite. There is a slight saltiness to the cheese.

Matcha has the bitter kick of matcha powder, fun to share as a side. Chocolate is ok but I not a big chocolate person at all so if you are don't let me stop you.

I nearly rated it 4 stars. Because when I sidle up at 915am. Only 2 flavours are ready and cheese is only out earliest 11 plus am I told. Regardless they do sell out most days. The only table is outside where its usually hot. I do want to sit and savour my donut and coffee and not have it on the run.

If the top item isn't produced till half the day is gone and you can't eat it, how to rate for it. Luckily I had it on an earlier visit after lunch. The guy was so kind he did say he would deliver me a few as he would be near my office the next day. In the end the uniqueness of the taste of the dough with cream cheese and the texture, if that doesn't get the last star what does.

They are going to open Sundays soon. That makes it a fun day.

text: Went there for after dinner boost. The bottled coffee is good and I tried their afogato with coconut ice cream paired with gula melaka. The coffee are fantastic. Earl Grey cheesecake is good, but I am not a big fans of cheese so I am not going to judge about it. However, I could tell by looking at the queue which mostly came for the cakes. We went there around 8.30pm and were told that the kitchen was already closed. Will go there again for coffee, the ambience is good for gathering.

text:
This Starbucks outlet will forever be special to me. Why? Because this was where I bumped into a Bollywood superstar, Hrithik Roshan -- 12 February 2011. A fellow Capricorn who's a Starbucks lover like I am. *sighs*

...Anyways! I am impressed with the services here so far. But nothing unique here, really. It's your everyday Starbucks. Though it's easy to spot as it's located just beside the escalators at the basement. It's also near another exit which I find to be quite convenient if you just wish to grab and ciao! 

Seats are a bit tough to get since they're almost always occupied. Never had the chance to actually sit here before. *pouts*

text: I really cannot find this shop. I had Sharetea in Bugis and always love it. My favorite bubble tea place! Order the black tea creama, their sea salt creama on top is very tasty, only Sharetea has this one!

text:
What's not to love? This bakery is family run and has some of the loveliest cakes and pastries. My favourite has to be the doughnut balls on a stick #childhoodflashback and the custard puffs. 

Their chicken pie is popular, though I have never had any. Hard to find the stomach room for pie after doughnuts and custard puffs.

text:
Bread & Hearth is the new coffee / pastry shop in the heart of Katong V mall. I'm so glad that this pastry shop filled the space once occupied by a dull furniture shop.

In my opinion the big draw of B&H are the pastries. The Pain Au Chocolat, croissants, French apple turnovers are all pretty solid. I particularly love the buttery crust of the Pain Au Chocolat. It's especially good after being heated (on request).

Unfortunately, the selection at B&H, particularly the main courses, is limited to just quiche and a few select sandwiches: Bacon egg mayo, tuna sandwich, etc. yikes, not good because I hate sandwiches.

Fortunately, this lack of selection is made up by a decent cup of Joe, in my case, a flat white. 

Given this limited selection, I can only give this place three stars. Group Therapy located a few steps away still reigns supreme in my eyes. The coffee selection is far superior and offers a full selection of high quality mains.

Would I come back? Yes, but just for the $3 Pastries and free water. :-)

Latte + iced mocha', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Latte + iced mocha'}]
text:
Decent coffee, ample and spacious seating, free and fast wifi (+power points for those who need them)... can't ask for much more! Add in the Korean music playing in the background, including familiar osts from the likes of Goblin... I guess that's why I've found myself going back there a couple of times :) 

Dal.komm has a good selection of cakes, none of which I've really tried so I can't give an honest opinion, but the coffee is pretty good. Their sweet drinks (such as their matcha latte) can be too sweet though for some...

This Hawker stand has a lot of variety!  Everything from classic Singaporean dishes to Western fare.

I got a solid education in Hainanese chicken rice and also got some good coffee in here.  I wish I had more time to try other things as there's many different cultures represented in here!  If you're in the area drop in and I'm sure you'll find something that interests you

What a classy tea shop,  great tea selection, not inexpensive but worth every penny.  Their macaroons are to die for, so many delish flavors and they always look so good displayed in their window.  Service is always courteous and friendly.

text:
When I go to restaurants, I'm always keen on the Specials.  So I have chosen their Specials a couple of time and they are a miss.  We went there sometime Christmas and it was just a couple of ham slices piled up with a very salty sauce.  We all had the same thing and they came looking different from one another with different serving sizes.
So lesson learned -- stick to their basics -- Ceasar Salad, Truffle Fries, Eggs Benedict...
Service also becomes bad when they are full -- so avoid weekends!

Everyone loves ice cream, and if you're a ice cream lover, try Tom's Palette!

Firstly, their ice cream flavours are all created by the owners themselves, and it not only taste so good, you've leave the place smiling like a little kid.

Yes, as most have already recommended, try the salted egg ice cream. Even if you're not a fan of salted egg, the unique and interesting taste might change your taste in salted egg. I'm serious! It's sweet, like ice cream should be and yet the taste of salted egg is rich and strong. I couldn't help imagining the actual salted egg.

Or, you can try the Granny's favourite. I'll definitely put that in my recommendation list.

Pen down your thoughts and write your little notes around the shop too.

text:
Get your carbs on!

Brunch lovers and carb lovers - this is YOUR spot!  Yes, the wait can be a little crazy, but if you're patient, you will be rewarded with some fab, soul-hugging, muffin-top making food (just spend an extra 10 minutes on the elliptical!)  The trick is to go early (before 10 am) and the wait is manageable.  They are only open until 6 pm now but that may change soon.

The food
We couldn't help but indulge in a few pastries.  The bacon, spinach, cheddar muffin was savory, a little sweet, and indulgent.  Even my baby loved it (well for obvious reasons). The cheddar scone was crumbly and had a wonderful buttery top.  But the real star is the crab cake eggs benedict.  It was the best eggs benedict I've ever eaten!  Each component from the just cooked spinach to the creamy hollandaise sauce to the rich crab cake was just plain delicious.  I also had the chorizo with eggs and it was savory and satisfying.  We were very happy with the food so far and this is one of my new, favorite brunch spots!

Better than your other rooftop bar options because you get an in-house brewery along with the best night time view (why go to the top of MBS when MBS IS part of the view??). The place was packed on a weekday night, but you can definitely still snag a table outside with a little wait. We got the beer flight -- IPA was good and I liked the ordering from light to dark brews. Combined with the elevated ambiance and stunning city view, LeVel33 should definitely be a top visit for rooftop bars!
Must try their lamb shank. Very delicious and roasted with long hours. A good place to chill out with friends as well.

Spize is one of our default places for supper after a night out or just when we're really hungry after midnight and most other places are shut.

For something I usually go for the tissue prata and a cup of hot teh halia. We've also tried the nasi goreng pattaya which is not bad, as well as some hot plate dishes like crayfish, sliced fish, egg tofu and sup kambing. Everything was OK although the sup kambing not as good as the ones in Malaysia albeit less oily. The murtabaks are generally decent. The drinks ie the Milo Dinosaur are pretty good.

They also do delivery.

text:
Full of hype? Check.
Lives up to its hype? Check.

I was lucky to be at ion at 11am on a Wednesday morning and there were only 3 people in line. I joined the line hoping to try this famous cheese tart.

Every customer is only allowed to buy 12, and I ended up getting a dozen, because well, I'm already in line so why not?? 

The tarts are super delicious when they are fresh out of the oven. Sinfully rich but not too much that it makes you sick. They are pretty pricey at $3.50 per tart, but well, I'm only here once a year.

My favorite coffee joint in the CBD area. It's a little bit on the pricier side, but the coffee is worth it and you can get a punch card and earn a free drink after 9 drinks. I personally love the flat white ($6) and the iced mocha ($7.50).
