text:
Young, hipster land, lots of chatter, noise, whimsical decor. A place for coffee and dessert. Go on a date. Instagram your food pics with ample light on the 3fl (Alfresco seating available in addition to inside) Third floor tends to get the high decibels, bordering on canteen levels, while the second is more hushed. Brunch maybe, but keep expectations low and order the same as your partner. As I type this, my bangers and mash has been consumed, and my better half's lemon grass chicken is 37 min after ordering and still not here! 

In the end, it took 40min to be plated. The kitchen is tiny. Stick with the easy to prepare dishes. Stick with the coffee which is decent. They are passionate about their beans. Mains are meh. Lastly, the price points are on the higher side. In sum, I wouldn't go out of my way. 2.5 Just average.

We came here one evening after dinner and were amazed at how many people were getting ice cream on a Friday night. I would have thought bars would be a much more popular destination. Nevertheless, we managed to snag a table just as a group was leaving so, lucky us!

We ordered a waffle with 3 scoops of ice cream to share. While I did not love the waffle, my friends did - I like my waffles crisp and light all the way through. This was a little dense and slightly undercooked in the middle which made it feel chewier and more substantial.

What I really enjoyed were the ice-creams! We got Pistachio, The Apiary, and dark chocolate. They were a little on the sweet side, but what is dessert without sugar anyway? My favorite was definitely the Apiary - it had a milk base with honey and vanilla, and also honeycomb. Yum on all counts!! The pistachio was fragrant but a little too sweet for me. The dark chocolate was heaven but I'm not a huge chocolate person.

I would go back to try their black and white sesame ice creams. Yum yum.

text:
Given that it's a fairly well known brand from NYC, lines and crowds are expected even in the soft launch phase. Approx 1 hour wait during weekend brunch. 

Order came pretty swiftly, had the classic Pancakes. Generous portions as per the ones in NYC. Chicken and waffles were decent but not mind blowing. Overall decent cool brunch spot, hopefully it survived beyond the hype.

Truffle fries and deserts my dudes. That's what matter at this place. The entrees and appetizers I've had here have been satisfying but not exactly memorable. However the milkshakes, pastries, and fries I've had here have all been fantastic. Order their truffle fries and a milk shake for a classed up version of the old frosty and fries combo at Wendy's. Beware though, it's kind of expensive for what you get - but it's Singapore, everything is expensive.

text:
Very fresh beans and superbly great atmosphere, however if your looking for a hearty meal this is not where you should be going. Only serve breakfast menu here. 
Beans are seasonally changed and every roast has their distinct flavor. Whether your looking for a robust or a weak perk me up kind of coffee, this place will satisfy all your needs. Food is just regular cafe sandwiches and wraps, no surprising wow menu. Consistent flavored will be a big draw to those that love their food standards to be stable.

text:
You're paying for the experience. From the elegant food to the bougey ambiance of the Marina Bay Shoppes, that is pretty much what you are paying for when you dine here. 

I've always walked by this location every time I've been to Singapore and I was always curious to what it was like. I landed in Singapore in the late afternoon and wanted a quick snack time with some caffeine involved.

I ordered the Fortune Tea Set during their high tea hours. I thought the food was very delicious. Just what you would want for an afternoon pick up. My tea tower included one of the finger sandwiches, scones or muffins, and three macarons. I decided on the truffle croque, the golden raisen scones, a earl grey tea macaron, a rose macaron, and a tiramisu macaron. For the tea, I decide on the hot original Black Tea 1837. 

I would be back again for afternoon high tea. Not sure if I want to eat here for a full meal because there are a ton of other heartier and more "value" options around the Marina Bay Shoppes. I say give this place a try if your looking for high tea and live your glamorous life! You're in Singapore in the first place!

text:
Week days. Wait staff could use some training the juniors.  

I'm gonna stick to Sunday roast. It's dam good.

Good news for all! This year, York Hotel Singapore is back to celebrate the 30th Anniversary for their renowned Penang Hawkers' Fare Buffet, held at their White Rose Cafe, Level 1.

They brought in 12 stalls this year and 3 sessions throughout 2016:
- March 11 to March 27, 2016
- Sept 2 to Sept 18, 2016
- Dec 16 to Jan 1st, 2017

Response was really good and NO RESERVATIONS entertained, walk-in-only. Lunch 12noon to 2.30pm / Dinner 6.30pm to 10pm.

Weekday Priced at $29++ Adult / $20++ Child below 12 / Weekends Priced at $33++ Adult / $20++ Child below 12 

If any of you interested to learn how to make their prawn noodles, assam laksa and ban chang kueh, last chance on 19 March 2016. Limited seats, call 68301156 to register now.

Here were some highlights from their Penang hawkers' fare buffet:

(1) Penang Assam Laksa

- Assam laksa, the best item I had that night. A bowl of thick bee hoon (rice noodles), soaked in pipin' hot broth made from fish and tamarind. Sourish, full of flavours, so SHIOK! Topped with pineapple slices, chilli buddy, shredded cucumber, torch ginger and complete with a small spoonful of prawn paste. I can have this everyday! Rating 5/5

(2) Prawn Noodles

- This bowl of "hae mee" (prawn noodles) wasn't as impressive as the laksa but was definitely comfort food. As told by the hawker chef, broth was made from piles of prawn heads, pork ribs and shells to obtain this robust consistency but I wished the taste was much stronger. Prawns given were really tiny, pork slices too dry but the rewarding part? Lotsa crispy pork lard! Rating 3/5

(3) Lor Bak

- A snack resembling our local fried prawn fritters (五香虾饼), this Penang version came with only 4 items; deep fried prawn, sweet potato, tau gua (fried beancurd) and handmade five-spiced meat roll. I love the meat rolls most while the other three were rather common. They were well marinated with good amount of chinese spices, not overpowering, while the meat was firm and juicy. Rating 3/5

(4) Penang Rojak

- This interesting plate of "chinese salad" caught my attention because of the ingredients used. Instead of the usual tau pok (fried beancurd skin) and dough fritters we had in our rojak, Penang version had jambu and green mango in it. Love the crunchiness of the fruits mixed in with the thick flavourful rojak sauce (prawn paste) and fragrant grounded peanuts. Not everybody could accept the pungent smell of prawn paste but I can and I quite like it. Rating 4/5

(5) Char Kway Teow

- Longest queues were found infront of this char kway teow stall. Everyone patiently waited, just to get their hands on this Penang's renowned char kway teow. A small plate of fried flat rice noodles in soya sauce, loaded with bean sprouts, spring onions, cockles, egg and prawn. Fragrant, savoury, semi sweet and least oily! It's a waste that my plate of CKT doesn't carry that smokey "wok hei" taste otherwise it would be perfect! Rating 4/5

(6) Kway Teow

- An ordinary looking bowl of dry kway teow with fishballs and shredded chicken. But the base sauce for tossing the kway teow was so yum! A mixture of Penang sweet sauce, dark soya sauce plus sesame oil, these sauces' combination seems so simple yet delicious and satisfying. Rating 3/5

(7) Pasembur

- This year's new item. A mixture of shredded cucumber pile, potato chunks, fried beancurd, Egg slice and thin crispy dough biscuits. Special? Yes, the sauce! The orange-coloured sauce on top was made from sweet potato! Sweet and slight grainy, interesting fusion taste when consume with the ingredients. Rating 3/5

(8) Ban Chang Kueh

- Crispy, sweet, buttery, loaded with lotsa grounded peanuts, so yummy so IRRESISTABLE! Nuff said :) Rating 5/5

(9) Chendol

- Personally, I felt this chendol wasn't as authentic as those I tried before, especially these greeny pandan jellies (If you know what I meant). Kidney beans were nicely done and not mushy, the thick caramelized  gula melaka was a highlight too but I prefer the portion to be more. Rating 4/5

Other stalls' delicacies include Nasi Lemak with Nonya Chicken Kapitan which had very fragrant coconut rice and nicely done ikan billis chilli, Oyster omelette which lack crispiness, Cuttlefish Kangkong and dessert Ice Kacang.

** The whole dining experience was really good, especially when dine with good friends. On site situation was crowded, even on a weekday Tuesday night, but all customers were really discipline and queued politely. Despite the long queues and busy nights, the hawkers cooking at individual stations were all smiles throughout. They were also kind enough to tell us more about the food recipes when asked upon. Thumbs up! Although each dish came in small portions but you could queue again, repeatedly, for your favourite choices, it's buffet anyway!!
For the price of $29++ on weekdays and $33++ on weekends, this deal was definitely worth! Hurry down before this fare ends on 27 March 2016. **

text:
Disclaimer: Depends on the barista on duty

Been a long while since I gave a review but this was disappointing considering the number of coffee shop options in Orchard and the fact that Jewel prides itself as a specialty coffee place. As seen in the photo, the flat white was void of any latte art. The flat white was the exact opposite of thick and creamy and failed to bring out the flavour of the beans.

Similarly, the cold brew was diluted and failed to produce any distinct notes.

Overall, a disappointment. If you're in the area, you'd be better of at the cozy Plain Vanilla nearby which surprisingly serves better coffee.

Only from 11am. Torturous for those with young children', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Only from 11am. Torturous for those with young children'}]
text:
No longer a select croissant/etc and pay-at-the-cashier, it's a sit down affair with an extensive brunch and lunch menu. However, part of the draw of TBB is its early opening at 8am, and only the usual croissants etc are available from 8. The avocado toast is available from 9, and other brunch food like pancakes only from 11am. Ugh. 

Still, I'm not complaining, as the croissants are delicious (as ever) and they open relatively early at 8am -- no waiting about for cafes to open at 9 or 10! Grateful for that.

text:
This is heaven!

I'm obsessed win Sanrio and made plans to come here months before our trip!

The decor is superb with everything Gudetama theme! It seriously was so so fun!

In terms of food.. it was OKAY. It was pretty overpriced and not that good. But reading from past reviews I already expected it so we just shared a dish for pictures lol!

If you're a Gudetama fan you have to stop by!

Service was wonderful !

Thank you guys!

Recently tried their new savoury croissants.

Speaking of the "Rolling Dumpling", I would not have guess that it was inspired from Xiao Long Bao if not for the menu description as it lacked the distinctive traits of this classic chinese dumpling such as the slurpy pork broth. Yes, there were pickled ginger and succulent minced meat but the black vinegar dressing could not lift up the dish.

Nonetheless, the sparkling chemistry between the subtly spiced chorizos and the sweet caramelized onion jam in the "Flying Pig" left me clamouring for more. Its miso dressing did not overpower the dish and I wouldn't even mind if the sausage was spammed with even more of the tasty onion relish on top. 

As a person with a soft spot for fish, I thought I would love the "Jumping Fish" the most but it turned out otherwise. A bite into this voluptuous croissant revealed an oasis of minced spinach and salmon filling. The smoked salmon was not too salty but the filling, which reminded me of the classic Greek Pie Spanakopita, needed a shake of herbs to bring it to life. 

Another calorie-worthy croissant is the "Running Egg" that was garnished with non-heady Japanese spicy flakes. While ramen egg gurus might insist that the "molten" egg yolk could be more gooey, I thought the current consistency worked well with the bonito flakes and mayonnaise sauce, which contributed to the tasty umami flavours.

Prepared fresh in batches and kept warm in hotboxes to retain the temperature, all the croissants, except for the Ramen egg, are baked together with the ingredients. This results in a croissant dough that are more moist and chewy while the external layer retains a delightful crunch.

Each croissant is retailing at $4.50 each or you can select any two flavours to go with the tangy salad with yuzu dressing, dried cranberry and mixed seeds for $12. My suggestion is to enjoy these savoury croissants at the outlets where they are served piping hot and fresh from the oven. 

It's alright if your stomach acknowledged the aroma of caramelized butter by making some embarrassing growls in public.

Mine did but so did everyone.

text:
A must-visit for tourists - so many different types of delicious food for cheap!

Tian Tian's Chicken Rice (4/5) - Not sure if this lived up to the hype - the rice was super delicious and had an insane amount of flavor packed into it, but the chicken itself was meh to me. The chili garlic sauce gave the dish a pretty nice kick, which I loved
 
Hainanese Curry Fish (4/5) - The curry was delicate and light, which paired perfectly with the fish and rice. Nice portions for the price.

Fish Bee Hoon (4/5) - Super light fish broth with tender of pieces of fish.

Juice Farm (5/5) - Pineapple dragonfruit smoothie was so delicious! Wish I could've tried their other smoothies as well.

A pretty basic place. 

Came here because I was craving Pancakes & they were pretty good. I enjoyed the blueberries  and the sauce with the pancakes which I felt were a good combination. I wished they gave more blueberries because towards the end it started to get pretty dry. The sauce also started to get too sweet once the blueberries finished. But the pancakes were fluffy and tasty. 

The chicken and waffles were a disappointment. I admit the waffles were done differently and could be subjectively just not up to my taste. But the chicken was poor. Tasteless, kinda soggy and dry. The sweet sauce didn't really go well with this and overall I'm really not a fan of this dish. 

Ordered the grits as well which was horrible. Could tell they didn't know how to cook cheese & grits and it is not like what it's meant to be like. Very dry and undercooked. Flavourless.. bah horrible. 

The sausage patty was just. Minced meat smashed & fried? Not what you'd expect. Disappointing because on the menu it said Sausage & Maple.

Er, no it ain't halal. I just went there with a Chinese friend during fasting month once. She was hungry and wanted to fuel up, so we ended up in this popular bakery. 

It's self-service at this store, so while my friend scrambled off to pick some bites, I made a quick inspection of the premises. The bakery oozes a casual vibe and boasts such a wide array of breads, even I was tempted to try some. Prices are mid-range.

My friend returned to our table with a cup of hot chocolate, a croissant and a Squid Ink Bun with Smoked Salmon and Ham sandwich.The Squid Ink bun does look exotic with its jet-black appearance.  She said the hot chocolate was chocolatey enough. She loved the croissant - it was crunchy but did not splinter to little pieces. Her sandwich was piled high with heaps of fresh greens and slices of smoked salmon and ham. My friend could not sense any distinct squid ink flavour but found the bread very soft and buttery. I was just sitting at the table, watching her eat. Evil woman.

I do hope some day Tiong Bahru bakery sets up a halal outlet somewhere. Then I could try their mouth-watering offerings myself!

This is your go-to supper place after a night of drinking and party at Zouk. That is if you still have the energy to walk there. 

The menu is rather extensive, the massive outdoor seating occupies most of the uniquely wide sidewalk of the area. Most revelers often come by to this place because it opens till the wee hours of the night and early morning. Most of the dishes is somewhat palatable but it is definitely not a food destination in itself. But when push comes to shove, I suppose anything would do at 4am in the morning. Though I have to say that they've got a generous portion of iced drinks, that, I gotta give it to them.

text:
1 of the Coffee Bean in town which is opened 24 hours.  I hope YELP can make the necessary changes needed for this location of The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf.  When the Dining period is opened to the Public, as usual this location of Coffee Bean is packed to the brim.

Located inside a Hospital to begin with...  all in all, I have good experiences here.

May return when needed.

YES it is OPENED 24 hours..

Definitely GOOD in my books.

My favorite item is definitely the SPICY Chicken Puff.  From all the chocolate or mocha beverages to even purchasing the Pineapple Tart for Chinese New Year, I do not mind returning.

Added Bonus, to my acknowledgement, ALL locations of The Coffee Bean & Tea Leaf is Halal Certified by MUIS.  Overall 3.75 STARS!

As of P2HA, NO dining is allowed.  ONLY takeaways or to go orders plus, food deliveries options..  Hence plan accordingly.

Strong and smooth coffee that is perfect for wetting your throat and perking your spirits up. You want to come here many times to try their different food offerings as well. A beautiful and cheery spot in Beach Road to escape the crowds and hot weather.

text:
Finally got to try out abc and totally love the pastries, bread and coffee. The pain au chocolat or chocolate croissant is crispy on the outside, soft & light on the inside. Coffee tends to be on the nutty side (not sour and acidic like at other cafes) which is my personal preference. 

And the plus!! Service is good - staff smile and greet customers to start their mornings and there's a great chirpy vibe here.

text: There are a lot of variety here but really came here for tian tian chicken and rice spot. Came here in November and it was hot and humid here. There are fans by the seating area but still very hot. Definitely grab a sugar cane juice or lime juice at one of the stalls!

Lots of choices here, it's clean, I enjoyed pad thai at one of the booths and prices are not bad. There are fans inside, but can still get a little warm. Make sure to bring your own napkins. However, this place was a little touristy, so if you are looking for somewhere more for the "locals" and authentic food, then I recommend the second floor of a building on Smith Street in Chinatown. It has many many options and excellent food.

text:
Another hipster cafe? Great. There aren't enough of them to go round this little island :)

The food is generally tasty - standard fare that you would expect from a regular hipster cafe. Likewise for decor - it may not necessary "wow" you but it certainly isn't poorly done up. Would I recommend it? Yes, if you happen to be in the neighborhood.

Corned beef croquettes', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Corned beef croquettes'}]
text:
We went to Riders on a Saturday for brunch and it was packed. We overheard the staff saying that the waiting time was about half an hour. Fortunately, we'd made a reservation, so we practically sailed right past the waiting line. 

I like the atmosphere of the cafe. It was open, inviting and bustling with activity. Perfect place for people-watching. We were seated on the balcony facing the stables. My initial concern was about the smell, but it was unnoticeable. 

We had the corned beef croquettes, Riders Burger, and homemade sausages with creme fraiche scrambled eggs. The croquettes were good - the crispy, golden brown breadcrumbs gave way to creamy potatoes with the occasional chewy beef bits. The corned beef offered a pleasant pop of flavour that accented the mild potato taste. They were truly enjoyable to eat. The portion was generous too. I expected maybe two pieces of croquettes but there were four - more than enough for a starter. 

The Riders Burger was all about the beef. The other ingredients were reminciscent of Burger King's Western Whopper, but they were all overwhelmed by the beef. This burger would be perfect for meat lovers.

I chose the homemade sausages and creme fraiche scrambled eggs because they came with a leek and potato rosti. Unfortunately they looked better than they tasted. The hollandaise sauce was the best part of the dish. The scrambled eggs were fluffy and creamy, but for the most part tasteless, but that was ok as we had salt and pepper at our table. The rosti was, strangely, creamy. It was essentially fried mashed potato and leek. There was a mild taste of leek on the fried surface, but that was overpowered by the flavourless mush that was underneath. Next to the mild flavours of the eggs and mush, the sausage tasted too strong, which shocks the taste buds. I dipped most of what I could in the hollandaise to get some flavour, but there was barely a spoonful of it to begin with. 

The food may have been slightly disappointing, but the service was excellent. The crew was attentive and proactive, and we could really tell that they were properly trained to provide high-level service. For that, kudos to the staff AND the owner/management of Riders Cafe for caring. 

Service really contributes half, if not more, to customer experience and satisfaction. For this, I would definitely go back to Riders (and order other things on the menu instead).

text:
This place is really strange. And I don't just mean the food.

Start with the menu. The first page introduces the 2 chefs to you. but instead of telling you their food philosophy or style, is all about their experiences working in well-known places and how good they are. One chef is "a gifted Chef" and a "prodigy of Celebrity Chef Sady Cerna" (I think they meant protégé).

Furthermore, they have something really peculiar called "enzymes" which feature prominently in many of their desserts. I have no idea what their "enzymes" are, they probably aren't you know from biology (otherwise their desserts might decompose if kept overnight). There were samples of their "enzymes" on the table, and they looked like mostly-clear liquids (though one bottle had a lot of cloudy stuff at the bottom, making it look like what kombucha presumably looks like).

I ordered the ice cream (they were out of the "enzyme" creme brulees) and it was bad. I had 3 flavours: butterscotch, melon (with guava) and pineapple tart

The butterscotch "ice cream" was really butterscotch-flavoured heavy cream - it didn't have the taste and temperature of ice cream. The melon (with guava) ice cream had a noticeable amount of ice crystals in it. And the pineapple tart ice cream was very mild tasting.

Meanwhile, the ice cream was served with a really random assortment of toppings (apple, banana and nuts) and caramel sauce, which didn't harmonise well with the ice cream flavours.

text: Every time I'm back i try to stop by D'Good Cafe for my favorite early grey lavender latte. Also got to try their maple sea salt cheesecake which is their signature cake. The cheesecake was alright, tasty though denser than I was expecting. Service was slow (~15 minutes) even there were only 3 tables occupied and the other 2 had already gotten their orders. The cafe is in a small-ish space with cute decor. The top floor has been converted into a cocktail bar of sorts. All in all, still a great spot to come chill and have a beverage.

text:
Uber cheap and a definite budget option offering tasty food.

Restrictive for gluten free - I went to several vendors with my little dietary card and was told that there was nothing there I could have. *sad face*

Then I found a thai vendor at the main entrance who made me seafood and vegetable fried rice. Lovely seasoning, huge portion (not much seafood) but very tasty for $5 sing.

You can take away or sit at little tables provided and other vendors sell drinks, it is very popular with locals and is meant to one of the cheapest 'hawker' markets in the main city. 

Non gf peeps will have a ball as there are lots of tasty options available!

text:
Cute cafe; I would have expected nothing less from the creators of Sogurt! The place was spacious and bright (at least the main hall was). 

Food was pretty good. I had the beef bowl, which was pretty good and spicy. 
However, for healthy food, it did have a lot of sauce (and salt). 

My main gripe was the experience. 
My colleagues and I (group of 7) went there for lunch, and had ordered our food. A little while later (maybe 15 minutes or so), a group of people form MediaCorp came into the cafe. We thought they were just stopping by to grab something to eat, little did we know they were going to film. We were approached by the staff to tell us that we needed to keep quiet while they were filming. 
It was a really unpleasant lunch as we kept getting stared at when we were eating (it's not like we can help it when our utensils hit the plates/bowls). 
We would have appreciated it if the staff had informed us of the filming before we ordered so that we could decide if we wanted to go somewhere else or continue to eat there in silence.

text:
I am in total awe of this store. Like steroidal effects, the colors and packaging heightened me to maximum. Cortisol level was so high, walking thru all the aisles..

In the basement folks... look for the $6 special Jollibee sign as a cue.. 

Great product and inventory. No bakery. Meat protein section, saba fish etc is extensive

Seats are pretty limited in the indoor. Two tall long tables, three small round tables and that's it. Came here on a Friday night and I'm not surprised that it is full house inside. Luckily my friends and I didn't have to wait long for seats. 

So we heard about their waffles and had it with two scoops of ice cream. Waffles are two quadrants. It was slightly overdone on the color but still not bad. The ice cream was okay. They got my order wrong but lazy me didn't change it. Thought their dark chocolate ice cream is better than Speculoos flavour which is too sweet for me. 

Next up was Earl Grey mousse cake. It was way too sweet to my liking. Each time I reach for the cake, I could only slice a thin small piece with my fork. Thank god this cake is shared. 

They do serve mains. But I don't think I will be back anytime soon to try other stuffs.

text:
Views are fabulous. I went during the afternoon and sat outside. The beer price was not any more expensive than anywhere else but the view was phenomenal. I ordered the pork belly which was good but not great. 

I found it interesting they make the beer in full view (and full smell) behind the bar. As anyone knows who's brewed their own, that sh&t smells nasty and they kept the door to exterior open most likely for that reason. 

I would absolutely recommend this place for a date night or a beer aficionado. I only had the IPA which could have been a little hoppier but it was still tasty.

text: Probably my favorite hawker center in Singapore. I was meeting up with someone here and they were telling me the usual ground rules of "go to the place with the longest lines, cash only, and skip Tian Tian chicken rice." We ended up eating a feast here with chicken rice, fish soup, nasi lemak, BBQ duck, dumplings, oyster cake, and finished it all off with soyabean curd for dessert. Everything tasted amazing and the fact it was all ~$2-3 each probably made me love it even more. I'm glad I went with the recommendation of skipping Tian Tian as Ah Tai tasted 2x better for me. Sorry Anthony Bourdain and Gordon Ramsay, I'm going to have to go with the locals on this one.

text:
The perfect place to bond with your friends or partner! There is Xbox and Wii To choose from both consoles are really good. I prefer wii over the Xbox as its more family fun type of games. 

Recommending Super smash Bros which is awesome fighting using all Nintendo characters. There is also Xbox dance central and Kinect sports which are so fun dancing together. 

Rock band are good too. Great place

This kooky little cafe tucked away in the Upper Bukit Timah neighbourhood of Lorong Kilat is certainly no stranger to being reviewed.  When we got to Carpenter & Cook one Sunday afternoon, we were greeted simultaneously by the chatter of diners, the clinking of cutlery and the aroma of oven-baked goodies the moment we pushed through the wood-panelled door. As we waited in line for a seat, the couple next to us used a vintage display cabinet as a tabletop for filling in a form to have their pre-wedding shoot held here.

As with all wildly popular eateries, there's always a presumption that service will be brusque and impersonal. I'm happy to report that the servers we encountered at Carpenter & Cook were welcoming and chirpy. Furnished with rustic pieces acquired by one of its three co-owners from all over the world, the cafe exuded a homely and laid-back vibe in spite of the teatime crowd. Communal seating is practised here, which is fine by me since I've recently been trained not to attack openly affectionate couples.

Lavender Bundt Cake, $4.00 - Whilst surveying the pastries on display, we were a little taken aback by how steep the prices were. It took just four bites to finish this palm-sized bundt cake (we're talking preschooler hands here), which tasted quite uninspiring. It was my first encounter with lavender in cake form, though apart from some notes of cinnamon I frankly couldn't detect anything else in the cake. I also felt the honey glaze was superfluous since it added neither depth of flavor nor moisture to the cake, which was a little too dry.

Passionfruit Meringue Tart, $6.50 - Highly raved about in almost every review of Carpenter & Cook I've read, this tart had a crisp, buttery shell that broke off easily when you cut into it with a fork. The beautifully seared meringue peaks had a texture akin to toasted marshmallow innards... that's actually meant to be much more delicious than it reads. Found the passionfruit curd way too sweet, but supporters swear by it so if too much sugar's your thing, go right ahead and order this.

Smashing Savoury Brioche Bun (Veg.), $6.50 - A sprinkle of sundried tomatoes, pine nuts, olives and a couple sprigs of parsley on a fluffy brioche bun. I have to say the bun was moist, soft and wonderfully herby, but for six friggin' fifty? I wouldn't have ordered this if I were allowed to have things my own tyrannical way.

Triple chocolate chip muffin, $3.50 - This was a flat out disaster. The muffin was so dry that every poke of the fork triggered an avalanche of crumbs. Also, the chocolate used was sickeningly sweet and of exceedingly poor quality - I say this as someone who has no qualms about eating Van Houten chocolates by the boxful.

Flat White, $5.00 - Like any Singaporean cafe worth their salt, Carpenter & Cook utilises the Speakeasy blend from Liberty Coffee. Sadly, premium beans alone do not a good cup of coffee make. My flat white was served lukewarm, left a slightly acrid aftertaste, and came with zero art boohoohoo. Maybe it was because the cafe was crowded when we visited, but they could definitely pay a little more attention to detail for drink prep.

By the end of our visit we were left scratching our heads about the hype surrounding Carpenter & Cook. It's obvious that they have the leisurely come-burn-your-weekend-afternoon-with-us ambiance bit down pat, but food and price wise there's so much room for improvement you could fit Mariah Carey and her entourage in there. I'd like to think that we visited on an off-day. I guess I wouldn't mind coming back if I happen to be in the area, though it'll be an uphill task convincing me to go out of my way to visit Carpenter & Cook a second time.

text:
This fish soup store that is situated in the same coffee shop as the famous Keng Eng Kee Seafood Restaurant has no store name. Instead its signboard just display the different items that they sell and the prices. Regardless of the lack of a store name, it has become famous - drawing long queues during lunch hour on weekdays. In fact, all the tables of the coffee shop are occupied by patrons of the fish soup store, leaving little room for the other stores in the coffee shop.

The soup is amazingly sweet and delicious but not too salty. This is one of the few fish soup stores where I dare to order sliced fish instead of fried fish because their fish is really fresh and has no fishy smell at all! The thick beehoon is cooked just right too - not clumpy or soggy. 

They also sell pig's organ soup, pork porridge and yam rice to go with your soup. My suggestion is to skip the yam rice which is not very special. Try the fish soup and if you have space left, get the pig's organ soup too.

text: Classic Singaporean breakfast that you have to try! The toast on its own is really sweet, but the key to enjoying it is to add soy sauce to the liquid eggs, mix it up and then dunk the toast into the egg mixture, making sure it is well coated. Don't be afraid to scoop more on top! The cold drinks were good as well.

text: Ok as I am still shock as the sticker price of hand dripped coffee, my husband wanted to try this place. As I was getting hungry to, why not see what is so special with pricey coffee. Well I totally put my foot in my mouth, this was amazing coffee, it was strong and had a seriously amazing after taste that I just can't describe, let's just say I didn't even really need to sugar or cream at all. Now what totally sold me on this place was their Hoshino Souffle blew my mind as I never had anything like it. It was tomato fried rice at the bottom with this creamy fluffy egg like whip cream topping. It put the Omu rice to the side and now not worst eating.  The teriyaki chicken sandwich was good too. The sevice was ok but at least here is a button to call them.

Art house bohemian vibe.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Art house bohemian vibe.'}]
text:
I used to frequent Sarnies cafe a few steps away until recently when their part time staff blew me away with their lousy attitude. 

So I ventured out into the unknown and hit up Free The Robot a few steps down the road. Boy, am I glad I did! Coffee they serve are from Toby's Estate and are pretty on point. Fantastic atmosphere. Loving the nook they've created by blocking out most of the outside, so you feel like you're in a Melbourne alleyway. 

Tiny gripe is that with gst(?) my average latte from $5 came up to about $6.40. Pricey for 2 shots of coffee and some milk. 

I work around the area so that adds up pretty quickly.

An affordable hawker center in the expensive Chinatown area. Because of the area, the stalls are primarily Chinese and there aren't many choices for Indian or Halal. Beer is also incredibly expensive and only at a few stands. Some of the stalls are also open very late. Try the famous chicken rice and the fried potato balls.

I think Tully's is fortunate to be located in a place with high traffic. If not for the daily office crowd grabbing take away coffee, Tully's would have shut down a long time ago. Don't get me wrong, coffee here is far from great. Infact the only reason why the coffee sells is because Tully's is the only cafe around that area serving espresso based coffee. I have not tried the food but it does not look too appealing either. If you work around the area, I guess this is your only option for take away coffee so get used to it.

text: They've completely remodeled and the food also tastes better than I remember. Either that or I've acclimated to local tastes. A good spot for a late night meal (or any time really, I just find myself here late at night when other spots in the neighborhood are closed).

text: Like this place! We came for Sunday brunch, not crowded. Food is delicious! Cajun chicken with rice ball is yummy, Spanish omelette is not bad, veggie pasta is in big portion, my son loves it so much. Good service as well! Will comeback again to try other dishes.

text:
This is my safe brunch place, when we can't quite make up our minds where to go, we always end up here. The coffee is from liberty and so I enjoy their lattes and cappuccinos. My husband swears by their French toast with bananas and bacon, which comes with two nice thick slices of eggy fried brioche, sliced bananas, crispy bacon all drenched in maple syrup! The sweet and savory combo wins him over. 

For me I always end up with the pork cheek sandwich. I agree with Marcus L, a little bit more toasted would be great. But once Ive sunk my teeth into that porky, cheesy, oily goodness I forget all about it. The small salad that comes with it lets me delude myself of it being pretty healthy. 

Not managed to try much else at this cafe, I like that the seats are reasonably spaced out and I always manage somehow to get a table. So just based on that sandwich and French toast, will keep Flock cafe as my default place to go.

My favorite popiah stall is in this center. The fresh rolls are not soggy like other places and the filling isn't heavily sweetened. Order it with some spicy sauce. I like to wash the popiah down with some fresh juice (either watermelon or pineapple juice). Cheap, good, relatively clean, and fast local food.

Food court areas in Sentosa resorts.  This is a nice and cooler location near the universal studios and sea aquarium.  They got my order wrong but it's ok, it's cool inside and has decent WiFi.  Good place to chill and catch your breath.

Affordable fare (at least in the area) and decent enough. We had the beef sandwich, garlic prawn pizza, smoked salmon salad, ravioli and lasagna for dinner.

The beef sandwich was pretty decent and the other items were acceptable. Nothing fantastic but not badly executed either. I wouldn't mind coming here again if I were stuck in Tanglin Mall, given the dearth of options.

Good music and drinks at #1 14', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Good music and drinks at #1 14'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/q4c_pQjt3U8z2xCV6u-ADA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/old-airport-road-food-centre-singapore?reviewid=GEHThySu1OA3jYi3ve28lg&select=q4c_pQjt3U8z2xCV6u-ADA', 'altText': 'Photo of Old Airport Road Food Centre - Singapore, Singapore. Cannot go wrong with Lucky Char Kway Teow at #1 30', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Cannot go wrong with Lucky Char Kway Teow at #1 30'}]
text:
We ate here after hearing many great stories of the local food stalls within the hallowed portals of the Old Airport Road Food Centre. We were on the hunt for my new local favorite Singapore dish, Char Kway Teow and settled on unit#1 30. The stall was named Lucky and their specialty was spelled differently as Char Kuay Tiao. Minor details aside, we ordered two plates of Char Kway Teow with chili. The drink stall across the crowded way crammed with tables and people was playing Classic Rock and had Carlsberg on special offer. We also ordered a couple of drinks from the juice stall beside our Lucky stall. 

The food was great. Great flavor of cockles, Chinese chives, bean sprouts and flat noodles all cooked in light and dark soy sauce. Just the right amount of spiciness and a good sized portion. What's not to love. Washed down with Carlsberg and Soursop and Plum juice listening to old Aerosmith and ACDC, our visit was a resounding success. Cannot wait to go back.

I pass by Maccha House frequently and finally gave in at one point as I do love me some matcha, but it was underwhelming to say the least (at least compared to my expectations).

I ordered the teriyaki chicken kamameshi - chicken, rice and veggies that came with salad and soup. The portion itself was quite small, so the additional sides helped. The taste was nothing to write home about, a bit bland and required chili to make it more pleasing. 

I also ordered their iced matcha latte, while great with the amount of matcha, it was too sweet for my liking.

OK to have tried as a one time option.

text:
3.5

Loved the atmosphere, very siimlar to the bars we used to frequent in New York so I instantly bookmarked it for dessert places to take visitors. it's located right across from the popular thai joint we frequent in Holland V. 

We got the Churros and Hot chocolate dip, sold separately, and it was good enough, except that the churros kept falling apart and was a bit over fried. but you really can't go wrong with churro + chocolate, so it was satisfying enough!

The fail of a dish was the Purple, with blackberry sorbet and lavendar marshmallows, which we expected more from the price and by the raving reviews on Yelp. We had better desserts elsewhere for much cheaper- it was basically Manhattan prices with child-size portions and no wow-factor. Another downer was the sad waiter in his 20s- he looked as if he hated working there and didn't' say ONE word when handing us/collecting the check and as we were leaving. It was just an odd sight to see at such a hip bar but hopefully next time he's in a better mood. overall, great place to go with friends for the atmosphere and perhaps drinks, but not for the dessert alone.

text:
Alway a lime at this outlet at lunch time.

Good quality sandwiches and croissants.

Almond croissant was a little heavy. Some sweet thing stuffed inside that makes it a bit jelat.

Coffee is strong.

Friendly service. Systematic way of dealing with the crowd.

From the notice board, I found that they have another 100% gluten free cafe called The Butcher's Wife which is about 5 minutes from this cafe.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/PMiZELJyFLd5mnMBVJxZuA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/chef-icon-nature-bakery-singapore?reviewid=Rqk7ZaoFX1aWgciyCJrqpA&select=PMiZELJyFLd5mnMBVJxZuA', 'altText': 'Photo of Chef Icon Nature Bakery - Singapore, Singapore. Yakiniku Style Mushroom Clubman', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Yakiniku Style Mushroom Clubman'}]
text:
Chef icon nature bakery is one of those place that no one knows about, but once you have had their signature cakes. you will want to know where it is.

their 2 signature cakes are Chocolate Trovana & new york cheese cake, and they are only available in whole cakes (500g, 1kg, Choco Trovana also comes in 2kg) and you gotta order them 2 to 3 days in advance. 

Francis also makes a whole list of stuff, baked goods, cakes (yes there are cakes available in slices), kaya, peanut butter with the same principles: Best natural ingredients, no preservatives, with lots of passion and love.

Drop by, get a clubman sandwich. and a flat white. (i know the duxton/ everton road area is full of gourmet coffeeshops, but he does a good cuppa too)

Closed on Sunday and Public Holidays.

text:
Oh wow, the prices are high compared with what I'm used to paying in the USA.

In Miami pay a little less than $5 for a tall coffee and here it was about $7.5

The place was clean, with nice background music, and wonderful service.

I got my Singapore Mug in here, as usual when I travel and I love it!!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/gKznZdUkDlOB4e3EXSOkzA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/laurent-bernard-chocolatier-singapore?reviewid=VgPuKGrVYnpty_0bcwcVLQ&select=gKznZdUkDlOB4e3EXSOkzA', 'altText': 'Photo of Laurent Bernard Chocolatier - Singapore, Singapore. rum and raisin souffle', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'rum and raisin souffle'}]
text:
Our absolute favourite is the Rum and Raisin souffle. To. Die. For. They use golden sultanas that burst with rum in your mouth and vapours of rum hits the back of your throat at first bite. Just recalling the experience makes me salivate. The souffle comes with a vanilla cream made of vanilla pods and not some processed food flavourings. You'll think it'll be too sweet but the cold vanilla with hot soufflet neutralise each other and the taste is heaven. 

The down side? Having to wait 30 minutes for it to be made on the spot. So if you are having dinner next door, come by and order it in advance and they will call you when it's ready. But the minute it's made, you have to eat it or it will collapse. It was actually ready at about 15-20 min. They could even serve it at Brussels sprouts next door if you are having dinner there.

I used to love going to PS Cafe for brunch during the weekend but I find that since practically a year, the food quality has degraded.
Is it cost cutting?, I am not sure but I wish their food was a good as before...
For example, their steak sandwich used to be so good. But the last time I ordered it, the bread and steak was different and ended up not being as tasty as before. The meat is so thin and dry now compare to the thick juicy one before.

First up, I'm not as discerning in the taste bud department as some others. I'm actually rather plebeian so subtle, nuanced eats and I don't really click. Next, I view hipster/indie joints with a morbid fascination. On one hand, it's revolting. I can't cycle so I don't see the allure of a bamboo bike. On the other hand, I quite like cement/brick walls and exposed pipes. 

Anyhow. You need reservations for this place. They write your name, time slot and number of pax on a rock so you know which table is yours, which is.. interesting because it looks like a bible verse. You know- Timothy 3:16 that kinda thing. 

Eggs are supposed to be done well here, so eggs it was. I had two eggs in a pepper puree sauce populated with an incredible amount of chopped sausage, while the other diner had eggs ben with maple glazed bacon. And because we were greedy, we had a cold cut platter to share too. And the eggs. Oh the runny eggs. My inner auntie frowns upon ordering a pair of eggs for $20 when you can get 10 for $2, but she's easily placated with cold cuts. Which were ok, really. Smoked salmon, parma ham and some cured meat thing that came with blue cheese and another slab of even smellier cheese. I do love me some smelly cheese. The mains fared much better though, and the other diner was pretty happy with the nosh. As the day wore on (we were there at 11), the place was absolutely buzzing with activity, but happily we were free to just chill. 

On the downside, the place is really cramped. Every time someone walks behind me, I get bumped, which is all the time. You can't really tell wait staff from diners, which can be a bit confusing since everyone's wearing those tortoise shell rimmed spectacles, sporting a tattoo or turned up pants. And the price point is on the high side for a place located opposite a cemetery (cemetery. symmetry. is there a link?). Would I return? Well, yes, but only when it's pay day.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/nJmW656F7gbZU93kS77I4Q/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/wild-honey-singapore-3?reviewid=iXkrTF7sGo5-L5bpjuON4Q&select=nJmW656F7gbZU93kS77I4Q', 'altText': 'Photo of Wild Honey - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/0Ve-IZyPnoebd9-XVPqaLw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/wild-honey-singapore-3?reviewid=iXkrTF7sGo5-L5bpjuON4Q&select=0Ve-IZyPnoebd9-XVPqaLw', 'altText': 'Photo of Wild Honey - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
Definitely on my go to list for weekend brunch. The ambiance here is quite pleasant for weekend gathering and stuff although it is rather noisy (lots of echoes but well it's quite common in dense SG isn't it?). The waiter are welcoming and are not intrusive at all despite the fact the place was crowded, which i really appreciate as I was able to catch up with my friend comfortably without feeling hurried to leave. 

Onto the main highlight, food. Pricewise, it's rather pricey (bout $30/pax) but portion is quite generous. We ordered the English breakfast and the Boulevard St Michel and it was delicious. I like the fact that jn both of our dishes, they successfully poached the eggs so it has firm whites but runny yolks which I adore. I also liked that they serve our dishes at the same time and are responsive whenever we call them although it was a busy day. 

Unfortunately, the coffee was a rather let down. We ordered the cold brew coffee but too bad it tasted more like your ordinary cup of joe on ice. I may be a bit of coffee snob but I believe cold brew should be slightly stronger and more aromatic. Nevertheless, my friend, whom is not a coffee drinker, enjoys it. So i guess it depends on your preferences.

All in all, i would recommend this place to people who seeks for a good brunch at central location. I would advice you to reserve your seats as it may be hard to get a seat, unless you don't mind sitting at the bar, facing the columns.

great brunch place and a very cool spot to eat and lounge in general. 

spanish baked eggs - hearty, tasty and loved the bread and small skillet it came in
the club - SO stinking good! the bacon was crispy and the amount of chicken was sizable. i would come back for this again and again.
pate - was only ok, i prefer my pate to be creamier. however, i liked that they have a wide variety of cured meats to choose from and i'm very curious about their other options. 

all in all, really enjoyed it and one of the few places i've had a good western meal.

Chinatown Complex: grungy, unbearably hot, dirt cheap...and yet awesome food. 

This is definitely a local's style food court upstairs in a sprawling ugly concrete building above a  market in Chinatown.  We went for breakfast a couple times since we were staying across the street and they have pretty much everything you could want.  Mainly there for Bedok chee kueh (google "chee kueh", and then go try some) and it didn't disappoint. Look for the stall right by the escalators to the left.   

We also ran into an enthusiastic local, who told us the soy sauce chicken stall here is actually better than the Michelin starred one across the street, which was a nice little tip.  Satay available later on in the day, but the famous Tian Tian fish porridge stall way in the back is open early.  And popiah.  So much goodness in one place!  There's even a craft beer stall (this place is actually becoming hipsterfied?).

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/lgoiiKQ2SZcs1N0w4Z8npA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/two-men-bagel-house-singapore?reviewid=rqVKoKwqp1pzY0eyYVOMvA&select=lgoiiKQ2SZcs1N0w4Z8npA', 'altText': 'Photo of Two Men Bagel House - Singapore, Singapore. Smoked beef bagel. Don&#39;t remember the actual name.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "Smoked beef bagel. Don't remember the actual name."}]
text:
Let's face it, bagels for $10 in Singapore is like chicken rice for £30 in London. You have to make sacrifices if you're not eating local specialties. 

Once I got over that, it was great. Every choice so far has been done perfectly, the bagel toasted yet soft, the ingredients top quality. The smoked beef one is particularly good, although being able to go and buy a decent smoked salmon bagel in Singapore still remains one of my favourite discoveries in the relative food desert of Tanjong Pagar. 

The filling is generous enough that these days we split one between two, but we're not big eaters. Service is fast and friendly.

Came in for the Sunday roast. What did I end up getting served was a VERY dry Sunday roast. Veggies were cooked all right, not mushy. However, the beef was very dry and couldn't even be reconstituted with gravy. Friendly but slow service as well. Definitely would not come back here.

The brunch here is one of the better ones I've had in Singapore for the longest time. 

The ambience here is great and you can spot many other like minded individuals and families here having coffee and enjoying the food.

It's shaded from the sun, thanks to a large awning and there's ample smoking area. the fans provide just the right amount of breeze should you choose to sit outside, or you can sit in air-conditioned comfort inside and watch the chefs prepare your meal, thanks to an open kitchen concept.

text:
This place is a little small and there is a space constraint so be prepared to go early during the peak timings or you might not find a seat. I find the food there quite good and i like the mushroom soup, though more to the salty side but i like my mushroom soup salty rather than bland.

I think that i would most probably go back for the coffee as i think the food is pretty average. The coffee is really valued for money as it is cheaper then Starbucks and the other usual coffee places yet tastes quite aromatic and different.

Service was really sincere and heart warming as well, a nice place to chill but mainly people go there for the coffee.

text: Came here before during weekday and was impressed with appetiser buffet.  Returned for the roast Sunday lunch and was less impressed.  The food was just decent and the service was very Ho-hum.  Except for the kids menus and plastic cutlery there wasnt even paper or crayons to draw, let alone toys.  The dessert was very very average.  Go there for the beer, cocktail and the view (which was stunning even on a hazy day) but we wouldn't be rushing back.

Definitely one of the best hawker centres in SIngapore! Maxwell is lined up with row after row of local delicacies, and they're some of the most tasty food in Singapore.

If you only have room or time for one thing, make it the Thai food stall, which makes one of my favourite phad thai on the island. The chicken rice is also great, although somehow people have a love/hate relationship with it.

Some of the stalls open late, so if you're hitting the night spots in the area you can always drop by for some chow.

text:
Rider's is on the favourites list of many brunch-goers, which is why if you plan to have a brunch date here on weekends, you better plan well ahead because its hard to get a seat if you didn't make reservations. 

Fairways Drive is not a place you want to go to if you don't drive, if you're taking a cab, you'll have to direct the cab driver because not many are familiar with the place. 

But even with its remote accessibility, its still packed! Because the food and ambience are something you'd travel for, they're that good.

To me, they have the best pancakes! Fluffy, buttery, creamy goodness with fresh blueberries and cream. Their poached eggs and salmon comes a close second. Plus enjoying it in a cosy setting against the greenery with horses grazing in the background doesn't hurt!

You can take a walk outside and maybe have your kids go on a pony ride (only $10!) after brunch, its not just a nice romantic brunch place but good for families too.

Final verdict: One of the most quaint brunch places in Singapore in one of the last countryside corners of this urban jungle.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/vFL2hpGLTfcWxsbarN4sWA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/boomarang-singapore?reviewid=QczmdZUcUZ1EhVdfu5ed3A&select=vFL2hpGLTfcWxsbarN4sWA', 'altText': 'Photo of Boomarang - Singapore, Singapore. Brekky menu :)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Brekky menu :)'}]
text:
Really nice place to hang out with a group of friends over a cuppa coffee. They serve a wide range of drinks with both a breakfast and a lunch/dinner menu. 

I had the chai latte and my mum had her latte. Both were equally fabulous. My chai had some really nice foam on the top which I seriously loved. 

Sadly, we didn't order any food but their breakfast menu looked and sounded delicious. (I uploaded a picture of their brekky menu)

Definitely recommend this place.

text: Line was long but moved fast. $3.50 per and $19.50 for six pieces. The cheese tarts are light and melt in your mouth. The cheese is a little gooey once bitten. It's a perfect accompaniment with tea or coffee. I wish I were able to bring this back home... I am already dreaming of eating more.

text:
Had their Toblerone coffee mocha today for the very first time. Def loving it so soo much! It's a great choice if you are not really in the mood for some strong coffee. You'd be able to taste both the dark chocolate and the coffee right from the first sip to the last drop. They don't use any kind of syrup at all in all kind of their chocolate mocha drinks (not like Starbucks). I can testify on that cos I saw the whole process when my barista was making my drink. Here you'll be spoiled by choice for your chocolate options. You could pick any of these: Cadbury, Toblerone, van Houten, Milka, Lindt, Godiva. You could literally have different chocolate coffee mocha mix everyday.

My old times favorite are definitely Hawaiian latte, cold brew and matcha latte. Even though there are 2 other coffee shops in the same building, YCC would get my vote by a lot. The barista here definitely knows what they are doing. The coffee always tastes consistently very good all day every day.

text:
We got the set which included a coffee, toast and two eggs for less than $5. We also got their coconut rice wrapped in a banana leaf.

If you want to get the same food for half the price, go to a hawker spot. If not, enjoy this chain haha. It's the same taste wise and in a nice, air conditioned mall!

Fast service, delicious iced Teh Tarik and humongous take-away cups. The fact that its called the Mr. Teh Tarik Cartel is curious but the prices don't seem inflated despite the allusion to monopolistic price fixing.

text:
Great ambience, pretty good service, delicious Sunday brunch.

Highlights:
Dry laksa was delicious- we were way too ambitious and ordered 2 for a table of 4. But no regrets!
Babi pong Tay - perfectly done stewed pork. Wow
Kuey pie tee- another yummy appetizer that everyone should try. 

Younger waitstaff a little blur, but the older ones were on it. Better training, perhaps? 
Will return for another brunch when I'm back on the island!

text:
This is a new joint the block replacing my old favorite Java Kitchen.  Since it looked clean and nice, we went in for some dessert and damn!  Their oreo cheesecake is to die for.  And a tiny Oreo on top to make it extra cute.  And their hot chocolate?  Perfect to end the night.  

I highly recommend it

I've been in here a few times, always on my way to see a movie at The Cathay. Why? For me, it's all about the beer. They usually have 2 taps of Archipelago's small batch beer, which is a perfect pre- (or post-) movie drink. The desserts are good, too. I love their sticky date pudding. And I've been told that their coffee is quite nice...
It's been popular every time I've been there, so it gets a bit noisy for my taste. But I'm an old guy, so consider the source. ;-)

Came here on a Sunday morning and was positively surprised with the food and coffee. (Most of the restaurants on Robertson Quay are popular only because of the location and not the food). The staff is also attentive and friendly.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/jnSBwh4H2g2XzcKMG-GVQw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/clinton-street-baking-company-and-restaurant-singapore?reviewid=RhVXYYsYZ4DtCnbrpwX_8Q&select=jnSBwh4H2g2XzcKMG-GVQw', 'altText': 'Photo of Clinton Street Baking Company & Restaurant - Singapore, Singapore. Mangled upside down pineapple cake', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Mangled upside down pineapple cake'}]
text:
My first time here. Ever. Didn't know about the New York branch so there is no basis for comparison. I've heard lots of excited rumblings of course, and friends who used to live in New York were thrilled about its opening. Fair enough. From all accounts, I hear that this place largely works. The food is comparable and all. I'll have to take their word for it. 

I only came here for some cake and I got the upside down pineapple cake. I don't know why but seeing a badly sliced and sloppily presented cake annoyed me. It shows a lack of care in the attentive-level of staff.

When I went to pay, I noticed that other cakes (of other flavors) were similarly badly sliced. Woah. 

I really did think Clinton St Bakery was better than this. 

Taste-wise, the cake was fine. Not great, not terrible. The staff was sufficiently polite. But I think the devil's in the details and they need to teach their staff how to slice cakes properly, lift the slices and place them on plates.

text: 100% based on friendly accomodating staff.  Decent breakfast.  Great ambience.  Good location.  OK, admittedly, I am severely biased in their favour.  The last 8 times I have been there it was to watch football games on widescreen TVs.  This is a cozy sports bar with multiple screens to watch several live games.  They allow groups to reserved tables and watch games and tolerate the cheers and noise.  Went to an upstairs wine tasting there years ago that was quite good.  Also have done a few upstairs lunches.  Decent fare, good price.  When it's left turn to Molly's or right turn to Boomarang, there is no hesitation.  Right is the right way to go for food and drink.

Kopi-O to go', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Kopi-O to go'}]
text: My mornings now have a new ritual: getting a Kopi-o to go from The Old Tea Hut, with the friendly and very efficient staff, for less then 2 S$. Amazing value for a strong, sweet cup that keeps me going for (nearly) the whole day :-)

I found a review online that mentioned the Ribeye steak was worth a shot! Steak in a cafe didn't seem like the natural option but none of the other items on the menu impressed me much so I decided to go for it! What's the worst that could happen? $27 wasted and a sad face. 

Boy! Was I glad I decided to take the path less travelled! The Ribeye steak was delicious (I had it medium done)! Unfortunately, the same cannot be said about their burgers! 

My friend asked the cashier, "what's good here?"
She replied, "up to you lor"
Unsatisfied with the answer I chimed in, "but what would you recommend?"
She asked, "the burger" 
He decided to go with her recommendation but we weren't impressed. The meat was subpar. It tasted kinda chewy and over marinated... kinda like cheap sausage meat grounded into a patty? Either she has poor taste or she gave him really bad information. 

Coffee-wise, I really didn't think that they were as good as Nylon etc. Passable but it wasn't impressive.

Service was also rather slow that day. My steak came out on time but my friends' food didn't. 

Ambiance-wise, Wheeler is unbeatable! A beautiful hipster cafe! I love the concept and the deco. Not so much the location and the parking. There's barely enough lots to fit 5% of the customers. They only have 4 lots out front. All 4 were taken when we arrived. Plus, the remote location (an industrial like area) didn't really help because it wasn't very accessible via public transportation so I wished they had more parking space!
The staff is very prompt and anxious to get you seated quickly. The food comes quickly also. It's quite a bit of food for the money. Very spacious seating area and the staff is very friendly.

Having only been here once, I asked what was their most popular famous dish and just ordered one of those.  (BBQ Chicken)  the chicken came in a quarter slice with rice and sambal sauce. While the flavor was tasty itself, the chicken was dry. 

This restaurant is located in a convenient location for businesses employees nearby. There is both indoor and outdoor seating.

text: Prawns for breakfast? Sure, why not? This is a cute place to have both Singapore based food and the American breakfast---both utterly crucial to WHERE me and my boyfriend were going to eat (he wanted American vs I wanted Singapore food). Tolido's came to the rescue! Although the walk was a bit of a hike from where we were staying (Bugis shopping mall area), it was worth the walk. The service was spot on and the wait wasn't too terrible. Granted, I still recommend making reservations if you want a spot inside! It can get pretty busy otherwise.

Good rating, mainly atmosphere, nice view,  just had wine and olives/apps.  Very attentive staff,  nice stop over after s stroll throughout the gardens

text: The coffee is good, really good. But under no circumstances is it appropriate to wait 30 minutes for a coffee. We ordered, received our food. I went to the counter after 15 minutes to confirm they remembered our coffees. Food now finished. Someone comes over to confirm our coffee order and we repeat our order. 15 more minutes we receive a coffee. This place has great potential, but great coffee without great service makes for an average experience.

Large display of sweet treads by the till, the Earl Grey Cheesecake looks yummy! Staff are informative and very friendly. Wish I lived near by!

text:
Love their service and especially their sticky date pudding. One of the most value for money sticky date pudding I've had and the portion and taste is awesome! The way the sticky date pudding is served is also rather different from any others out there. You have the ice cream sandwiched between 2 slices of cake and the sauce around. A good way to have a spoonful of all the goodies in one mouth. 

They also serve half portions for pasta and sandwiches. Check with the server to get more info on that. 

Do note that it's really crowded during meal times so go during off peak to enjoy your meal in peace.

text: Probably a good thing for my waist line that  I found this spot on my last day in Singapore.  The salted caramel chocolate tart (gluten free) paired extremely well with my iced coffee.  The flavors were well balanced, rich, but somehow not too sweet.  They also had savory buttery crusted pies and other delicious items to choose from. You can take items to go or eat in.  The space was a needed respite after a long day on my feet.  Very cozy and somewhat darkened interior, delicious food at decent prices, and friendly staff.  You order upfront and pay at the cash register. Take a number and find a seat.  The food is then delivered to you.   Exactly what the doctor ordered.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/-sJePOSVKkOAwJ07CZK83g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/common-man-coffee-roasters-singapore?reviewid=u782m7T5KLaLlVFet256rg&select=-sJePOSVKkOAwJ07CZK83g', 'altText': 'Photo of Common Man Coffee Roasters - Singapore, Singapore. Veggie Wonderland', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Veggie Wonderland'}]
text:
The Veggie Wonderland was delicious. I adore grilled haloumi!  I'm very happy to have found a healthy breakfast spot in my hood. 

But...regardless of how popular a restaurant is, you should never have to wait 35 minutes for food. They should reconsider how many covers they can serve at once without hurting the diners overall impression.

This is the first true farm to table in Singapore. Tucked among the trees off of Holland Road before you hit Dempsey Hill is this great new secret.  It used to be a casual bar the husband and I used to go to when we arrived here in 2013. I think it served the 9 hole golf course that was across Minden Road.  However when the golf course closed to make way for progress (aka The brown line) It closed. Then Jim Thompson used it for a bit as a our side bar area.  Now its Open Farm Community.  As a member of the community I welcome it!

Totally redo its reminds me of the farm to table restaurants in the USA.  Very shabby/rustic chic interior with wood floors and walls, floor to ceiling windows facing the herb farm.  Small bar area, open kitchen and cool lighting with reclaimed rot iron panels on the ceiling with fairy lights,  

Try the chilled avocado soup, its to die for. I order it every time, clean, fresh, cooling for this climate.  Mains I've had are the barrumindi grilled to perfection and rigatoni is done with a pesto sauce that is not too oily or too basil infused.  I also have had the warm broccoli salad with pine nuts, just devine,  It is truly warm and not hot or luke warm.

If you are in to clean eating, this is a place you need to try. Make reservations as the word is out, this place is the best clean eating restaurant in Singapore.

I like the food here.  It takes a while to be served, but I think their Italian food quality is quite good.  Try the pasta.
一見単なるカフェにしか見えませんが、きちんとメニューには料理があります。イタリアンが多いですが、トマトパスタも悪くないですし、日本人的にはアリかと。料理が出てくるまで時間がかかるのが玉に瑕。
ちょっぴり高めかなと思う部分はありますが、まともなのでまたいつか行きます。2015/11
p.s. 同じビルに出来たjamiesもそろそろ試したいところ。空いてきたかな？

text:
Unlike CHSS and Nylon, Common Man Roasters patron base is made up of an unusually large number of Westerners, akin to dining at PF Changs in The States.  The expat crowd is decidedly CBD in neck knot style and a far cry from the "hipster" look that so many other reviewers comment on.

I prefer the more "local" atmosphere at Chye Seng Huat Hardware (CHSS), where there is a livelier vibe and coffee aficionados are actually speaking with one another rather than having their heads buried in a mobile device.

A large dining room welcomes guests to a full breakfast and lunch menu complete with creative and delicious dishes as well as wonderfully prepared coffee drinks.  Bonus points for the French glassware in which lattes are served, I had purchased these very same glasses at Merci in Paris last November.

text:
Read about this place on a cafe hunter's blog and hence I sought it out.

The only cafe I had visited that listed the controversial Flat White right at the top of its coffee offering!!!! The coffee was really really good, in the sense that I did not noticed I had finished off my cup so quickly without realizing it! I was alone. The rain outside just started. Either the cup was smaller than my usual or that the coffee was indeed too good for me to notice my greedy gulps (I swear I thought I was sipping :(). My cuppa break was accompanied by a slice of banana bread, which was tasty and delightfully moist despite its look.

Alas the service staff were too zoned out to make me feel embraced. The place was relatively big but emotionless.

text:
I stopped here briefly for a community meeting and only had tea, so I can't comment on the coffee or food. But I can tell you that you can still find the best sellers here (Taisho Black, Taisho MAD Milk.) Also, I really enjoyed the ambiance though I wouldn't say it's as cosy as their flagship in Somerset (that one will always be my favourite!) 

However, if you're looking for a not-too-corporate cafe to meet up with someone, in a very convenient location, this one fits the bill. 

I also noticed a lot of freelancers chillin' with their laptops and werkin' away in the open area, so this is also great for werk x 5 (just... sing the Rihanna version for me, please!)

Egg Island with Additional Mushrooms.', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Egg Island with Additional Mushrooms.'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/MMoQQqxVRX83J1m6AsQ9zg/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/oh-deli-singapore?reviewid=dPPej1j4cMKLv1gems7-fg&select=MMoQQqxVRX83J1m6AsQ9zg', 'altText': 'Photo of Oh Deli - Singapore, Singapore. Omelette!', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Omelette!'}]
text:
We happened to discover Oh Deli quite by accident and what an accident it was. 

From the outside, it doesn't look like much. 
Even at a first glance, the menu isn't fancily done.
But what it lack on these aesthetics was made up 100% by the food. 

Omelette ($10.90)
Freshly made and piping hot, the omelette isn't your fold over, elegant omelette. These are more, cook-in-a-skillet, hearty, home made omelettes and it tasted like it too. 
Made with really fresh ingredients, it was lightly seasoned and allowed each ingredient to be nicely highlighted. 
Simple, fuss free, hearty and satisfying. 

Egg Island ($14.50 + $4.00 for additional grilled mushroom) 
This feels like the ultimate comfort British breakfast. 
Baked beans were nicely cooked, soft without being mushy. 
The poached egg was perfect. And I mean PERFECT! The white wrapped around the yolk beautifully and the yolk was nice, thick and runny.
Sour dough was pretty good without being too sour (which I personally prefer). The mushrooms were well cooked with minimal seasoning but was packed with flavor and the sausage was so so so good. 
Not overly seasoned, the sausage had a great meat to fat ratio and was nicely coarse. Yummy!

The food here was very well done. Slightly on the mid-price side due to most of their ingredients being organic or free ranged (which is better than paying for for "fancy" all day breakfasts) but what they did was make a good hearty breakfast... well... good and hearty without being overly fancy or hipsterish. 

Will definitely recommend you check out this place if you're around the area and Oh! (All pun intended), it's also a grocery store so you can grab some really great ingredients while waiting for your food to be served too!

text: Populus is really popular. There is a wait for a table. And if you think that is the hard part, try waiting for the food. We waited for an hour for one of the main dishes. That's being said, I loved my populous scramble and flat white. But I will definitely not come here unless I have time to wait...

I love this bar.  It's obviously a bit out of the way if you don't happen to be out on Sentosa already, but the view alone is worth the trip.  You can recline on super comfy day beds while enjoying cocktails and snacking on tapas, and soaking in that view.

text: If you visit Singapore and want to try some street-food - literally - try the satay in Boon Tat street. The  street (on the front doorstep of the Singapore Exchange) closes from 7PM to 3AM and the satay stales opens up. The merchants will pester you to choose their stalls - my favorite is 3/4 at the Robinson Road end of the street.  Just sit down. The menus and beer lady will arrive promptly and enjoy some great satay.

At this point, I'm no longer shocked by prices in this part of town. Anywhere in one north is almost exclusively catering for ex-pats and high-income locals. Jimmy Monkey is no different. Egg's Benedict will run you a whopping $24, pancakes are $14, and the french toast is $17.

They had run out of pancakes on a Sunday at noon so I went with the french toast, and added on a chocolate, peanut butter, speculoos shake for good measure. This was not a wallet-friendly brunch but I was happily surprised by how tasty everything was. The french toast comes in a healthy serving, and includes berries and crème fraîche. By the end I was actually struggling to finish my serving because everything was so sweet.

I wouldn't be opposed to returning but this place is definitely a treat, and not a joint for regular meals. Seating is fairly limited, but somehow sufficient for the number of patrons. It gets a little warm, and the space does feel a little cramped. Nonetheless there are a variety of seating options depending on what you're up to.

text:
Smelly sofa seats!!! Super stinky and wet sofa. Really terrible stench! 

Not my first time at Hoshino Coffee, but this is probably going to be my last. At least for this branch. 

They are known for their drip coffee, matcha and soufflé. They have pretty good pasta too. This is based on past knowledge and past visits.

Today, we just popped in for a cup of matcha green tea. ($7!) For a Japanese chain, ordering matcha green tea should be a very safe choice. Unfortunately, it was extremely terrible! It tasted like instant green tea, it looks green but taste plain and bitter. It super disappointing. 

The thing that annoyed me most was the horrible smell. It smelled like stinky sweat all over the fabric of the sofa. It was so bad that I had to ask my friends to move to another seat. It stink too but was just so slightly better. I highly suspect it's the dirty, moist and stinky cloth that they use to wipe across all the surfaces that is causing the stench. 

The only redeeming factor is that the service is good. Good but not enough to redeem itself from the horrible smell and drink.
