text: Cute space. Pretty good coffee. Every item on the menu has too many elements. They take the no substitutions thing too far. I wanted ciabatta instead of foccacia under my smashed avo. Seriously. Is it really that hard? Why do you have so many different breads then?

Kith is a cute, cozy place on the quieter side of Robertson Quay .  

It's one of those places I'd been meaning to try for years, literally, and I finally got round to it about about 2 months ago - this tells you I've got quite a backlog of reviews!

Kith offers a decent selection of food (ranging from biccies to small bites to traditional full breakfasts and to sandwiches) at reasonable price points, e.g. $10 for a sandwich.  Our table only tried several simple food items like the smoked salmon sandwich, brioche with yogurt and strawberries, and a tuna + green apple toastie.  Even simple dishes can sometimes go awry, but I'm happy to report that all these items were well executed and presented.

Where I felt a bit let down was in the coffee department.  I'd heard a lot about Kith's coffee and had been tremendously looking forward to trying it.  However, the coffee was disappointingly average.  I'd certainly put places like Toby's Estate and Smitten above Kith in the coffee stakes.

Still, Kith is a pleasant place that's hard to dislike.  It's a comfortable place which is family-friendly, pet-friendly and offers ample people watching opportunities.  If I lived in RQ, I'd be happy to call it my local.

A very cute two story café with a nice ambience. First of all, why people come here? To have their face printed on a drink. I must admit I'm one of them. But it is a very unique experience that ill remember- drinking myself. I ordered a honey milk which is nice! ( I like honey and milk) 
The most unique drink experience ever (But quite a one time experience for me)
If you have not been there before, I recommend trying it for yourself!!!
Honey milk- 7/10

Sin Hoi Sai Eating House - If I lived anywhere closer to the East, I am guessing I would be here a lot more than I'd be willing to admit. In a tight group of 8 friends, 7 of them live pretty close to Sin Hoi, and these 7 congregate here for dinner at least 2-3 times a week.

On the few occassions I've been here, service has been excellent, also in part due to the fact that my friends are regulars. They swiftly take your order for beverages, leave, bring them to your table and collect your food orders while they are at it. On weekends this place does get crowded, so avoid peak dinner timings, or be prepared to wait for a table and for your food orders to be served.

We have a few favourites, I'll list them out - do be certain to give them a try! We love going for their sambal char siew fried rice, prepared with an adequate amount of spice and served in a portion good for 1 person. We swear by their Indonesian chicken dish, a slightly tangy crispy chicken dish where the fried chicken is glazed with a light, spicy gravy and onions. Being chicken fans, we almost always have to have their hot plate chilli ginger chicken as well - a bowl of it dropped right on to the hot plate at your table so it's sizzling and all the more enjoyable when had with the fried rice. The few other favourites include their baby kailan in oyster sauce, crispy noodles, fried salad you tiao, sambal kang kong and prawn paste chicken. 

Their menu is expansive, and I wouldn't say that the food here is inexpensive, but given it's prime location and good quality, you pay for what you get. (I spend an average of $10 - 15 here including soft drinks and food shared with about 4-5 friends). I would definitely have to come back here many more times to try everything else on their menu. Lucky I have friends who are regulars.

text:
another hawker center with tons of eating options.. we came with a couple other people and pretty much ordered everything 

bbq pork.. duck rice.. roasted chicken rice.. fish ball soup... noodles with shark meat.. noodle soups.. oyster omelette.. bak kut teh with noodles.. laksa.. char kway teow.. and a bunch of fruity desserts.. 

you gotta come here if you like cheap delicious food..

My mum is in love with this eating house, and then she made us all fall in love with the awesome hor fun and sambal kangkong. There is a charred fried flavour that the chinese call "wok hey" with the hor fun and they have concocted a really solid sambal  for their vegetables. Prices are really reasonable, for a family dinner with 4-5 dishes, we would probbly pay $60- $70.

 It can get really crowded and noisy over the weekends. So if you're starving maybe it's not so good an option to go for dinner on a weekend.

I am a fan, the food is excellent and healthy. It is a tad expensive but I would not expect otherwise given the quality and location of this place. A random find that I warmly recommend to those who love simple and high quality meals and olive oil.

text:
A great treat to the neighbourhood. I've followed Vanessa from Holland V to Tiong Bahru and even to some of her pop-ups. She has been consistently fabulous at her baking. 

She keeps things simple and in this day and age, it's the most welcoming approach to bakeries. While her HV store is small and cosy, this is welcoming and enticing. I love the wide space and benches. The counter space allows us to stand in front and ponder. Her selection as always, spoils us like an only child in the family. I am always drawn to a salted caramel or special of the day. 

A new old favourite is earl grey lavender cuppie. An old because I always had it in USA but never in Singapore. Thank you for bringing it here. 

Have yet to attend her events. Plain Vanilla has a line up of events through out the month so pop over to their facebook for more details.

Really great place to grab a cup of filter coffee and perhaps a pastry or two. I found it through a recommendation from the friendly guy running Revolution Coffee who recommended a visit. 

The tiny roaster roast their own coffee and it can occasionally be found wt other places in Singapore but it is really nice to visit here and also pick up some beans for your home-brewing needs.

If it was not in such an inconvenient place I would surely visit every time I am in Singapore

text:
Nice place for a weekend brunch, loved the natural light filtering through its ample windows and lush greenery surrounding the restaurant. 

Reservations HIGHLY recommended. We visited on a Sat morning at 11, right when it opened, without a reservation. We were turned away by the hostess, who informed us that the restaurant was fully booked till 3. She did offer to seat us at the bar, thankfully, which held only 4 people. Other customers who arrived later without reservations were turned away disappointedly - not a very smart move, given that I saw many empty tables that were being held for later reservations. Service staff weren't very forthcoming nor friendly either, and the food did take some time to arrive. Not ideal for the brunch rush hour. 

Coffee is by Common Man, so they were expectedly decent. :)

We tried:
- Eggs Benedict with poached chicken, spinach, semi-dried tomatoes, sourdough & green curry hollandaise sauce ($24): eggs were beautifully poached, yolks were a rich golden orange. I particularly enjoyed the twist on the hollandaise though. The green curry taste definitely shone, though it might not be for everyone. 

- Truffle scrambled organic egg, shimeji mushrooms, portobello mushrooms, baby spinach & sourdough ($24): would recommend ordering this dish. The egg was soft and flavorful and the mushrooms were generously portioned. Went excellently on the sourdough. 

- Lemon tart with basil ice cream ($17): I'd heard so much about this dish before visiting that I HAD to order it (despite the price). It didn't disappoint. Presentation was gorgeous and was reminiscent of a Mille-feuille. I'd have preferred the lemon curd to have been on the tarter side though. The basil ice cream was refreshing and went wonderfully with the lemon. Thoroughly enjoyed it. 

Portions aren't big for the price, but we left satiated. Would return to try its other dishes during lunch/dinner!

text:
I've been to other breakfast cafes like Wild honey, common man, and W39, and I've found a new favourite in d'good. I came across it on Yelp, so I thought I'd give it a try as I'm always looking for new places to get quality coffee and good food. 
From the outside it has a hipster grungy feel as it is hidden away down a side street. On the inside it is very trendy, and with 3 rooms to choose from to eat in, it caters for a range of people. It also has a roof top bar if you don't mind the heat. 
The coffee is really good! 
The food is great and affordable. I had the egg upon egg, which filled me up (and I'm a big eater).
The service was exceptional. All the staff were very welcoming, friendly and helpful.

text:
This is a new cafe that opened near my home and we ordered:
Basil Chicken Rice with Egg - they have a spicy and non-spicy version and we opted for a non-spicy as my girl is not sure if she can handle the spice level here. She loved it! I had a mouthful and it's actually pretty good. Good flavours without being overly salty. 

Tom Yum Soup with Tanghoon - I'm happy that its not the instant Tom Yum sauce version. The soup is slightly creamy and tasty. The ingredients is about 3 slices of fish and 3 medium sized prawns. I will order this again. 

Chicken Chop Rice Set - my girl insisted that I try her Rice and chicken Chop although I told her, deep-fried chicken Chop taste the same anywhere. Which it was, it's ok nice. 

We'll come back for the Basil Chicken and Tom Yum for sure!

text:
Best breakfast/brunch restaurant there is!
They have all kinds of breakfast: Spanish with chorizo, the classic English breakfast which comprise of bacon eggs and baked beans, Tunisian breakfast, salmon, and so on. The portion is very filling. I went for English breakfast, which was very good. I will definitely go for Spanish next time!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/pJMNdqkBUdpMIfDgLfk-dg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/nanyang-old-coffee-singapore?reviewid=uc1W3PhyB-iSqkIAwxHmUg&select=pJMNdqkBUdpMIfDgLfk-dg', 'altText': 'Photo of Nanyang Old Coffee - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text:
In a world where everything's moving so fast, and the youth moving on to 'ang moh' coffee la, espresso this and macchiato that, it's nice to know that places like this that serve a mean cuppa good ol' coffee (like the Samsui women used to sip!) still exist.

This is the best out of the old-world cafés (Ya Kun, Wangz, etc) in my opinion. Great toast and kaya, fragrant coffee served in the traditional white cups and saucers, though the Nyonya Nasi Lemak is a huge, huge disappointment (probably one of the factory made, pre-packed variety). The coffee aunties are sweet and nice (just like the coffee - if you like it with condensed milk!), and we might move on to beans from Rwanda and Ecuador, but it's nice to know what kept our country awake and working (and growing to the finesse it is today!) during the 60s! Take a sip of some rich, rich delicious history.

Croissant', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Croissant'}]
text:
Really awesome bakery in a young kinda hipster neighborhood of Singapore... make sure to walk around and check out stores/bookshops/murals!

The croissant was heavenly, but i think my favorite part was the creams and jams available in little pots. I was able to put as much nutella as i wanted on my croissant, which made me quite happy :) Def take advantage!!

I love PS cafe downtown. So when one opened in Tiong Bahru, I was very happy about it. Finally went to check it out with a Friend. Take away menu only. Okieeeeeee ... Then what's with all the nice nice places to sit and the pretty pretty deco? Anyways... 

Was given a seat, given the menu, and was told to go order at the counter. Which is all well and good - a lot of cafes does that. Menu is kinda basic, don't expect a lot to choose from. And after paying, was told that I had to collect my food as well. Okieeeeee... Bear in mind the kind of prices you are paying .... 

Order pizza, a salad, a cuppa coffee and a juice. When I went to collect the food, all were in paper boxes.... But ok, they did say take away only. The salad came in the box and we were suppose to share so I went to ask for another box. I was told that they don't give any more boxes.  was the expression on my face. Went to take two paper cups to use as container to share out the salad. 

Not the most environmentally friendly kinda place. And for the a-bit-above-average-cafe-prices that you are paying, I think it's only right to expect a wee bit more. 

That said, if you are willing to pay that price for take away only, you are in luck, because the food is decent. I liked their pizza but the whole experience really put me off. 

If I wanna go back to a PS cafe, will go to the one downtown.

text: This hawker centre was not as big as the Chinatown one but it still had a good array of options. Lots of seating and pretty clean as well. Remember to get some sugar cane juice. There's so many sugar cane places here and juice places. The most famous stall her would be Tian Tian but unfortunately I came on a day they weren't here so I went to the other store (which has some relation to Tian Tian, you can look up the story) and it very good. But the other stores I tried, were still pretty good.

Interior of PS Cafe', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Interior of PS Cafe'}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/vNc-u90zV0MpUospBq5Muw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/ps-cafe-singapore-8?reviewid=ZKr6A2wphix7JT-eE16mdw&select=vNc-u90zV0MpUospBq5Muw', 'altText': 'Photo of PS.Cafe - Singapore, Singapore. Ribs', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Ribs'}]
text:
Really like this place can't believe I've only just discovered it - have always known it was here, but its so well hidden behind the foliage in Dempsey that you don't really notice it when you drive past - it has a little secret garden feel to it walking up to the place, but once you're inside its high ceilings, lights, cake, laughter - the quiet exterior is completely different from the warm interior. 

Although pricey, it is a lovely place to go for a special night out or a date - and the food is surprisingly good!  The portions are big, and the ribs that I had were drop off the bone fantastic - even better than the ones at Lawry's the Prime Rib! The meat was soooo succulent and easy to take off the bone, and the coleslaw and fried onions that accompanied it were executed just as well.

The fries ($12) are huge, thus explaining the price. You could happily share a plate between 4 people - but it smelt so strongly of bottled truffle oil that it really took the flavour of the fries themselves away. Think it would have been better served salted and with sweet chilli and aioli. 

All in all a very good experience, will be going back again!

text:
The fare at Open Farm Community was wholesome, soulful, exquisite, and quite simply, sustainable clean-eating at its most delicious.

Be sure to make reservations: we didn't think reservations were necessary on a Thursday evening, but boy were we wrong; the restaurant was a full-house, so we were "banished" to the counter seats at the bar.

We had:

1) 'Hail Caesar' ($25): a novel deconstruction of the classic green salad, with romaine lettuce cups cradling tender slabs of smoked chicken, layered with 5J jamon, the thickest ever parmesan crackers, slicked with a light horseradish caesar dressing, and finished with soft-boiled egg confit and garlic croutons. This was well-executed, elegant, incredibly balanced, and the best caesar salad I've ever had. A must-try.

2) Sweet Corn & Basil Soup ($19) chunked up with charred baby corn, caramelised onion strips, and mopped up by fluffy hunks of pita bread - velvety smooth and nuanced.

3) Mud Crab Pappardelle ($29): the sweet flecks of shredded crabmeat complemented the mild Thai curry gravy swirled with coconut milk, dotted with yellow squash, and topped with fried Thai basil leaves. Despite the spice, this was very restrained.

4) 48 Hour Barolo Braised Oxtail Strozzapreti ($26): unabashed and bold, the smoky sweet of the wine highlighted by the heft of the meat, and cut through by fresh thyme and parmesan crisps.

5) Coconut Laksa Barramundi ($29): outstanding as well, the skin of the fish seared to a tantalising crackling, yielding luscious moist flesh underneath. This was sided by an otah-potato cake blend, blanched bok choy and garnished with chilli oil beads that looked like ikura

There are a few times in life when a meal overwhelms your senses with craftsmanship and complexity. This meal is not it. It is middle of the road fare at unreasonable prices. 

Very unremarkable food that certainly could be better prepared in the home kitchen. 

I ordered an $11 banana-blueberry smoothie expecting a taste that justifies the price. Instead, I received a blueberry smoothie without the banana because the kitchen had none in stock. I wasn't even given a choice to decline or change my order, rather it was served to me expecting me to just take it. I did, because I don't like causing a scene, and it was as disappointing as my $13 breakfast sandwich with $5 has brown top up as their dishes don't come with sides. Sad!

Brunch', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Brunch'}]
text:
they have a cool system where you put your name and number into an ipad outside, and they send you an automated call when your table is ready. seems a lot more efficient then a manual wait-list... other places should get on it stat. once you're inside, the place has a wonderful vibe. hispter art deco, random vintage furniture, raw wood, etc etc. music could have been a pitchfork top 100 countdown. 

unfortunately, it was pretty packed, so we were relegated to one of the side tables, with barely any space for our mains. livable, though. the menu was really cool, with nicely drawn art, but the prices, not so much. i just feel like charging ~$20 for brunch can be justified by location, portions or quality of food. since the place was sort of out of the way and we were told that these weren't "sharing-portions" we were really banking on the latter. sadly, our eggs benedict ($20) and eggs sur le plat ($22), while awesome in presentation, were not that good. the eggs benedict was merely ok, but the eggs sur le plat felt like watery tomato sauce with eggs and bits of chorizo. i would have been cool with it if it was like $7 less, but it really wasn't worth it. sad because i really wanted to like this place for all its other elements, but a pretty well-known brunch spot should really be judged on the quality of the food. 

the bright spot was the coffee, which was good.  might come back in the future for coffee + dessert, but will skip the mains.

With all the rave reviews I don't understand just a 4 * rating. For me, anyway, it's 5 all the way. 

Yes the spot is (was - expanded space opening soon) tiny, but that doesn't detract from the quality or experience overall. You're greeted upon entering, served with a smile, and thanked on your way out. Even if the coffee and food wasn't that great it would still be a pleasant experience. But the coffee and food IS great. Limited food menu, but I prefer quality over quantity. 

I get the chicken and mushroom wrap or roast beef sandwich with a coffee and am always pleasantly satisfied - good, reliable, quality. Add a pastry for dessert if you're still hungry. And if there are no seats left, have your coffee to go and take a seat in the climbing gym next door to watch the action. 

I have nothing but praise for this place!

text: So cheap and so good!  The Shanghai was dumplings, tian tian chicken rice and the banana fritter were so good!  The oyster pancake with different seafood was also very good. I'd recommend this place on the weekends when it's less busy although some of the stalls are not open.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/W7ilk4JRA6mFRTdFwIQJoQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/apiary-singapore?reviewid=DOTndIktOeeJp4Z4FKMGvw&select=W7ilk4JRA6mFRTdFwIQJoQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Apiary - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text:
Craving for some dessert after your dinner around outram area? Scout out this gem amongst the shady looking bars along Neil road! 

I love that apiary has many craft flavors and they rotate often. My favorite is definitely black sesame, featured in my post. Not too sweet, just the right amount to end the night. It was pretty funny that the cone was sweeter than black sesame when I tried it another time, so that's probably not a combi you'd want. Other interesting flavors are uji matcha, blue milk, Ferraro roche. 

In general, apiary ice cream is the smooth kind. So if you like more texture in your ice cream, they have very few flavors with nuts and crunch added. 

There are some tables around for you to enjoy your dessert and hang out with friends. Probably enough to fit 15 or so people so it does get a little crowded on weekends. 

Bring your cash or nets. No credit cards accepted here!

Yu Kee is known for its stew sauce recipe, which has been used and improved on for over 60 years. I ordered the Specialty Duck Rice ($3.80) that comes with a plate of brown stewed rice, duck, stewed bean curd and hardboiled egg and a bowl of soup. 

Their rice has been known to be stewed in a special sauce, which turns in brown. It was great because the rice was tasty enough to be eaten alone. The duck meat was tender and very lean. Together with the sauce that it was covered in, it was delightful without an overpowering herbal flavor. This dish is great when eaten with their ikan bilis chili. The soup was flavorful with an herbal taste to it, but it was a tad too salty. 

Overall, the duck rice was enjoyable but slightly salty. In a coffee shop atmosphere, it is also a place that is more suitable more a quick meal.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/hSGyFNVrNLzuFt7qJSh3Fg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/watanabe-coffee-singapore?reviewid=q4EKDQMQ3bGyzZvNNP5bag&select=hSGyFNVrNLzuFt7qJSh3Fg', 'altText': 'Photo of Watanabe Coffee - Singapore, Singapore. From left to right: Cold Matcha Latte,Soy Chai Latte, Syphon Coffee', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'From left to right: Cold Matcha Latte,Soy Chai Latte, Syphon Coffee'}]
text:
A nice, cozy cafe where people can socialize and work. If you are in need of several cups of good coffee, this place is for you! The syphon coffee came in a round flask that served ~3 cups. It was smooth and not too bitter.

The soy chai latte was mediocre--it could have used more spice than sugar water.

The matcha pudding was good but overly too sweet because of the added syrup on top. The coffee paired well with the pudding.

I would recommend the ice matcha latte though! The matcha was not overpowered by the milk and it was just the right amount of sweetness.

If it weren't for the slow service (it took ~20mins for the drinks), this place would have received a 4/5.

Note: Free wifi upon request

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/YTcJb8lKf4P7_7qTQuVCAQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/coftea-marine-parade-market-and-food-centre-singapore?reviewid=Oz2pgclz9CaQRA01NSffeA&select=YTcJb8lKf4P7_7qTQuVCAQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Coftea @ Marine Parade Market and Food Centre - Singapore, Singapore. Coftea + Vegetarian = my fav combination!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Coftea + Vegetarian = my fav combination!'}]
text:
While one might argue that it takes the simple kopi-0 romance of a coffee shop away from a market, Coftea cleverly caters to the young and growing white collar crowd who still want their kopi fix in a genuine setting, while offering the option of flavoured coffee and tea, soy options and more. And what's great about Coftea is that is gives you the same hazlent or vanilla taste that Starbuck of Coffee Bean might offer without the overpriced mass-marketed prices and packaging. 

Enjoy a Hazlenut Coffee for just $1.70 or a straight up Soya Bean Milk for a dollar. It's got that touch of class without diverting too far from the kopitiam scene! 

Also, watch out for frequent arguements between the Coftea lady and the Vegetarian stall uncle right night door. It's a love-hate relationship that's lovely to watch while your enjoying your vanilla coffee or a nice cup of tea. 

They open early and all through lunch so if you're in the area at any time, stop by for some not-so-fancy fancy coffee. Starbucks is across the street but you're far better off here. :)

Lovely little joint - the furniture, lights and even the shell for the espresso machine are custom made, and beauuuuutiful. Gwen handles the shop on her own, from baking to coffee-making to cashiering and dish washing. SALUTE! And she's got a smile on too... Very very impressive. Coffees were pretty good. I preferred the Sumatra Lintong + Colombia blend: fuller body and flavour. And that slice of lemon cream cheese bundt cake was just what I needed this afternoon. Will be looking to come back!

Why I'm only the 2nd reviewer I have no idea. Perhaps everyone already knows about TDC judging by the massive line ups every single bloody day. We come here almost religiously whenever we want a quick healthy warm bite to cover off our protein/veggie/ grain needs. Excellent value especially the ribeye add-on.

A nice place for coffee and eats, that gets super packed.  The space is very modern and cool and...noisy?  With concrete floors and high ceilings, this place does get loud, but it's still a very pleasant space with lots of light, large tables and friendly staff.  I had a very solid latte here, and food also looked quite good and also with some healthier options, although I didn't try any this time.   But as it's close to our church, it's good to know that there is more than just MCD around!

This place has the best location and is a fancy place to get your local fare. Never knew the name but I've walked past this place like since 10 years ago. Tried the Chicken Rice and I must say it's hotel standard. The meat is tender and comes in copious amount. The rice is fragrant and the whole set is displayed in a neat and very appetizing way. The creme bulee was sweet and pretty good too.
The menu is not overwhelmingly difficult to read and there's all your local and Western stuff. I hear the burger is not bad too, but I wanna try the Char Kway Teow and Laksa Lemak the next time I'm here.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/92MU6C5zv-TBD5GFeeEdoQ/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dulcet-and-studio-singapore?reviewid=Dz_iS_dKhcIJ-c203IoLGQ&select=92MU6C5zv-TBD5GFeeEdoQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Dulcet & Studio - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/B7o6NTT8xEG3im9-yvLRTg/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dulcet-and-studio-singapore?reviewid=Dz_iS_dKhcIJ-c203IoLGQ&select=B7o6NTT8xEG3im9-yvLRTg', 'altText': 'Photo of Dulcet & Studio - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/XnI39JsJsjOb5JOzgq-Zyg/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dulcet-and-studio-singapore?reviewid=Dz_iS_dKhcIJ-c203IoLGQ&select=XnI39JsJsjOb5JOzgq-Zyg', 'altText': 'Photo of Dulcet & Studio - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}]
text:
This is a relatively new set up lifestyle cafe by the folks @ Tampopo.  

Most of the hot favorite desserts like creme puff, different flavored milk pudding and cheesecakes @ the Tampopo restaurants can be found here.  They don't sell just desserts here, they do sell western/japanese food for lunch and dinner. The other of my all time favorite is their handmade warabi mochi. It is done just nice with the right amount of sweetness. It is soft yet chewy.

We loved the milk pudding so much that we often have it takeaway and slowly enjoy it at home.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/BiFub_obyIr_67Z7-KgN7Q/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/oberstrasse-singapore?reviewid=IedsznUM-98Cs9mNaT8zwg&select=BiFub_obyIr_67Z7-KgN7Q', 'altText': 'Photo of Oberstrasse - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/VwH5BDF5HlcSecBkJss5uw/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/oberstrasse-singapore?reviewid=IedsznUM-98Cs9mNaT8zwg&select=VwH5BDF5HlcSecBkJss5uw', 'altText': 'Photo of Oberstrasse - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/y9bNd747M_wbCPMFmC88Ew/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/oberstrasse-singapore?reviewid=IedsznUM-98Cs9mNaT8zwg&select=y9bNd747M_wbCPMFmC88Ew', 'altText': 'Photo of Oberstrasse - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/8QuWkBgsFDSwNFO8cTFGzQ/180s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/oberstrasse-singapore?reviewid=IedsznUM-98Cs9mNaT8zwg&select=8QuWkBgsFDSwNFO8cTFGzQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Oberstrasse - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': None}]
text:
Oberstrasse is a German term for Upper Street and is commonly used in Germany. The cafe is just a stone throw away from Lavendar MRT Station. It's quite a popular place for some breakfast and brunch. It was a last minute idea that we came here for a meal, but for a dinner.

Interior feels cosy under the orange lights. In fact the theme of using transparent containers with the bulbs in them gave the environment a rustic feel altogether with the wooden tables and chair.

I bet everyone hear about their Rosti and comes here for this! The homemade potato rosti was awesome accompanied by a pretty sunny side up egg, wedge of lemon and a spat of sour cream. The Rosti was pan-fried to crisp at some parts and texture was perfect without being too burnt. If I were to compare Rosti from Marche, both as are tasty, just that the differences is that Oberstrasee Rosti are more of wider and shorter while Marche's were machined cut thus the size of it is uniform.

Sunny Rosti - $11

Sandwichies are served in freshly baked Ciabatta with Smoked Cheddar, Coral lettuces, Tomatoes and Onions. It consist of Norwegian smoked salmon, Avocado spread, horseradish dill sauce and alfalfa sprouts.

Smokled Salmon & Avocado - $12

I had the Duck Confit as my main course that come with 2 sides and I had the homemade slaw as well as the House Salad. The color combination of this course looked pleasing to the eyes with purple slaw and Salad drenched with roasted sesame dressing. On the other hand the Duck Confit was deep fried, though it was a tad on the dry side, it was well complimented by the Lingonberry Sauce that elevated the dining experience of the dish.

Duck Config with Lingonberry Sauce - $18

It was quite quiet during the night and perhaps many would come for their brunch or breakfast. Service was friendly and prompt. The only down side I would have think of is perhaps the smell on the clothing after dining. I don't mind returning for sausage and rosti.

text: There are many awesome bakeries and cafes in Tiong Bahru but none are as packed as this one. This is both the upside and downside of this local bakery - the constant line and flow of people means they are always putting out fresh goodies and pastries and even the displayed cakes aren't laying around for long. On the downside, it is rather difficult to find a place to sit especially on the weekends and lunch time. With that said, Tiong Bahru bakery is worth a visit as they have many original pastries, cakes and even savory treats, including one of my favorites the squid ink bun. When I lived in Tiong Bahru and even now, it is one of my favorite breakfast cafes.

text:
I happen to be in the Orchard area on a Monday morning and my first thought was "Cheese Tart for Breakfast!"  BAKE opens at 10am and I arrived less than 10 minutes before opening.  No one was at the queue, so I roamed to the store front to check things out.  The tarts are baking in the oven and one of the staff waved at me to ask me to queue.  When I got to the queue, there were three ladies waiting.  5 more minutes until opening and about 15 more people are in queue.  A staff came out to the queue right at 10am sharp to hand out confirmation cards to the first two people.  10:03am and it was my turn!  The staff looked at my baby and I and asked how many I was getting. When I said a dozen, she was like "oh, only 12, ok, here is your card" as if she was expecting me to buy more with a baby in tow. Thank you for acknowledging my baby as a person!  The cashier was very friendly and informed me that the tarts can be refrigerated up to 4 days, or kept frozen for up to one month! Don't microwave.  Reheat in toaster, oven or air fryer at 200C for 30 seconds to a minute.  Got it!  Out the door we go to try these babies.  By now my 20 month old is screaming "Chee taat Chee taat."  I carefully peeled the sticker off to open the box.  I really appreciate BAKE's thoughtfulness in designing their boxes.  Each tart has it own "compartment" so they don't bump into each other and become mush.  First bite into the freshly baked tart is the crunchy crust that snaps off, then comes the warm fluffy, light and whipped cream like cheese filing that's has a hint of tartness.  The contrast of the crunchy shell and of fluffy cheese filling is heavenly.  I slurped the cheese filling down like one would with whipped cream, and finished off the crunchy crust with the next few bites.  15 mins late, after I settled by baby down for a drink, the cheese tart shells are getting softer and losing its crunchiness.  Now it has become more of a soft cookie texture.  When I got home, put some in the fridge, and a couple in the freezer to try the different ways of eating these babies.  The refrigerated ones tasted just ok.  It's sort of like an over beaten cheesecake, nothing like ice cream.  While the filing is soft, it has a lot of air bubbles, so it's not creamy.  The frozen ones were more like frozen cheesecake, hard and crumbly.   Hubby and my children tried it and no one care for the frozen ones.  

So my conclusion is that the BAKE cheese tarts are best eaten right after you buy them.  Enjoy the contrast of crunchy cookie shell and the fluffy whipped filling.  

Are they worth 1-3 hr wait? Nope!  If I need a cheese tart fix, the bakery across has lava cheese tarts, while not as fluffy and whipped cream like, those were creamier, cheaper, and no queue.

text:
I don't think this serves the best Eggs Benedict in Singapore. But to be fair, one man's meat is another's poison. 

I tried both the Eggs Benedict and Eggs Royal. The Benedict did not impress me. The hollandaise sauce is so so only. The Royal is another story. The smoked salmon is nice when eaten with the bread and eggs, but too salty on its own. My photo of Eggs Benedict was labelled wrongly.

We sat by the side and the sun was glaring into our eyes at 8.30 am. There's no offer to pull the day curtains to block the sun rays.

We took away a quarter loaf of poilane bread. I bought it before from a shop in Dempsey Hill, was surprised they have it here too, but comes already sliced. After trying out the poilane bread, I noticed that it is not as fresh as the one I bought from Dempsey Hill.

The sourdough bread is... what can I say? My search for true sourdough bread in Singapore continues.

text:
The new concept cafe on the block is called Ogopogo, refering to a mythical "caffiend" monster that lives in the pipes that run along the walls of the whole interior. Cute little place that's an undiscovered gem.. For now.

It's kind of funky and retro at the same time. Tv sets, tin carriers and other old school paraphernalia sets the mood. The mad mix of mismatching chairs also adds to the charm of the place. 

Come here for the coffee! Using beans from Toby's estate, the coffee is well balanced and easy to drink, and does not even require sugar!

Other than coffee, thy also have chai lattes, craft beers and ciders available all day. Check out the Japanese Hitachino Nest flavours - the one that caught my eye was the espresso stout! Definitely an interesting taste to it! :)

Lovely desserts and cakes here, ad I really enjoyed the cookies and the mango passion fruit cake there too. It went perfectly with my coffee!

Because its so new, they haven't really gotten a full menu set up yet. However they have partnered up with other nearby restaurants, so you can go there and enjoy a variety of cuisines such as Italian and middle eastern! But that's for another review.

Lastly, there's a cute little outdoor area one can smoke shisha in. Really loved the entire feel and ambience of the place, and the friendly, attentive staff on duty there.

Am keen to see what else Ogopogo comes up with! I'll definitely be back! I've also just found out that if u call in advance, they will prepare your order and run out for a drive by takeaway! Perfect for those on the go, especially since parking can be a little tricky around that area!

And I love the fact that the name is a palindrome. Make sure you check out their handwritten exercise book menus - they're super cute and fun!

text:
I really wanted to like this place. I really did. Cos the guy running it is really nice. Very warm and all round nice guy. 
Decor is welcoming and not so hipster it makes your teeth ache. The vibe is cosy and relaxed. 
We sat down and ordered breakfast. We were the only ones in the cafe. 
Dude running the place recommended the breakfast set - $12 for coffee and kaya toast with scrambled eggs. Sounded good so I ordered that. The BF went for hot dog. 
So we waited. And waited. 
6 mins later the coffee came. 
We waited and waited. 
Dude went out to chat with cabbie friend. 
20 minutes later, my kaya toast came. 2 slices of mass produced bread. Scant kaya on one slice. Scrambled eggs was fluffy and moist. But I can make this at home with better toast and more kaya. 
The hot dog took another 10 minutes. Probably cos he had to chop cabbage for the salad. 
Verdict : coffee is ok but the food is overpriced and meh. 
Can hang out for coffee. But the area has better food elsewhere. Sleepy neighbourhood joint is fine and good but this is too sleepy for my taste.

text:
I was lucky to have my cousin queue for me once so I didn't have to. Tried one of the tarts right away and instantly fell in love with it! I'm usually not a fan of something related to cheese but this is stupendous. Literally the only kind of tart I'd eat again and again in my life. It's just soooo goooood.

The tarts are really yummy but the price is a bit on a high side (@$3.5) but I guess that's fine considering the tarts are flown in from Hokkaido and the rental in Ion.
Now that I have tried, I really love it and crave it every moment but I wouldn't queue more than 15 minutes. I'll repurchase IF I was in the area, and no sign of long queue.

Love the feel of this place and the food is great - although that might be a personal taste. If you like organic feeling food with veg, grains and nuts, you will enjoy the food. The coffee and tea is a definite yes though.

Nice menu spread, although on the pricey side. The whole place smells of truffle oil, which could be good or bad depending on your taste. Needless to say, truffle fries are a popular order here. 

Free wi-fi takes a while to connect, but it's pretty speedy once you're on at 3mbps down/1.5 mbps up. There are only a couple outlets here and there, so you have to snag them quick, or come with fully charged devices. Nice alternative music to get you in the productive or daydreamy mood. 

There's several different interesting teas and coffees as well as all sorts of dishes. I hear the buckwheat pancakes and the fried chicken are pretty bomb, but have yet to try them myself.

text:
Reasonable pricing and pretty decent portions. Nice new addition amongst the coffee shops and hawker Centre. Bold venture in my opinion. 
They bring in a small range of tiong Bahru bakery's bread and have their own cakes. Their coffee menu is also pretty standard with reasonable price and size, great for the office crowd nearby who wants an upgrade from the local kopi. 
Had the ratatouille pasta, a vegetarian pasta with squash, cherry tomatoes  and a veggie stock base   The pasta was surprisingly quite good! 
Liked their raspberry cheesecake too 

The coffee is also decently made with a decent size 

I see myself coming back to try the rest of the menu!

Spize is the perfect post clubbing spot. I know my fellow reviewers say that its the perfect post-Zouk clubbing spot, but honestly, I know for a fact that revellers from Mink and Butter come to this perennial popular supper spot for food too. Food wise, Spize has an extensive menu. It serves local classics like prata and roti john. Portions are pretty sizeable - which might not be the best idea if you're going directly to bed after this, but it sure helps in soaking up alcohol. Some drawbacks to Spize though are its spotty service, and the non-existent parking available. But considering the location, I think you'll be hard pressed to do better.

text:
I visited for brunch on a Saturday morning. The place wasn't full which was great, if you're looking for a place where you can have a conversation without shouting. At one side of the restaurant, there are couches that were perfect for relaxing with a good book. And books there were aplenty for you to browse with. 

The service staff were friendly and eager to please. 

Unfortunately, the food though decent, isn't good enough for me to specially return for it. I had the eggs blackstone (English muffin, spinach, tomatoes, eggs, rosti) and a flat white. The coffee was better than I expected - low in acidity. I was excited about the apple pie based on previous reviews, but it didn't live up to the hype. I prefer a harder crust; the filling had just the right hint of tartness and sweetness. My friend really enjoyed his chicken sandwich which he ordered based on the recommendation of another reviewer. 

It's a nice place to hang out with friends but if you're a picky eater, it may not live up to your expectations. 

Free wifi available. Toilet is very clean and orderly.

text:
Second time in a month I'm here at their Capitol outlet. I like this outlet as its not too crowded and this time I get to sit near the fountain. 

Food is good here. This time I had the Chicken Mushroom Pie Pizza and an Ice Coffee. Their ice coffee is served in a high thermal conductivity copper cup to sustain the coldness. My partner had the Omelette Risotto. 

I will definitely recommend this place.
Get coffee from here very often. They make decent coffee consistently which is a great thing.

text:
Ordered the pancake Apple crumble. It is sweet and tasty. Cost $12. Filled with Apple crumble. I really like it a lot. The texture of the pancake is soft too. Yummy ! My friend ordered housemade English breakfast. Cost $16.50
It looks yummy and smells good too. She ordered the Cold Brew and I ordered the Chamomile tea. Total bill cost $44.95 with gst. This cafe have a outdoor seating on the 3rd floor. 2nd floor have a two seat designed as a swing facing the window. But the spaces are limited. The ambience is nice. Thumbs up!

text:
Yes, yes, and more yes!  Simplest breakfast foods ever, but SO GOOD that I had it twice during my stay in Singapore.  Kaya Toast, soft boiled eggs, and soy milk with grass jelly cost no more than ~5 SGD!!!  Walk up to the counter, order, pay, sit down, and out comes to the food.  Nothing fancy, just plain and simple.

This place is an institution and has a lot of history to it.  Great to visit and to try especially how cheap it is.  This one is also the original in Singapore, so def visit.  Consider also getting a jar of the kaya spread.  You can even try to make it yourself at home.  I did.  *___*

text:
Loved the slick deco design and atmosphere. It's buzzy for weekend brunch. Priced relatively high but you get quite a bit of bang for your buck spread around all the different items in a dish. The Turkish breakfast was the standout because of the egg wrapped in strands of filo and fried -- amazing looking! I was pleasantly surprised by the number of veg breakfast options. 

Service was a little slow and haphazard at times -- par for the course. The staff, however, is charming through the gaffes.

Why am I giving this place 5 stars? While many may say that the toast or the eggs are not very special or that the food is expensive but one of the biggest draws for me is the convenience of the drinks to go. They are pretty efficient with the dual counters and dual queue system which enables the crazy, hungry and thirsty crowd at Raffles Place to get their drinks to go.

The other big plus for me is that the cashier has somehow identified me as a regular and remember what my usual order is (I tend to buy large amounts of honey lemon drinks to go) and she is ever cheerful and helpful, sometimes giving me good recommendation for new drinks I'd like to try.

The honey lemon here comes with 2 slices of lemon and a very generous amount of honey to sweeten things up. I wouldn't say they use great honey but when you do try to press the lemons farther before drinking, the sourness from the lemon slices and the sweetness from the honey comes to a nice balance.

As a few others pointed out, if price is an issue, do go to Golden Shoe for better priced drinks and food. But the service here plus the convenience and pretty good speed of fulfilling their orders would keep the crowds coming.

As a side note, they do have a main competitor Teahut which also makes excellent honey lemon, but they tend to be a little generous with their honey and lemons.

text:
wholesome, chichi, yummy-mummy-abound buffet of antipasti and salads at this cafe in the rather-tough-to-get-to shangri-la hotel (they serve up some fantastic mains too). I have finally made my way to this place, and it couldn't be sooner - the food is light and clean (on the palate; hygiene here taken for granted) and varied in both flavor and color, and there's a relaxing vibe to this place that lends itself to lazy weekend brunches.

great service too, and reasonable prices given the quality and type of food served - it's worth the drive/ trek.

shangri-la is one of those chains that's sort of familiar and posh without trying too hard - and it always has this languid vibe about it that's rather reflected in this restaurant - filled with lunching ladies in flowing dresses, set by the pool side.

the mostly mediterranean-styled food is laid out on a long, gorgeous wooden table - 
many different flavors and all well-balanced-and-seasoned - but it's a light flavor profile that seems much better suited to women. but to bulk things up, the lunch sets also offer the option of an additional set course - anything from fish to beef.

my main courseof  fish was properly seared - the skin was suitably crispy, the meat flaky, and the little salad on the side of baby carrot and corn was plenty tasty.

but you don't need the main course - we were just being greedy - the salads are pretty much sufficient for a satisfying, sating weekend lunch, without any of that usual heft that necessitates a post-meal siesta (though you can still take one, if you're so inclined). delicious food - tastes and feels almost like you're in a leisurely holiday town - well worth the almost unbelievably reasonable price for lunch.

This is by far one of the most interesting places I've seen in Singapore... Set up to look like a library, The Reading Room has a varied selection of books to read (and to purchase) while being a full functioning café. I only went for afternoon drinks and was delightfully surprised by very nice happy hour offerings, on glasses of red and white wine as well as on beers, and other drinks. It did look like it had a nice brunch menu, and their burger offerings for dinner looked quite nice. At around 6:30 PM however, they shut off most of the lights, which I think was a real mood killer. No need to have lighting resembling that of a sketchy club, when you are in a nice café where people want to go to talk each other, and in fact, see each other too.

text:
This is one quaint cafe tucked in the middle of Serangoon Gardens. My friend, who lives nearby, often comes here for his coffee fix. Really limited seating and even slightly cramped but I guess it adds to the charm of the place.

We shared the waffles with a scoop of cheesecake ice cream and my friend has a latte as well. The waffles were slightly too small for my liking though their soft texture is a matter of personal preference. The latte was nothing to shout about but it isn't terrible either.

The place is a nice option for a cafe chillout for folks around the area.

text: If u want to find dempsey's worst service come to jones the grocer. The truffle fries and coffee are amazing, but I can't believe I'm paying $5 service tax for TRASH service. I wasn't even directed to my table and had to wait there forever. Infact I'm still sitting here waiting for them to collect my bill. I am so done with the horrible service here. Update: they made me WALK to the cashier and wait in line to pay. Jones the grocer needs to ask siri what service is because they're all tax no talk. If I wanted to stand in line to pay I would be at McDonald's where I get my money's worth of service charges, which is by the way $0.
